{"title_page": "John Kourkouas", "text_new": "{{about|the 10th-century general|his 9th-century grandfather|John Kourkouas (9th century)|the 11th-century governor of Italy|John Kourkouas (catepan)}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          =John Kourkouas\n| birth_date          = before 900\n| death_date          = after 946\n| allegiance    = [[Byzantine Empire]]\n| serviceyears  = {{circa|915}}\u2013944\n| rank          = [[Domestic of the Schools]]\n| relations     = [[Theophilos Kourkouas]], [[Romanos Kourkouas]], [[John Tzimiskes]]\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Byzantine-Arab Wars}}\n'''John Kourkouas''' ({{lang-gr|\u1f38\u03c9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03b1\u03c2|Ioannes Kourkouas}}, {{fl.|{{circa|915}}\u2013946}}), also transliterated as '''Kurkuas''' or '''Curcuas''',{{cref|a}} was one of the most important generals of the [[Byzantine Empire]]. His success in battles against the [[Caliphate|Muslim states]] in the East definitively reversed the course of the centuries-long [[Byzantine\u2013Arab Wars]] and began Byzantium's 10th century \"Age of Conquest\".\n\nKourkouas belonged to a family of [[Armenians|Armenian]] descent that produced several notable Byzantine generals. As commander of an imperial bodyguard regiment, Kourkouas was among the chief supporters of [[Byzantine emperor|Emperor]] [[Romanos I Lekapenos]] ({{reign|920|944}}) and facilitated the latter's rise to the throne. In 923, Kourkouas was appointed commander-in-chief of the Byzantine armies along the eastern frontier, facing the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] and the semi-autonomous Muslim border emirates. He kept this post for more than twenty years, overseeing decisive Byzantine military successes that altered the strategic balance in the region.\n\nDuring the 9th century, Byzantium had gradually recovered its strength and internal stability while the Caliphate had become increasingly impotent and fractured. Under Kourkouas's leadership, the Byzantine armies advanced deep into Muslim territory for the first time in almost 200 years, expanding the imperial border. The emirates of [[Melitene]] and [[Erzurum|Qaliqala]] were conquered, extending Byzantine control to the upper [[Euphrates]] and over [[western Armenia]]. The remaining [[Caucasian Iberia|Iberian]] and Armenian princes became Byzantine vassals. Kourkouas also played a role in the defeat of a major [[Rus' (people)|Rus']] raid in 941 and recovered the ''[[Mandylion]]'' of [[Edessa, Mesopotamia|Edessa]], an important and holy [[relic]] believed to depict the face of [[Jesus Christ]]. He was dismissed in 944 as a result of the machinations of Romanos Lekapenos's sons but restored to favour by Emperor [[Constantine VII]] ({{reign|913|959}}), serving as imperial ambassador in 946. His subsequent fate is unknown.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and career===\nJohn was a [[kinship|scion]] of the Armenian [[Kourkouas]] family&mdash;a [[Hellenization|Hellenized]] form of their original surname, Gurgen (Armenian: \u0533\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0563\u0565\u0576) &mdash;which had risen to prominence in Byzantine service in the 9th century and established itself as one of the great families of the [[Anatolia]]n land-holding military aristocracy (the so-called \"''[[dynatoi]]''\").<ref>{{harvnb|ODB|loc=\"Kourkouas\" (A. Kazhdan), pp. 1156\u20131157}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|pp=337\u2013338}}.</ref> John's [[John Kourkouas (9th century)|namesake grandfather]] had been a commander of the elite ''[[Hikanatoi]]'' regiment (''[[tagma (military)|tagma]]'') under Emperor [[Basil I]] ({{reign|867|886}}); John's brother [[Theophilos Kourkouas|Theophilos]] became a senior general, as did John's own son, [[Romanos Kourkouas|Romanos]], and his great-nephew, [[John Tzimiskes]].<ref name=\"ODB\">{{harvnb|ODB|loc=\"Kourkouas, John\" (A. Kazhdan), p. 1157}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Guilland|1967|pp=442\u2013443, 446, 463, 571}}.</ref>\n\n[[File:Romanus I with Christopher, solidus.jpg|thumb|left|250px|alt=Obverse (right) and reverse (left) view of gold coin. On the obverse, Christ seated on throne. On the reverse, two crowned men, one bearded and one not, holding a patriarchal cross on a staff between them.|Gold coin (''[[solidus (coin)|solidus]]'') of Romanos I Lekapenos, depicting him and his eldest son (and co-emperor from 921 on), [[Christopher Lekapenos|Christopher]].]]\n\nLittle is known about John's early life. His father was a wealthy official in the imperial palace. John himself was born at Dokeia (now [[Tokat]]), in the region of Darbidos in the [[Armeniac Theme]], and was educated by one of his relatives, the bishop of [[Gangra]] Christopher.<ref>{{harvnb|Guilland|1967|pp=443, 571}}.</ref> In the late regency of Empress [[Zoe Karbonopsina]] (914\u2013919) for her infant son [[Constantine VII]] ({{reign|913|959}}), Kourkouas was appointed as the commander of the ''[[Vigla (tagma)|Vigla]]'' palace guard regiment, probably through the machinations of the fellow Armenian, admiral [[Romanos Lekapenos]], as part of his drive for the throne. In this capacity, he arrested several high officials who opposed Lekapenos's rise to power, opening the road to the appointment of Lekapenos as regent in place of Zoe in 919. Lekapenos gradually assumed more powers until he was crowned senior emperor in December 920.<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=58\u201362}}; {{harvnb|Guilland|1967|p=571}}.</ref> As a reward for his support, in {{Circa|923}}, Romanos Lekapenos promoted Kourkouas to the post of [[Domestic of the Schools]], in effect commander-in-chief of all the imperial armies in Anatolia.<ref name=\"ODB\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=69}}.</ref> According to the chronicle of [[Theophanes Continuatus]], Kourkouas held this post for an unparalleled continuous term of 22&nbsp;years and seven months.<ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=418}}; {{harvnb|Guilland|1967|pp=447, 571}}.</ref>\n\nAt this time, and following the disastrous [[Battle of Acheloos]] in 917, the Byzantines were mostly occupied in the Balkans in a [[Byzantine\u2013Bulgarian war of 913\u2013927|protracted conflict]] against [[First Bulgarian Empire|Bulgaria]].<ref name=\"Whittow317\">{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=317}}.</ref> Hence, Kourkouas's first task as Domestic of the East was the suppression of the revolt of [[Bardas Boilas]], the governor (''[[strategos]]'') of [[Chaldia]], a strategically important area on the Empire's northeastern Anatolian frontier. This was quickly achieved and his brother, Theophilos Kourkouas, replaced Boilas as governor of Chaldia. As commander of this northernmost sector of the eastern frontier, Theophilos proved a competent soldier and gave valuable assistance to his brother's campaigns.<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=70\u201371, 135}}; {{harvnb|Guilland|1967|pp=442\u2013443, 571\u2013572}}.</ref>\n\n===First submission of Melitene, campaigns into Armenia===\nFollowing the [[Muslim conquests]] of the 7th century, the [[Arab\u2013Byzantine Wars|Arab\u2013Byzantine conflict]] had featured constant raids and counter-raids along a relatively static border roughly defined by the line of the [[Taurus Mountains|Taurus]] and [[Anti-Taurus Mountains]].<ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|pp=176\u2013178}}.</ref> Until the 860s, superior Muslim armies had placed the Byzantines on the defensive. Only after 863, with the victory in the [[Battle of Lalakaon]], did the Byzantines gradually regain some lost ground against the Muslims, launching ever-deeper raids into [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]] and [[Upper Mesopotamia]] and annexing the [[Paulicians|Paulician]] state around Tephrike (now [[Divri\u011fi]]).<ref>{{harvnb|El-Cheikh|2004|p=162}}; {{harvnb|Whittow|1996|pp=311\u2013314}}.</ref> Furthermore, according to historian Mark Whittow, \"by 912 the Arabs had been pinned back behind the Taurus and Anti-Taurus\", encouraging the Armenians to switch their allegiance from the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] to the Empire, in whose service they entered in increasing numbers.<ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=315}}.</ref> The revival of Byzantine power was further facilitated by the progressive decline of the Abbasid Caliphate itself, particularly under [[al-Muqtadir]] ({{reign|908|932}}), when the central government faced several revolts. In the periphery of the Caliphate, the weakening of central control allowed the emergence of semi-autonomous local dynasties.<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=136\u2013137}}.</ref> In addition, after the death of the Bulgarian Tsar [[Simeon I of Bulgaria|Simeon]] in 927, a peace treaty with the Bulgarians allowed the Empire to shift attention and resources to the East.<ref name=\"Whittow317\"/>\n\nBy 925, Romanos Lekapenos felt himself strong enough to demand the payment of tribute from the Muslim cities on the western side of the [[Euphrates]]. When they refused, in 926, Kourkouas led the army across the border.<ref name=\"Runciman137\">{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=137}}.</ref> Aided by his brother Theophilos and an Armenian contingent under the ''strategos'' of [[Lykandos]], Mleh ([[Melias]] in Greek sources),<ref name=\"Treadgold479\">{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|p=479}}.</ref> Kourkouas targeted Melitene (modern [[Malatya]]), the center of an emirate which had long been a thorn in Byzantium's side.<ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=310}}; {{harvnb|Treadgold|1998|p=111}}.</ref> The Byzantine army successfully stormed the lower city, and although the citadel held out, Kourkouas concluded a treaty by which the emir accepted tributary status.<ref name=\"Runciman137\"/><ref name=\"Treadgold479\"/>\n\n[[File:Caucasus, 884-962.gif|thumb|right|250px|alt=Map of the southern Caucasus and the area of eastern Turkey and northern Iraq and Syria. Greater Armenia in the center with minor Caucasian principalities to its northeast, the Byzantines to the west and the Abbasid caliphate to the south and east.|Map of Armenia and the Caucasian states in the mid-10th century.]]\n\nIn 927\u2013928, Kourkouas launched a large raid into Arab-controlled [[Bagratuni Kingdom of Armenia|Armenia]]. After taking Samosata (modern [[Samsat]]), an important stronghold on the Euphrates, the Byzantines advanced as far as the Armenian capital of [[Dvin (ancient city)|Dvin]].<ref name=\"Treadgold479\"/> An Arab counter-offensive forced them out of Samosata after only a few days, and Dvin, which was defended by the [[Sajids|Sajid]] general Nasr al-Subuki, successfully withstood the Byzantine siege, until the mounting losses forced the Byzantines to abandon it.<ref>{{harvnb|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=77}}.</ref> At the same time, [[Thamal al-Dulafi|Thamal]], the emir of Tarsus, conducted successful raids into southern Anatolia and neutralized [[Ibn al-Dahhak]], a local [[Kurds|Kurdish]] leader who supported the Byzantines.<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=138}}.</ref> The Byzantines then turned toward the [[Kaysites|Kaysite]] emirate in the region of [[Lake Van]] in southern Armenia. Kourkouas's troops plundered the region and took the towns of [[Ahlat|Khliat]] and [[Bitlis]], where they are said to have replaced the [[mosque]]'s ''[[minbar]]'' with a cross. The local Arabs appealed to the Caliph for aid in vain, prompting an exodus of Muslims from the region.<ref name=\"TG82\">{{harvnb|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=82}}.</ref><ref name=\"Treadgold480\">{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|p=480}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=138\u2013139}}.</ref> This incursion, more than {{convert|500|km}} from the nearest imperial territory, was a far cry from the defensive-minded strategy Byzantium had followed during the previous centuries and highlighted the new capabilities of the imperial army.<ref name=\"Whittow317\"/> Nevertheless, famine in Anatolia and the exigencies of parallel campaigns in [[Catepanate of Italy|southern Italy]] weakened Kourkouas's forces. His army was defeated and driven back by [[Muflih al-Saji|Muflih]], a former Sajid ''[[Ghulam (slave soldier)|ghulam]]'' and governor of [[Adharbayjan]].<ref name=\"TG82\"/><ref name=\"Treadgold480\"/><ref name=\"Runciman139\">{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=139}}.</ref>\n\nIn 930, Melias's attack on Samosata was heavily defeated; among other prominent officers, one of his sons was captured and sent to [[Baghdad]].<ref name=\"Runciman139\"/> Later in the same year, John and his brother Theophilos besieged Theodosiopolis (modern [[Erzurum]]), the capital of the emirate of Qaliqala.<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=139\u2013140}}.</ref> The campaign was complicated by the machinations of their ostensible allies, the [[Caucasian Iberia|Iberian]] rulers of [[Tao-Klarjeti]]. Resenting the extension of direct Byzantine control adjacent to their own borders, the Iberians had already provided supplies to the besieged city. Once the city was invested, they vociferously demanded that the Byzantines hand over several captured towns, but when one of them, the fort of Mastaton, was surrendered, the Iberians promptly returned it to the Arabs. As Kourkouas needed to keep the Iberians placated and was aware that his conduct was being carefully observed by the Armenian princes, he did not react to this affront.<ref name=\"Runciman140\">{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=140}}.</ref> After seven months of siege, Theodosiopolis fell in spring 931 and was transformed into a tributary vassal, while, according to Constantine VII's ''[[De Administrando Imperio]]'', all territory north of the river [[Araxes]] was given to the Iberian king [[David II of Iberia|David II]]. As in Melitene, the maintenance of Byzantine control over Theodosiopolis proved difficult and the population remained restive. In 939, it revolted and drove out the Byzantines, and Theophilos Kourkouas could not finally subdue the city until 949. It was then fully incorporated into the Empire and its Muslim population was expelled and replaced by Greek and Armenian settlers.<ref name=\"Runciman140\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=322}}; {{harvnb|Holmes|2005|p=314}}.</ref>\n\n===Final capture of Melitene===\nFollowing the death of Emir [[Abu Hafs ibn Amr|Abu Hafs]], Melitene renounced its Byzantine allegiance.<ref name=\"Runciman137\"/> After attempts to take the city by storm or subterfuge failed, the Byzantines established a ring of fortresses on the hills around the plain of Melitene, and methodically ravaged the area.<ref name=\"Whittow317\"/> By early 931, the inhabitants of Melitene were forced to come to terms: they agreed to tributary status and even undertook to provide a military contingent to campaign alongside the Byzantines.<ref name=\"Whittow317\"/>\n\nThe other Muslim states were not idle, however: in March, the Byzantines were hit by three successive raids in Anatolia, organized by the Abbasid commander [[Mu'nis al-Muzaffar]], while in August, a large raid led by Thamal of Tarsus penetrated as far as [[Ancyra]] and [[Amorium]] and returned with prisoners worth 136,000&nbsp;[[gold dinar]]s.<ref name=\"Runciman141\">{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=141}}.</ref> During this time, the Byzantines were engaged in southern Armenia, aiding the ruler of [[Vaspurakan Kingdom|Vaspurakan]], [[Gagik I of Vaspurakan|Gagik I]], who had rallied the local Armenian princes and allied himself with the Byzantines against the emir of Adharbayjan. There they raided the Kaysite emirate and razed Khliat and [[Berkri]] to the ground, before marching into Mesopotamia and capturing Samosata again. Gagik was unable to take advantage of this and capture Kaysite territory, however, as Muflih immediately raided his domains in retaliation.<ref name=\"TG82\"/><ref name=\"Runciman141\"/><ref name=\"Jenkins246\">{{harvnb|Jenkins|1987|p=246}}.</ref> At this point, the Melitenians called upon the [[Hamdanid]] rulers of [[Mosul]] for help. In response, the Hamdanid prince [[Sa'id ibn Hamdan]] attacked the Byzantines and drove them back: Samosata was abandoned, and in November 931, the Byzantine garrison withdrew from Melitene as well.<ref name=\"Runciman141\"/><ref name=\"Treadgold481\">{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|p=481}}.</ref> Sa'id was, however, unable to remain in the area or to leave a sufficient garrison; once he left for Mosul, the Byzantines returned and resumed both the blockade of Melitene and their scorched-earth tactics.<ref name=\"Whittow317\"/>\n\n[[File:Melitene by the Byzantines in 934 from the Chronicle of John Skylitzes.jpg|thumb|left|250px|alt=Medieval miniature depicting a city being stormed. To the left is the Byzantine army, with shields and spears, with the tents of their camp to their back. They are scaling ladders onto the walls of a city (right), whose defenders try to fight them off from their top.|The fall of Melitene, miniature from the ''[[Skylitzes Chronicle]]''.]]\n\nThe sources record no major Byzantine external campaigns for 932, as the Empire was preoccupied with two revolts in the [[Opsician Theme]].<ref name=\"Treadgold481\"/> In 933, Kourkouas renewed the attack against Melitene. Mu'nis al-Muzaffar sent forces to assist the beleaguered city, but in the resulting skirmishes, the Byzantines prevailed and took many prisoners and the Arab army returned home without relieving the city.<ref name=\"Runciman141\"/><ref name=\"Treadgold481\"/> In early 934, at the head of 50,000&nbsp;men, Kourkouas again crossed the frontier and marched toward Melitene. The other Muslim states offered no help, preoccupied as they were with the turmoil following Caliph [[al-Qahir]]'s deposition. Kourkouas again took Samosata and besieged Melitene.<ref name=\"Runciman141\"/><ref name=\"Treadgold481\"/> Many of the city's inhabitants had abandoned it at the news of Kourkouas's approach and hunger eventually compelled the rest to surrender on 19 May 934. Wary of the city's previous rebellions, Kourkouas only allowed those inhabitants to remain who were Christians or agreed to convert to Christianity. Most did so, and he ordered the remainder expelled.<ref name=\"Whittow317\"/><ref name=\"Treadgold481\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=141\u2013142}}.</ref> Melitene was fully incorporated into the empire, and most of its fertile land was transformed into an imperial estate (''kouratoreia''). This was an unusual move, implemented by Romanos I to prevent the powerful Anatolian landed aristocracy from taking control of the province. It also served to increase direct imperial presence and control on the crucial new borderlands.<ref name=\"Treadgold481\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|pp=341\u2013342}}.</ref>\n\n===Rise of the Hamdanids===\nThe fall of Melitene profoundly shocked the Muslim world: for the first time, a major Muslim city had fallen and been incorporated into the Byzantine Empire.<ref name=\"Runciman142\">{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=142}}.</ref> Kourkouas followed this success by subduing parts of the district of Samosata in 936 and razing the city to the ground.<ref name=\"Treadgold483\">{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|p=483}}.</ref> Until 938, the East remained relatively calm. Historians suggest that the Byzantines were likely preoccupied with the full pacification of Melitene, and the Arab emirates, deprived of any potential support from the Caliphate, were reluctant to provoke them.<ref name=\"Runciman142\"/><ref name=\"Whittow318\">{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=318}}.</ref>\n\nWith the decline of the Caliphate and its obvious inability to defend its border provinces, a new local dynasty, the [[Hamdanids]], emerged as the principal antagonists of Byzantium in [[northern Mesopotamia]] and [[al-Sham|Syria]]. They were led by al-Hasan, called ''[[Nasir al-Dawla]]'' (\"Defender of the State\"), and by his younger brother Ali, best known by his [[laqab|epithet]], ''[[Sayf al-Dawla]]'' (\"Sword of the State\").<ref name=\"Whittow318\"/> In {{circa|935}}, the Arab tribe of [[Banu Habib]], defeated by the rising Hamdanids, defected in its entirety to the Byzantines, converted to Christianity, and placed its 12,000&nbsp;horsemen at the disposal of the Empire. They were settled along the western bank of the Euphrates and assigned to guard five new [[Theme (Byzantine district)|themes]] created there: Melitene, [[Charpezikion]], Asmosaton ([[Arsamosata]]), [[Derzene]], and [[Chozanon]].<ref name=\"Treadgold483\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Treadgold|1998|p=78}}.</ref>\n\nThe first Byzantine encounter with Sayf al-Dawla took place in 936, when he tried to relieve Samosata, but a revolt at home forced him to turn back.<ref name=\"Treadgold483\"/> In another invasion in 938, however, he captured the fort of [[Charpete]] and defeated Kourkouas's advance guard, seizing a great amount of booty and forcing Kourkouas to withdraw.<ref name=\"Treadgold483\"/><ref>{{harvnb|ODB|loc=\"Sayf al-Dawla\" (A. Kazhdan), p. 1848}}.</ref> In the same year, a peace agreement was signed between Constantinople and the Caliphate. The negotiations were facilitated by the rising power of the Hamdanids, which caused anxiety to both sides.<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=142\u2013143}}.</ref> Despite the official peace with the Caliphate, ''ad hoc'' warfare continued between the Byzantines and the local Muslim rulers, now aided by the Hamdanids. The Byzantines attempted to besiege Theodosiopolis in 939, but the siege was abandoned at the news of the approach of Sayf al-Dawla's relief army.<ref name=\"Treadgold483\"/>\n\nBy that time, the Byzantines had captured Arsamosata and additional strategically important locations in the mountains of southwest Armenia, posing a direct threat to the Muslim emirates around Lake Van.<ref name=\"Whittow318\"/> To reverse the situation, in 940&nbsp;Sayf al-Dawla initiated a remarkable campaign: starting from [[Mayyafiriqin]] (Byzantine Martyropolis), he crossed the [[Bitlis]] pass into Armenia, where he seized several fortresses and accepted the submission of the local lords, both Muslim and Christian. He ravaged the Byzantine holdings around Theodosiopolis and raided as far as [[Koloneia on the Lykos|Koloneia]], which he besieged until Kourkouas arrived with a relief army and forced him to withdraw.<ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|pp=319\u2013320}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=143\u2013144}}; {{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|pp=483\u2013484}}.</ref> Sayf al-Dawla was not able to follow up on this effort: until 945, the Hamdanids were preoccupied with internal developments in the Caliphate and with fighting against their rivals in southern [[Iraq]] and the [[Ikhshidids]] in Syria.<ref name=\"Runciman144\">{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=144}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=320}}.</ref>\n\n===Rus' raid of 941===\n{{main|Rus'\u2013Byzantine War (941)}}\nThe distraction by the Hamdanids proved fortunate for Byzantium. In early summer 941, as Kourkouas prepared to resume campaigning in the East, his attention was diverted by an unexpected event: the appearance of a [[Rus' (people)|Rus']] fleet that raided the area around Constantinople itself. The Byzantine army and navy were absent from the capital, and the appearance of the Rus' fleet caused panic among the populace of Constantinople. While the navy and Kourkouas's army were recalled, a hastily assembled squadron of old ships armed with [[Greek Fire]] and placed under the ''[[protovestiarios]]'' [[Theophanes (chamberlain)|Theophanes]] defeated the Rus' fleet on June 11, forcing it to abandon its course toward the city. The surviving Rus' landed on the shores of [[Bithynia]] and ravaged the defenseless countryside.<ref>{{harvnb|Jenkins|1987|pp=250\u2013251}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=111\u2013112}}.</ref> The ''patrikios'' [[Bardas Phokas the Elder|Bardas Phokas]] hastened to the area with whatever troops he could gather, contained the raiders, and awaited the arrival of Kourkouas's army. Finally, Kourkouas and his army appeared and fell upon the Rus', who had dispersed to plunder the countryside, killing many of them. The survivors retreated to their ships and tried to cross  to [[Thrace]] under the cover of night. During the crossing, the entire [[Byzantine navy]] attacked and annihilated the Rus'.<ref>{{harvnb|Jenkins|1987|p=251}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=112}}; {{harvnb|Guilland|1967|pp=442\u2013443, 572}}.</ref>\n\n===Campaigns in Mesopotamia and recovery of the ''Mandylion''===\n[[File:Surrender of the Mandylion to the Byzantines.jpg|thumb|right|250px|thumb|alt=Beneath a domed superstructure, a delegation of bearded men stands left, in the center, a man surrenders a cloth with the face of Christ to another man, who kisses it, while churchmen stand to the right.|The surrender of the ''Mandylion'' to the Byzantine ''[[parakoimomenos]]'' Theophanes by the Edessenes, from the [[Madrid Skylitzes]].]]\n\nFollowing this distraction, in January 942 Kourkouas launched a new campaign in the East, which lasted for three years.<ref name=\"Runciman144\"/> The first assault fell on the territory of [[Aleppo]], which was thoroughly plundered: at the fall of the town of Hamus, near Aleppo, even Arab sources record the capture of 10\u201315,000 prisoners by the Byzantines.<ref name=\"Runciman144\"/> Despite a minor counter-raid by Thamal or one of his retainers (''[[ghilman]]'') from Tarsus in the summer, in autumn Kourkouas launched another major invasion. At the head of an exceptionally large army, some 80,000 men according to Arab sources, he crossed from allied [[Taron (historic Armenia)|Taron]] into northern Mesopotamia.<ref name=\"Runciman144\"/><ref name=\"Treadgold484\">{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|p=484}}.</ref> Mayyafiriqin, [[Amida (Roman city)|Amida]], [[Nisibis]], [[Dara (Mesopotamia)|Dara]]&mdash;places where no Byzantine army had trod since the days of [[Heraclius]] 300&nbsp;years earlier&mdash;were stormed and ravaged.<ref name=\"Runciman144\"/><ref name=\"Whittow321\">{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=321}}.</ref><ref name=\"Jenkins247\">{{harvnb|Jenkins|1987|p=247}}.</ref> The real aim of these campaigns, however, was [[Edessa, Mesopotamia|Edessa]], the repository of the \"Holy ''[[Mandylion]]''\". This was a cloth believed to have been used by [[Christ]] to wipe his face, leaving an imprint of his features, and subsequently given to King [[Abgar V of Edessa]]. To the Byzantines, especially after the end of the [[Byzantine Iconoclasm|Iconoclasm period]] and the restoration of image veneration, it was a relic of profound religious significance. As a result, its capture would provide the Lekapenos regime with an enormous boost in popularity and legitimacy.<ref name=\"Whittow321\"/><ref name=\"Guilland572\">{{harvnb|Guilland|1967|p=572}}.</ref>\n\nKourkouas assailed Edessa every year from 942 onward and devastated its countryside, as he had done at Melitene. Finally, its emir agreed to a peace, swearing not to raise arms against Byzantium and to hand over the ''Mandylion'' in exchange for the return of 200 prisoners.<ref name=\"Whittow321\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=5}}.</ref> The ''Mandylion'' was conveyed to Constantinople, where it arrived on August 15, 944, on the feast of the [[Dormition of the Theotokos]]. A triumphal entry was staged for the venerated relic, which was then deposited in the [[Theotokos of the Pharos]] church, the palatine chapel of the [[Great Palace of Constantinople|Great Palace]].<ref name=\"Whittow321\"/><ref name=\"Jenkins247\"/> As for Kourkouas, he concluded his campaign by sacking Bithra (modern [[Birecik]]) and Germanikeia (modern [[Kahramanmara\u015f]]).<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=145}}.</ref>\n\n===Dismissal and rehabilitation===\nDespite this triumph, the downfall of Kourkouas, as well as of his friend and protector, Emperor Romanos I Lekapenos, was imminent. The two eldest surviving sons of Romanos I, co-emperors [[Stephen Lekapenos|Stephen]] and [[Constantine Lekapenos|Constantine]], were jealous of Kourkouas and had in the past tried to undermine him, albeit without success.<ref name=\"Runciman146\">{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=146}}.</ref> Following the success of Kourkouas in the East, Romanos I considered marrying his trusted general into the imperial family. Kourkouas's daughter Euphrosyne was to be wedded with the emperor's grandson, the future [[Romanos II]] ({{reign|959|963}}), the son of his son-in-law and junior emperor Constantine VII. Although such a union would effectively cement the loyalty of the army, it would also strengthen the position of the legitimate [[Macedonian dynasty|Macedonian line]], represented by Constantine VII, over the imperial claims of Romanos's own sons.<ref name=\"Guilland572\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|pp=484\u2013485}}; {{harvnb|Holmes|2005|pp=131\u2013132}}.</ref> Predictably, Stephen and Constantine opposed this decision and prevailed upon their father, who was by this time old and ill, to dismiss Kourkouas in the autumn of 944.<ref name=\"Runciman146\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|p=485}}.</ref>\n\nKourkouas was replaced by a certain [[Pantherios]], who was almost immediately defeated by Sayf al-Dawla in December while raiding near Aleppo. On 16 December, Romanos I himself was deposed by Stephen and Constantine and banished to a monastery on the island of [[Prote]]. A few weeks later, on 26 January, another coup removed the two young Lekapenoi from power and restored the sole imperial authority to Constantine VII.<ref name=\"Whittow321\"/><ref name=\"Runciman146\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|p=486}}.</ref> Kourkouas himself appears to have soon returned to imperial favour: Constantine provided the money for the repair of Kourkouas's palace after it was damaged by an earthquake, and in early 946, he is recorded as having been sent with the ''[[magistros]]'' Kosmas to negotiate a [[Arab\u2013Byzantine prisoner exchanges|prisoner exchange]] with the Arabs of Tarsus. Nothing further is known about him.<ref>{{harvnb|Guilland|1967|pp=442, 572}}.</ref> \n\nThe fall of the Lekapenoi signalled the end of an era in terms of personalities, but Kourkouas's expansionist policy continued: he was succeeded as Domestic of the Schools by [[Bardas Phokas the Elder]], followed by [[Nikephoros II|Nikephoros Phokas]], who reigned as emperor in 963\u2013969, and finally, by Kourkouas's own great-nephew, [[John Tzimiskes]], who reigned as emperor in 969\u2013976. All of them expanded the Byzantine frontier in the East, recovering [[Cilicia]] and northern Syria with [[Antioch]], and converting the Hamdanid emirate of Aleppo into a Byzantine [[protectorate]].<ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|pp=322\u2013327}}.</ref>\n\n==Assessment==\n{{quote box\n|width     = 260px\n|align     = right\n|bgcolor   = #c6dbf7\n|quote     = \"... the aforementioned ''[[magistros]]'' and Domestic of the Schools John became unrivalled in matters of war, and set up many and great trophies, and expanded the Roman boundaries and sacked many [[Hagarenes|Hagarene]] cities.\"\n|source    = Chronicle of [[Theophanes Continuatus]], ''Reign of Romanos Lekapenos'', 40.<ref>{{harvnb|Niebuhr|1838|p=426}}; {{harvnb|Holmes|2005|pp=135\u2013136}}.</ref>\n}}\nKourkouas ranks among the greatest military leaders Byzantium produced, a fact recognized by the Byzantines themselves: later Byzantine chroniclers hailed him as the general who restored the imperial frontier to the [[Euphrates]],<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=148}}.</ref> and in a contemporary eight-book history, written by a ''[[protospatharios]]'' Michael and now lost save for a short summary in [[Theophanes Continuatus]], he is acclaimed as \"a second [[Trajan]] or [[Belisarius]]\".<ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=344}}.</ref>\n\nThe ground work for his successes had certainly been laid by others: [[Michael III]], who broke the power of Melitene at Lalakaon; [[Basil I]], who destroyed the [[Paulicians]]; [[Leo VI the Wise]], who founded the vital theme of [[Mesopotamia (theme)|Mesopotamia]]; and Empress [[Zoe Karbonopsina|Zoe]], who extended Byzantine influence again into Armenia and founded the theme of Lykandos.<ref name=\"Jenkins246\"/><ref name=\"Runciman146\"/> It was Kourkouas and his campaigns, however, that incontrovertibly changed the balance of power in the northern [[Middle East]], securing the frontier provinces against Arab raids and turning Byzantium into an expansionist power.<ref name=\"Jenkins246\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=146\u2013149}}.</ref> In the words of historian [[Steven Runciman]], \"a lesser general might [...] have cleared the Empire of the [[Saracen]]s and successfully defended its borders; but [Kourkouas] did more. He infused a new spirit into the imperial armies, and led them victoriously deep into the country of the infidels. The actual area of his conquests was not so very large; but they sufficed to reverse the age-old roles of Byzantium and the Arabs. Byzantium now was the aggressor... [John Kourkouas] was the first of a line of great conquerors and as the first is worthy of high praise.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=150}}.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{refbegin}}\n{{Cnote|a|\"Kourkouas\" represents the transliteration of his Greek name following the norm used in the ''[[Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium]]''. \"Kurkuas\" and \"Curcuas\" are different [[Latinisation (literature)|Latinized]] forms.}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n*{{cite book|last=El-Cheikh|first=Nadia Maria|title=Byzantium Viewed by the Arabs|location=Cambridge, Mass.|publisher=Harvard Center for Middle Eastern Studies|year=2004|isbn=0-932885-30-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QC03pKNpfaoC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Guilland|first=Rodolphe| authorlink=Rodolphe Guilland|title=Recherches sur les institutions byzantines, Tome I|language=French|location=Berlin|publisher=Akademie-Verlag|year=1967|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1_MnAQAAIAAJ|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Holmes|first=Catherine|title=Basil II and the Governance of Empire (976\u20131025)|location=Oxford|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2005|isbn=0-19-927968-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0rIFIdM8SrkC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Jenkins|first=Romilly|title=Byzantium: The Imperial Centuries, AD 610\u20131071|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O5JqH_NXQBsC|location=Toronto|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1987|isbn=0-8020-6667-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium}}\n*{{cite book|editor-last=Niebuhr|editor-first=Barthold Georg|title=Theophanes Continuatus, Ioannes Cameniata, Symeon Magister, Georgius Monachus|publisher=E. Weber|location=Bonn|year=1838|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0GgGAAAAQAAJ|oclc=246268950|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Runciman|first=Steven|authorlink=Steven Runciman|title=The Emperor Romanus Lecapenus and His Reign: A Study of Tenth-Century Byzantium|location=Cambridge, UK|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1988|origyear=1929|isbn=0-521-35722-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XHVzWN6gqxQC|ref=harv}}\n*{{The Arab Emirates in Bagratid Armenia}}\n*{{A History of the Byzantine State and Society}}\n*{{cite book|last=Treadgold|first=Warren T.|authorlink=Warren Treadgold|title=Byzantium and Its Army, 284\u20131081|year=1998|origyear=1995|location=Stanford, Cal.|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=0-8047-3163-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xfV0LkMNaLUC|ref=harv}}\n*{{The Making of Byzantium, 600\u20131025}}\n{{refend|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last1=Shepard |first1=Jonathan |authorlink1=Jonathan Shepard|editor1-last=Rogers |editor1-first=Clifford J. |editor-link1=Clifford J. Rogers|title=The Oxford Encyclopedia of Medieval Warfare and Military Technology |date=2010 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0195338423 |url=https://www.oxfordreference.com/abstract/10.1093/acref/9780195334036.001.0001/acref-9780195334036-e-0515?rskey=Y78qXm&result=1 |chapter=Kourkouas, John|ref=harv}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pothos Argyros (Domestic of the Schools)|Pothos Argyros]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Domestic of the Schools]]|years=922\u201344}}\n{{s-aft|after=Pantherios}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kourkouas, John}}\n[[Category:9th-century births]]\n[[Category:10th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:10th-century Byzantine people]]\n[[Category:Byzantine generals]]\n[[Category:Kourkouas family|John]]\n[[Category:History of Malatya]]\n[[Category:Byzantine people of the Arab\u2013Byzantine wars]]\n[[Category:Domestics of the Schools]]\n[[Category:Magistroi]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the 10th-century general|his 9th-century grandfather|John Kourkouas (9th century)|the 11th-century governor of Italy|John Kourkouas (catepan)}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          =John Kourkouas\n| birth_date          = before 900\n| death_date          = after 946\n| allegiance    = [[Byzantine Empire]]\n| serviceyears  = {{circa|915}}\u2013944\n| rank          = [[Domestic of the Schools]]\n| relations     = [[Theophilos Kourkouas]], [[Romanos Kourkouas]], [[John Tzimiskes]]\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Byzantine-Arab Wars}}\n'''John Kourkouas''' ({{lang-gr|\u1f38\u03c9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03b1\u03c2|Ioannes Kourkouas}}, {{fl.|{{circa|915}}\u2013946}}), also transliterated as '''Kurkuas''' or '''Curcuas''',{{cref|a}} was one of the most important generals of the [[Byzantine Empire]]. His success in battles against the [[Caliphate|Muslim states]] in the East definitively reversed the course of the centuries-long [[Byzantine\u2013Arab Wars]] and began Byzantium's 10th century \"Age of Conquest\".\n\nKourkouas belonged to a family of [[Armenians|Armenian]] descent that produced several notable Byzantine generals. As commander of an imperial bodyguard regiment, Kourkouas was among the chief supporters of [[Byzantine emperor|Emperor]] [[Romanos I Lekapenos]] ({{reign|920|944}}) and facilitated the latter's rise to the throne. In 923, Kourkouas was appointed commander-in-chief of the Byzantine armies along the eastern frontier, facing the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] and the semi-autonomous Muslim border emirates. He kept this post for more than twenty years, overseeing decisive Byzantine military successes that altered the strategic balance in the region.\n\nDuring the 9th century, Byzantium had gradually recovered its strength and internal stability while the Caliphate had become increasingly impotent and fractured. Under Kourkouas's leadership, the Byzantine armies advanced deep into Muslim territory for the first time in almost 200 years, expanding the imperial border. The emirates of [[Melitene]] and [[Erzurum|Qaliqala]] were conquered, extending Byzantine control to the upper [[Euphrates]] and over [[western Armenia]]. The remaining [[Caucasian Iberia|Iberian]] and Armenian princes became Byzantine vassals. Kourkouas also played a role in the defeat of a major [[Rus' (people)|Rus']] raid in 941 and recovered the ''[[Mandylion]]'' of [[Edessa, Mesopotamia|Edessa]], an important and holy [[relic]] believed to depict the face of [[Jesus Christ]]. He was dismissed in 944 as a result of the machinations of Romanos Lekapenos's sons but restored to favour by Emperor [[Constantine VII]] ({{reign|913|959}}), serving as imperial ambassador in 946. His subsequent fate is unknown.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and career===\nJohn was a [[kinship|scion]] of the Armenian [[Kourkouas]] family&mdash;a [[Hellenization|Hellenized]] form of their original surname, Gurgen (Armenian: \u0533\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0563\u0565\u0576) &mdash;which had risen to prominence in Byzantine service in the 9th century and established itself as one of the great families of the [[Anatolia]]n land-holding military aristocracy (the so-called \"''[[dynatoi]]''\").<ref>{{harvnb|ODB|loc=\"Kourkouas\" (A. Kazhdan), pp. 1156\u20131157}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|pp=337\u2013338}}.</ref> John's [[John Kourkouas (9th century)|namesake grandfather]] had been a commander of the elite ''[[Hikanatoi]]'' regiment (''[[tagma (military)|tagma]]'') under Emperor [[Basil I]] ({{reign|867|886}}); John's brother [[Theophilos Kourkouas|Theophilos]] became a senior general, as did John's own son, [[Romanos Kourkouas|Romanos]], and his great-nephew, [[John Tzimiskes]].<ref name=\"ODB\">{{harvnb|ODB|loc=\"Kourkouas, John\" (A. Kazhdan), p. 1157}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Guilland|1967|pp=442\u2013443, 446, 463, 571}}.</ref>\n\n[[File:Romanus I with Christopher, solidus.jpg|thumb|left|250px|alt=Obverse (right) and reverse (left) view of gold coin. On the obverse, Christ seated on throne. On the reverse, two crowned men, one bearded and one not, holding a patriarchal cross on a staff between them.|Gold coin (''[[solidus (coin)|solidus]]'') of Romanos I Lekapenos, depicting him and his eldest son (and co-emperor from 921 on), [[Christopher Lekapenos|Christopher]].]]\n\nLittle is known about John's early life. His father was a wealthy official in the imperial palace. John himself was born at Dokeia (now [[Tokat]]), in the region of Darbidos in the [[Armeniac Theme]], and was educated by one of his relatives, the bishop of [[Gangra]] Christopher.<ref>{{harvnb|Guilland|1967|pp=443, 571}}.</ref> In the late regency of Empress [[Zoe Karbonopsina]] (914\u2013919) for her infant son [[Constantine VII]] ({{reign|913|959}}), Kourkouas was appointed as the commander of the ''[[Vigla (tagma)|Vigla]]'' palace guard regiment, probably through the machinations of the fellow Armenian, admiral [[Romanos Lekapenos]], as part of his drive for the throne. In this capacity, he arrested several high officials who opposed Lekapenos's rise to power, opening the road to the appointment of Lekapenos as regent in place of Zoe in 919. Lekapenos gradually assumed more powers until he was crowned senior emperor in December 920.<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=58\u201362}}; {{harvnb|Guilland|1967|p=571}}.</ref> As a reward for his support, in {{Circa|923}}, Romanos Lekapenos promoted Kourkouas to the post of [[Domestic of the Schools]], in effect commander-in-chief of all the imperial armies in Anatolia.<ref name=\"ODB\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=69}}.</ref> According to the chronicle of [[Theophanes Continuatus]], Kourkouas held this post for an unparalleled continuous term of 22&nbsp;years and seven months.<ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=418}}; {{harvnb|Guilland|1967|pp=447, 571}}.</ref>\n\nAt this time, and following the disastrous [[Battle of Acheloos]] in 917, the Byzantines were mostly occupied in the Balkans in a [[Byzantine\u2013Bulgarian war of 913\u2013927|protracted conflict]] against [[First Bulgarian Empire|Bulgaria]].<ref name=\"Whittow317\">{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=317}}.</ref> Hence, Kourkouas's first task as Domestic of the East was the suppression of the revolt of [[Bardas Boilas]], the governor (''[[strategos]]'') of [[Chaldia]], a strategically important area on the Empire's northeastern Anatolian frontier. This was quickly achieved and his brother, Theophilos Kourkouas, replaced Boilas as governor of Chaldia. As commander of this northernmost sector of the eastern frontier, Theophilos proved a competent soldier and gave valuable assistance to his brother's campaigns.<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=70\u201371, 135}}; {{harvnb|Guilland|1967|pp=442\u2013443, 571\u2013572}}.</ref>\n\n===First submission of Melitene, campaigns into Armenia===\nFollowing the [[Muslim conquests]] of the 7th century, the [[Arab\u2013Byzantine Wars|Arab\u2013Byzantine conflict]] had featured constant raids and counter-raids along a relatively static border roughly defined by the line of the [[Taurus Mountains|Taurus]] and [[Anti-Taurus Mountains]].<ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|pp=176\u2013178}}.</ref> Until the 860s, superior Muslim armies had placed the Byzantines on the defensive. Only after 863, with the victory in the [[Battle of Lalakaon]], did the Byzantines gradually regain some lost ground against the Muslims, launching ever-deeper raids into [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]] and [[Upper Mesopotamia]] and annexing the [[Paulicians|Paulician]] state around Tephrike (now [[Divri\u011fi]]).<ref>{{harvnb|El-Cheikh|2004|p=162}}; {{harvnb|Whittow|1996|pp=311\u2013314}}.</ref> Furthermore, according to historian Mark Whittow, \"by 912 the Arabs had been pinned back behind the Taurus and Anti-Taurus\", encouraging the Armenians to switch their allegiance from the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] to the Empire, in whose service they entered in increasing numbers.<ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=315}}.</ref> The revival of Byzantine power was further facilitated by the progressive decline of the Abbasid Caliphate itself, particularly under [[al-Muqtadir]] ({{reign|908|932}}), when the central government faced several revolts. In the periphery of the Caliphate, the weakening of central control allowed the emergence of semi-autonomous local dynasties.<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=136\u2013137}}.</ref> In addition, after the death of the Bulgarian Tsar [[Simeon I of Bulgaria|Simeon]] in 927, a peace treaty with the Bulgarians allowed the Empire to shift attention and resources to the East.<ref name=\"Whittow317\"/>\n\nBy 925, Romanos Lekapenos felt himself strong enough to demand the payment of tribute from the Muslim cities on the western side of the [[Euphrates]]. When they refused, in 926, Kourkouas led the army across the border.<ref name=\"Runciman137\">{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=137}}.</ref> Aided by his brother Theophilos and an Armenian contingent under the ''strategos'' of [[Lykandos]], Mleh ([[Melias]] in Greek sources),<ref name=\"Treadgold479\">{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|p=479}}.</ref> Kourkouas targeted Melitene (modern [[Malatya]]), the center of an emirate which had long been a thorn in Byzantium's side.<ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=310}}; {{harvnb|Treadgold|1998|p=111}}.</ref> The Byzantine army successfully stormed the lower city, and although the citadel held out, Kourkouas concluded a treaty by which the emir accepted tributary status.<ref name=\"Runciman137\"/><ref name=\"Treadgold479\"/>\n\n[[File:EarlyBagratid884-962.gif|thumb|right|250px|alt=Map of the southern Caucasus and the area of eastern Turkey and northern Iraq and Syria. Greater Armenia in the center with minor Caucasian principalities to its northeast, the Byzantines to the west and the Abbasid caliphate to the south and east.|Map of Armenia and the Caucasian states in the mid-10th century.]]\n\nIn 927\u2013928, Kourkouas launched a large raid into Arab-controlled [[Bagratuni Kingdom of Armenia|Armenia]]. After taking Samosata (modern [[Samsat]]), an important stronghold on the Euphrates, the Byzantines advanced as far as the Armenian capital of [[Dvin (ancient city)|Dvin]].<ref name=\"Treadgold479\"/> An Arab counter-offensive forced them out of Samosata after only a few days, and Dvin, which was defended by the [[Sajids|Sajid]] general Nasr al-Subuki, successfully withstood the Byzantine siege, until the mounting losses forced the Byzantines to abandon it.<ref>{{harvnb|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=77}}.</ref> At the same time, [[Thamal al-Dulafi|Thamal]], the emir of Tarsus, conducted successful raids into southern Anatolia and neutralized [[Ibn al-Dahhak]], a local [[Kurds|Kurdish]] leader who supported the Byzantines.<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=138}}.</ref> The Byzantines then turned toward the [[Kaysites|Kaysite]] emirate in the region of [[Lake Van]] in southern Armenia. Kourkouas's troops plundered the region and took the towns of [[Ahlat|Khliat]] and [[Bitlis]], where they are said to have replaced the [[mosque]]'s ''[[minbar]]'' with a cross. The local Arabs appealed to the Caliph for aid in vain, prompting an exodus of Muslims from the region.<ref name=\"TG82\">{{harvnb|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=82}}.</ref><ref name=\"Treadgold480\">{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|p=480}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=138\u2013139}}.</ref> This incursion, more than {{convert|500|km}} from the nearest imperial territory, was a far cry from the defensive-minded strategy Byzantium had followed during the previous centuries and highlighted the new capabilities of the imperial army.<ref name=\"Whittow317\"/> Nevertheless, famine in Anatolia and the exigencies of parallel campaigns in [[Catepanate of Italy|southern Italy]] weakened Kourkouas's forces. His army was defeated and driven back by [[Muflih al-Saji|Muflih]], a former Sajid ''[[Ghulam (slave soldier)|ghulam]]'' and governor of [[Adharbayjan]].<ref name=\"TG82\"/><ref name=\"Treadgold480\"/><ref name=\"Runciman139\">{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=139}}.</ref>\n\nIn 930, Melias's attack on Samosata was heavily defeated; among other prominent officers, one of his sons was captured and sent to [[Baghdad]].<ref name=\"Runciman139\"/> Later in the same year, John and his brother Theophilos besieged Theodosiopolis (modern [[Erzurum]]), the capital of the emirate of Qaliqala.<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=139\u2013140}}.</ref> The campaign was complicated by the machinations of their ostensible allies, the [[Caucasian Iberia|Iberian]] rulers of [[Tao-Klarjeti]]. Resenting the extension of direct Byzantine control adjacent to their own borders, the Iberians had already provided supplies to the besieged city. Once the city was invested, they vociferously demanded that the Byzantines hand over several captured towns, but when one of them, the fort of Mastaton, was surrendered, the Iberians promptly returned it to the Arabs. As Kourkouas needed to keep the Iberians placated and was aware that his conduct was being carefully observed by the Armenian princes, he did not react to this affront.<ref name=\"Runciman140\">{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=140}}.</ref> After seven months of siege, Theodosiopolis fell in spring 931 and was transformed into a tributary vassal, while, according to Constantine VII's ''[[De Administrando Imperio]]'', all territory north of the river [[Araxes]] was given to the Iberian king [[David II of Iberia|David II]]. As in Melitene, the maintenance of Byzantine control over Theodosiopolis proved difficult and the population remained restive. In 939, it revolted and drove out the Byzantines, and Theophilos Kourkouas could not finally subdue the city until 949. It was then fully incorporated into the Empire and its Muslim population was expelled and replaced by Greek and Armenian settlers.<ref name=\"Runciman140\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=322}}; {{harvnb|Holmes|2005|p=314}}.</ref>\n\n===Final capture of Melitene===\nFollowing the death of Emir [[Abu Hafs ibn Amr|Abu Hafs]], Melitene renounced its Byzantine allegiance.<ref name=\"Runciman137\"/> After attempts to take the city by storm or subterfuge failed, the Byzantines established a ring of fortresses on the hills around the plain of Melitene, and methodically ravaged the area.<ref name=\"Whittow317\"/> By early 931, the inhabitants of Melitene were forced to come to terms: they agreed to tributary status and even undertook to provide a military contingent to campaign alongside the Byzantines.<ref name=\"Whittow317\"/>\n\nThe other Muslim states were not idle, however: in March, the Byzantines were hit by three successive raids in Anatolia, organized by the Abbasid commander [[Mu'nis al-Muzaffar]], while in August, a large raid led by Thamal of Tarsus penetrated as far as [[Ancyra]] and [[Amorium]] and returned with prisoners worth 136,000&nbsp;[[gold dinar]]s.<ref name=\"Runciman141\">{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=141}}.</ref> During this time, the Byzantines were engaged in southern Armenia, aiding the ruler of [[Vaspurakan Kingdom|Vaspurakan]], [[Gagik I of Vaspurakan|Gagik I]], who had rallied the local Armenian princes and allied himself with the Byzantines against the emir of Adharbayjan. There they raided the Kaysite emirate and razed Khliat and [[Berkri]] to the ground, before marching into Mesopotamia and capturing Samosata again. Gagik was unable to take advantage of this and capture Kaysite territory, however, as Muflih immediately raided his domains in retaliation.<ref name=\"TG82\"/><ref name=\"Runciman141\"/><ref name=\"Jenkins246\">{{harvnb|Jenkins|1987|p=246}}.</ref> At this point, the Melitenians called upon the [[Hamdanid]] rulers of [[Mosul]] for help. In response, the Hamdanid prince [[Sa'id ibn Hamdan]] attacked the Byzantines and drove them back: Samosata was abandoned, and in November 931, the Byzantine garrison withdrew from Melitene as well.<ref name=\"Runciman141\"/><ref name=\"Treadgold481\">{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|p=481}}.</ref> Sa'id was, however, unable to remain in the area or to leave a sufficient garrison; once he left for Mosul, the Byzantines returned and resumed both the blockade of Melitene and their scorched-earth tactics.<ref name=\"Whittow317\"/>\n\n[[File:Melitene by the Byzantines in 934 from the Chronicle of John Skylitzes.jpg|thumb|left|250px|alt=Medieval miniature depicting a city being stormed. To the left is the Byzantine army, with shields and spears, with the tents of their camp to their back. They are scaling ladders onto the walls of a city (right), whose defenders try to fight them off from their top.|The fall of Melitene, miniature from the ''[[Skylitzes Chronicle]]''.]]\n\nThe sources record no major Byzantine external campaigns for 932, as the Empire was preoccupied with two revolts in the [[Opsician Theme]].<ref name=\"Treadgold481\"/> In 933, Kourkouas renewed the attack against Melitene. Mu'nis al-Muzaffar sent forces to assist the beleaguered city, but in the resulting skirmishes, the Byzantines prevailed and took many prisoners and the Arab army returned home without relieving the city.<ref name=\"Runciman141\"/><ref name=\"Treadgold481\"/> In early 934, at the head of 50,000&nbsp;men, Kourkouas again crossed the frontier and marched toward Melitene. The other Muslim states offered no help, preoccupied as they were with the turmoil following Caliph [[al-Qahir]]'s deposition. Kourkouas again took Samosata and besieged Melitene.<ref name=\"Runciman141\"/><ref name=\"Treadgold481\"/> Many of the city's inhabitants had abandoned it at the news of Kourkouas's approach and hunger eventually compelled the rest to surrender on 19 May 934. Wary of the city's previous rebellions, Kourkouas only allowed those inhabitants to remain who were Christians or agreed to convert to Christianity. Most did so, and he ordered the remainder expelled.<ref name=\"Whittow317\"/><ref name=\"Treadgold481\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=141\u2013142}}.</ref> Melitene was fully incorporated into the empire, and most of its fertile land was transformed into an imperial estate (''kouratoreia''). This was an unusual move, implemented by Romanos I to prevent the powerful Anatolian landed aristocracy from taking control of the province. It also served to increase direct imperial presence and control on the crucial new borderlands.<ref name=\"Treadgold481\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|pp=341\u2013342}}.</ref>\n\n===Rise of the Hamdanids===\nThe fall of Melitene profoundly shocked the Muslim world: for the first time, a major Muslim city had fallen and been incorporated into the Byzantine Empire.<ref name=\"Runciman142\">{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=142}}.</ref> Kourkouas followed this success by subduing parts of the district of Samosata in 936 and razing the city to the ground.<ref name=\"Treadgold483\">{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|p=483}}.</ref> Until 938, the East remained relatively calm. Historians suggest that the Byzantines were likely preoccupied with the full pacification of Melitene, and the Arab emirates, deprived of any potential support from the Caliphate, were reluctant to provoke them.<ref name=\"Runciman142\"/><ref name=\"Whittow318\">{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=318}}.</ref>\n\nWith the decline of the Caliphate and its obvious inability to defend its border provinces, a new local dynasty, the [[Hamdanids]], emerged as the principal antagonists of Byzantium in [[northern Mesopotamia]] and [[al-Sham|Syria]]. They were led by al-Hasan, called ''[[Nasir al-Dawla]]'' (\"Defender of the State\"), and by his younger brother Ali, best known by his [[laqab|epithet]], ''[[Sayf al-Dawla]]'' (\"Sword of the State\").<ref name=\"Whittow318\"/> In {{circa|935}}, the Arab tribe of [[Banu Habib]], defeated by the rising Hamdanids, defected in its entirety to the Byzantines, converted to Christianity, and placed its 12,000&nbsp;horsemen at the disposal of the Empire. They were settled along the western bank of the Euphrates and assigned to guard five new [[Theme (Byzantine district)|themes]] created there: Melitene, [[Charpezikion]], Asmosaton ([[Arsamosata]]), [[Derzene]], and [[Chozanon]].<ref name=\"Treadgold483\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Treadgold|1998|p=78}}.</ref>\n\nThe first Byzantine encounter with Sayf al-Dawla took place in 936, when he tried to relieve Samosata, but a revolt at home forced him to turn back.<ref name=\"Treadgold483\"/> In another invasion in 938, however, he captured the fort of [[Charpete]] and defeated Kourkouas's advance guard, seizing a great amount of booty and forcing Kourkouas to withdraw.<ref name=\"Treadgold483\"/><ref>{{harvnb|ODB|loc=\"Sayf al-Dawla\" (A. Kazhdan), p. 1848}}.</ref> In the same year, a peace agreement was signed between Constantinople and the Caliphate. The negotiations were facilitated by the rising power of the Hamdanids, which caused anxiety to both sides.<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=142\u2013143}}.</ref> Despite the official peace with the Caliphate, ''ad hoc'' warfare continued between the Byzantines and the local Muslim rulers, now aided by the Hamdanids. The Byzantines attempted to besiege Theodosiopolis in 939, but the siege was abandoned at the news of the approach of Sayf al-Dawla's relief army.<ref name=\"Treadgold483\"/>\n\nBy that time, the Byzantines had captured Arsamosata and additional strategically important locations in the mountains of southwest Armenia, posing a direct threat to the Muslim emirates around Lake Van.<ref name=\"Whittow318\"/> To reverse the situation, in 940&nbsp;Sayf al-Dawla initiated a remarkable campaign: starting from [[Mayyafiriqin]] (Byzantine Martyropolis), he crossed the [[Bitlis]] pass into Armenia, where he seized several fortresses and accepted the submission of the local lords, both Muslim and Christian. He ravaged the Byzantine holdings around Theodosiopolis and raided as far as [[Koloneia on the Lykos|Koloneia]], which he besieged until Kourkouas arrived with a relief army and forced him to withdraw.<ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|pp=319\u2013320}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=143\u2013144}}; {{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|pp=483\u2013484}}.</ref> Sayf al-Dawla was not able to follow up on this effort: until 945, the Hamdanids were preoccupied with internal developments in the Caliphate and with fighting against their rivals in southern [[Iraq]] and the [[Ikhshidids]] in Syria.<ref name=\"Runciman144\">{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=144}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=320}}.</ref>\n\n===Rus' raid of 941===\n{{main|Rus'\u2013Byzantine War (941)}}\nThe distraction by the Hamdanids proved fortunate for Byzantium. In early summer 941, as Kourkouas prepared to resume campaigning in the East, his attention was diverted by an unexpected event: the appearance of a [[Rus' (people)|Rus']] fleet that raided the area around Constantinople itself. The Byzantine army and navy were absent from the capital, and the appearance of the Rus' fleet caused panic among the populace of Constantinople. While the navy and Kourkouas's army were recalled, a hastily assembled squadron of old ships armed with [[Greek Fire]] and placed under the ''[[protovestiarios]]'' [[Theophanes (chamberlain)|Theophanes]] defeated the Rus' fleet on June 11, forcing it to abandon its course toward the city. The surviving Rus' landed on the shores of [[Bithynia]] and ravaged the defenseless countryside.<ref>{{harvnb|Jenkins|1987|pp=250\u2013251}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=111\u2013112}}.</ref> The ''patrikios'' [[Bardas Phokas the Elder|Bardas Phokas]] hastened to the area with whatever troops he could gather, contained the raiders, and awaited the arrival of Kourkouas's army. Finally, Kourkouas and his army appeared and fell upon the Rus', who had dispersed to plunder the countryside, killing many of them. The survivors retreated to their ships and tried to cross  to [[Thrace]] under the cover of night. During the crossing, the entire [[Byzantine navy]] attacked and annihilated the Rus'.<ref>{{harvnb|Jenkins|1987|p=251}}; {{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=112}}; {{harvnb|Guilland|1967|pp=442\u2013443, 572}}.</ref>\n\n===Campaigns in Mesopotamia and recovery of the ''Mandylion''===\n[[File:Surrender of the Mandylion to the Byzantines.jpg|thumb|right|250px|thumb|alt=Beneath a domed superstructure, a delegation of bearded men stands left, in the center, a man surrenders a cloth with the face of Christ to another man, who kisses it, while churchmen stand to the right.|The surrender of the ''Mandylion'' to the Byzantine ''[[parakoimomenos]]'' Theophanes by the Edessenes, from the [[Madrid Skylitzes]].]]\n\nFollowing this distraction, in January 942 Kourkouas launched a new campaign in the East, which lasted for three years.<ref name=\"Runciman144\"/> The first assault fell on the territory of [[Aleppo]], which was thoroughly plundered: at the fall of the town of Hamus, near Aleppo, even Arab sources record the capture of 10\u201315,000 prisoners by the Byzantines.<ref name=\"Runciman144\"/> Despite a minor counter-raid by Thamal or one of his retainers (''[[ghilman]]'') from Tarsus in the summer, in autumn Kourkouas launched another major invasion. At the head of an exceptionally large army, some 80,000 men according to Arab sources, he crossed from allied [[Taron (historic Armenia)|Taron]] into northern Mesopotamia.<ref name=\"Runciman144\"/><ref name=\"Treadgold484\">{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|p=484}}.</ref> Mayyafiriqin, [[Amida (Roman city)|Amida]], [[Nisibis]], [[Dara (Mesopotamia)|Dara]]&mdash;places where no Byzantine army had trod since the days of [[Heraclius]] 300&nbsp;years earlier&mdash;were stormed and ravaged.<ref name=\"Runciman144\"/><ref name=\"Whittow321\">{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=321}}.</ref><ref name=\"Jenkins247\">{{harvnb|Jenkins|1987|p=247}}.</ref> The real aim of these campaigns, however, was [[Edessa, Mesopotamia|Edessa]], the repository of the \"Holy ''[[Mandylion]]''\". This was a cloth believed to have been used by [[Christ]] to wipe his face, leaving an imprint of his features, and subsequently given to King [[Abgar V of Edessa]]. To the Byzantines, especially after the end of the [[Byzantine Iconoclasm|Iconoclasm period]] and the restoration of image veneration, it was a relic of profound religious significance. As a result, its capture would provide the Lekapenos regime with an enormous boost in popularity and legitimacy.<ref name=\"Whittow321\"/><ref name=\"Guilland572\">{{harvnb|Guilland|1967|p=572}}.</ref>\n\nKourkouas assailed Edessa every year from 942 onward and devastated its countryside, as he had done at Melitene. Finally, its emir agreed to a peace, swearing not to raise arms against Byzantium and to hand over the ''Mandylion'' in exchange for the return of 200 prisoners.<ref name=\"Whittow321\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=5}}.</ref> The ''Mandylion'' was conveyed to Constantinople, where it arrived on August 15, 944, on the feast of the [[Dormition of the Theotokos]]. A triumphal entry was staged for the venerated relic, which was then deposited in the [[Theotokos of the Pharos]] church, the palatine chapel of the [[Great Palace of Constantinople|Great Palace]].<ref name=\"Whittow321\"/><ref name=\"Jenkins247\"/> As for Kourkouas, he concluded his campaign by sacking Bithra (modern [[Birecik]]) and Germanikeia (modern [[Kahramanmara\u015f]]).<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=145}}.</ref>\n\n===Dismissal and rehabilitation===\nDespite this triumph, the downfall of Kourkouas, as well as of his friend and protector, Emperor Romanos I Lekapenos, was imminent. The two eldest surviving sons of Romanos I, co-emperors [[Stephen Lekapenos|Stephen]] and [[Constantine Lekapenos|Constantine]], were jealous of Kourkouas and had in the past tried to undermine him, albeit without success.<ref name=\"Runciman146\">{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=146}}.</ref> Following the success of Kourkouas in the East, Romanos I considered marrying his trusted general into the imperial family. Kourkouas's daughter Euphrosyne was to be wedded with the emperor's grandson, the future [[Romanos II]] ({{reign|959|963}}), the son of his son-in-law and junior emperor Constantine VII. Although such a union would effectively cement the loyalty of the army, it would also strengthen the position of the legitimate [[Macedonian dynasty|Macedonian line]], represented by Constantine VII, over the imperial claims of Romanos's own sons.<ref name=\"Guilland572\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|pp=484\u2013485}}; {{harvnb|Holmes|2005|pp=131\u2013132}}.</ref> Predictably, Stephen and Constantine opposed this decision and prevailed upon their father, who was by this time old and ill, to dismiss Kourkouas in the autumn of 944.<ref name=\"Runciman146\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|p=485}}.</ref>\n\nKourkouas was replaced by a certain [[Pantherios]], who was almost immediately defeated by Sayf al-Dawla in December while raiding near Aleppo. On 16 December, Romanos I himself was deposed by Stephen and Constantine and banished to a monastery on the island of [[Prote]]. A few weeks later, on 26 January, another coup removed the two young Lekapenoi from power and restored the sole imperial authority to Constantine VII.<ref name=\"Whittow321\"/><ref name=\"Runciman146\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Treadgold|1997|p=486}}.</ref> Kourkouas himself appears to have soon returned to imperial favour: Constantine provided the money for the repair of Kourkouas's palace after it was damaged by an earthquake, and in early 946, he is recorded as having been sent with the ''[[magistros]]'' Kosmas to negotiate a [[Arab\u2013Byzantine prisoner exchanges|prisoner exchange]] with the Arabs of Tarsus. Nothing further is known about him.<ref>{{harvnb|Guilland|1967|pp=442, 572}}.</ref> \n\nThe fall of the Lekapenoi signalled the end of an era in terms of personalities, but Kourkouas's expansionist policy continued: he was succeeded as Domestic of the Schools by [[Bardas Phokas the Elder]], followed by [[Nikephoros II|Nikephoros Phokas]], who reigned as emperor in 963\u2013969, and finally, by Kourkouas's own great-nephew, [[John Tzimiskes]], who reigned as emperor in 969\u2013976. All of them expanded the Byzantine frontier in the East, recovering [[Cilicia]] and northern Syria with [[Antioch]], and converting the Hamdanid emirate of Aleppo into a Byzantine [[protectorate]].<ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|pp=322\u2013327}}.</ref>\n\n==Assessment==\n{{quote box\n|width     = 260px\n|align     = right\n|bgcolor   = #c6dbf7\n|quote     = \"... the aforementioned ''[[magistros]]'' and Domestic of the Schools John became unrivalled in matters of war, and set up many and great trophies, and expanded the Roman boundaries and sacked many [[Hagarenes|Hagarene]] cities.\"\n|source    = Chronicle of [[Theophanes Continuatus]], ''Reign of Romanos Lekapenos'', 40.<ref>{{harvnb|Niebuhr|1838|p=426}}; {{harvnb|Holmes|2005|pp=135\u2013136}}.</ref>\n}}\nKourkouas ranks among the greatest military leaders Byzantium produced, a fact recognized by the Byzantines themselves: later Byzantine chroniclers hailed him as the general who restored the imperial frontier to the [[Euphrates]],<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=148}}.</ref> and in a contemporary eight-book history, written by a ''[[protospatharios]]'' Michael and now lost save for a short summary in [[Theophanes Continuatus]], he is acclaimed as \"a second [[Trajan]] or [[Belisarius]]\".<ref>{{harvnb|Whittow|1996|p=344}}.</ref>\n\nThe ground work for his successes had certainly been laid by others: [[Michael III]], who broke the power of Melitene at Lalakaon; [[Basil I]], who destroyed the [[Paulicians]]; [[Leo VI the Wise]], who founded the vital theme of [[Mesopotamia (theme)|Mesopotamia]]; and Empress [[Zoe Karbonopsina|Zoe]], who extended Byzantine influence again into Armenia and founded the theme of Lykandos.<ref name=\"Jenkins246\"/><ref name=\"Runciman146\"/> It was Kourkouas and his campaigns, however, that incontrovertibly changed the balance of power in the northern [[Middle East]], securing the frontier provinces against Arab raids and turning Byzantium into an expansionist power.<ref name=\"Jenkins246\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|pp=146\u2013149}}.</ref> In the words of historian [[Steven Runciman]], \"a lesser general might [...] have cleared the Empire of the [[Saracen]]s and successfully defended its borders; but [Kourkouas] did more. He infused a new spirit into the imperial armies, and led them victoriously deep into the country of the infidels. The actual area of his conquests was not so very large; but they sufficed to reverse the age-old roles of Byzantium and the Arabs. Byzantium now was the aggressor... [John Kourkouas] was the first of a line of great conquerors and as the first is worthy of high praise.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Runciman|1988|p=150}}.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{refbegin}}\n{{Cnote|a|\"Kourkouas\" represents the transliteration of his Greek name following the norm used in the ''[[Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium]]''. \"Kurkuas\" and \"Curcuas\" are different [[Latinisation (literature)|Latinized]] forms.}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n*{{cite book|last=El-Cheikh|first=Nadia Maria|title=Byzantium Viewed by the Arabs|location=Cambridge, Mass.|publisher=Harvard Center for Middle Eastern Studies|year=2004|isbn=0-932885-30-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QC03pKNpfaoC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Guilland|first=Rodolphe| authorlink=Rodolphe Guilland|title=Recherches sur les institutions byzantines, Tome I|language=French|location=Berlin|publisher=Akademie-Verlag|year=1967|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1_MnAQAAIAAJ|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Holmes|first=Catherine|title=Basil II and the Governance of Empire (976\u20131025)|location=Oxford|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2005|isbn=0-19-927968-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0rIFIdM8SrkC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Jenkins|first=Romilly|title=Byzantium: The Imperial Centuries, AD 610\u20131071|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O5JqH_NXQBsC|location=Toronto|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1987|isbn=0-8020-6667-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium}}\n*{{cite book|editor-last=Niebuhr|editor-first=Barthold Georg|title=Theophanes Continuatus, Ioannes Cameniata, Symeon Magister, Georgius Monachus|publisher=E. Weber|location=Bonn|year=1838|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0GgGAAAAQAAJ|oclc=246268950|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Runciman|first=Steven|authorlink=Steven Runciman|title=The Emperor Romanus Lecapenus and His Reign: A Study of Tenth-Century Byzantium|location=Cambridge, UK|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1988|origyear=1929|isbn=0-521-35722-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XHVzWN6gqxQC|ref=harv}}\n*{{The Arab Emirates in Bagratid Armenia}}\n*{{A History of the Byzantine State and Society}}\n*{{cite book|last=Treadgold|first=Warren T.|authorlink=Warren Treadgold|title=Byzantium and Its Army, 284\u20131081|year=1998|origyear=1995|location=Stanford, Cal.|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=0-8047-3163-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xfV0LkMNaLUC|ref=harv}}\n*{{The Making of Byzantium, 600\u20131025}}\n{{refend|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last1=Shepard |first1=Jonathan |authorlink1=Jonathan Shepard|editor1-last=Rogers |editor1-first=Clifford J. |editor-link1=Clifford J. Rogers|title=The Oxford Encyclopedia of Medieval Warfare and Military Technology |date=2010 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0195338423 |url=https://www.oxfordreference.com/abstract/10.1093/acref/9780195334036.001.0001/acref-9780195334036-e-0515?rskey=Y78qXm&result=1 |chapter=Kourkouas, John|ref=harv}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pothos Argyros (Domestic of the Schools)|Pothos Argyros]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Domestic of the Schools]]|years=922\u201344}}\n{{s-aft|after=Pantherios}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kourkouas, John}}\n[[Category:9th-century births]]\n[[Category:10th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:10th-century Byzantine people]]\n[[Category:Byzantine generals]]\n[[Category:Kourkouas family|John]]\n[[Category:History of Malatya]]\n[[Category:Byzantine people of the Arab\u2013Byzantine wars]]\n[[Category:Domestics of the Schools]]\n[[Category:Magistroi]]\n", "name_user": "Fridolin freudenfett", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:EarlyBagratid884-962.gif\u2192File:Caucasus, 884-962.gifCriterion 1(original uploader\u2019s request) \u00b7 better describes the view", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Kourkouas"}
{"title_page": "Ashot I of Armenia", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name            = Ashot I\n| image           = Ashot Medz.gif\n| caption         =\n| succession      = [[King of Armenia]]; Prince of Princes of Armenia\n| reign           = 884\u2013890\n| coronation      =\n| predecessor     =\n| successor       = [[Smbat I|Smbat I the Martyr]]\n| spouse          = [[Katranide I]]\n| issue           = [[Smbat I]]<br>Sahak<br>David<br>Shapuh\n| house           = [[Bagratuni Dynasty]]\n| house-type      = Dynasty\n| father          = Smbat the Confessor\n| mother          = Hripsime\n| birth_date      = c. 820\n| birth_place     =\n| death_date      = {{death year and age|890|820}}\n| death_place     = [[Gugark]], [[Kingdom of Armenia (antiquity)|Greater Armenia]]\n| date of burial  =\n| place of burial = [[Bagaran, Armenia]]\n| religion        = [[Armenian Apostolic]]\n|}}\n'''Ashot I''' ({{lang-hy|\u0531\u0577\u0578\u057f \u0531}}; c. 820 \u2013 890) was an [[Armenia]]n king who oversaw the beginning of Armenia's second [[golden age]] (862 \u2013 977). He was known as '''Ashot the Great''' (\u0531\u0577\u0578\u057f \u0544\u0565\u056e) and was the son of Smbat VIII the Confessor and was a member of the [[Bagratuni Dynasty]].\n\n==Life==\n\n===Early life===\nAshot was born around 820 to [[Smbat VIII Bagratuni]] and his wife Hripsime. Smbat VIII was ''[[sparapet]]'' (supreme commander) and the son of [[Ashot Msaker]], the Prince of Armenia (r. 806\u2013826).{{sfn|Toumanoff|1990|p=121}} Ashot also had a brother named Abas. The family, the [[Bagratuni dynasty|Bagratunis]], was one of the most powerful in the kingdom, along with the [[Artsruni]]. Both families struggled for power through warfare against [[Arab]] invaders. The kingdom was later taken over by Armenians who overthrew the [[Arminiya|Arab government]]. Smbat VIII was exiled to [[Samarra]], where he later died.{{sfn|Grousset|2008|pp=367, 378}} Ashot continued to live in his father's quarters,{{sfn|Martin-Hisard|2007|p=236}} located around the city of [[Bagaran (ancient city)|Bagaran]].{{sfn|Martin-Hisard|2007|p=234}} He was married to Katranide.{{sfn|Donab\u00e9dian|Thierry|1987|p=124}} Like Smbat before him, Ashot was named ''sparapet'' in 856 by the [[Abbasid Caliphate|Abbasid Caliph]] [[al-Mutawakkil]].{{sfn|Grousset|2008|p=372}}\n\n===Prince of Princes of Armenia===\n[[File:Arab-Byzantine frontier zone.svg|thumb|The Arab-Byzantine frontier zone during Ashot's lifetime.]]\nDuring the [[Arab-Byzantine Wars]], much of Ashot's territory was located near the main site of conflict. In 862, Ashot was recognized as the Prince of Princes of Armenia by Abbasid Caliph [[al-Musta'in]], who saw this as a measure of protection against the local autonomous [[emir]]s.{{sfn|Martin-Hisard|2007|p=237}}{{sfn|Cowe|2000|p=78}} This title essentially granted Ashot the status of ''de facto'' king{{sfn|Garso\u00efan|2004|p=147}} and placed him at a similar level of power as the emirs,{{sfn|Martin-Hisard|2007|p=237}} but did not allow Ashot to have administrative rule over the kingdom.{{sfn|Grousset|2008|p=373}} Ashot kept this status during the reigns of Abbasid Caliphs [[al-Mu'tazz]] (866\u2013869), [[al-Muhtadi]] (869\u2013870) and [[al-Mu'tamid]] (870\u2013892).\n\nAshot annexed [[Bagrevand]] in 862, shortly after the death of the ruling [[Mamikonian|Mamikonian Dynasty's]] head, Grigor Mamikonian.{{sfn|Martin-Hisard|2007|p=236}} Ashot mediated between Grigor-Derenik Artsruni and Gurgen Artsruni, cousins and members of the Artsruni family who controlled [[Vaspurakan]].{{sfn|Martin-Hisard|2007|p=236}} Ashot then captured Grigor-Derenik{{sfn|Grousset|2008|p=374}} and reduced the size of the cantons around [[Van, Turkey|Van]].{{sfn|Thierry|2007|p=275}} Ashot released Grigor-Derenik to avoid further conflict with the Artsruni family. Ashot later arranged a marriage between his daughter, Sophie, and Grigor-Derenik, in order to reconcile.{{sfn|Grousset|2008|p=375}} Ashot also strengthened relations with the [[Siunia Dynasty]] by arranging another marriage between his second daughter, Mariam, with Prince Vasak Gabur IV.{{sfn|Garso\u00efan|2007|p=272}} These familial ties helped strengthen relations between Ashot's sons and the surrounding dynasties.\n\nAshot used this support to wage war against the emirs. He began by defeating the [[Kaysites]] of [[Manazkert]] in 863,{{sfn|Grousset|2008|p=376}} with the help of his brother and [[sparapet]], Abas Bagratuni.{{sfn|Martin-Hisard|2007|p=236}} In 877, he began to fight against the emir of [[Barda, Azerbaijan|Barda]] alongside his [[ostikan]]; however, failure of this ostikan led to his replacement.{{sfn|Grousset|2008|p=385}} The new ostikan made a secret peace treaty with the emir and betrayed Ashot. Ashot learned of the conspiracy against him and sent Abas to disarm the ostikan in [[Dvin (ancient city)|Dvin]]; Abas escorted him to the border under Ashot's orders in order to prevent the Caliph's retaliation.{{sfn|Grousset|2008|p=386}} Ashot defeated the emirs of Barda and Manazkert, laying siege to the latter city in 884; however, the siege was ceased prematurely. The siege caused Grigor-Derenik to worry about the borders of [[Taron (historic Armenia)|Taron]], which was under Grigor-Derenik's control.{{sfn|Grousset|2008|p=387}} Ashot gained control of the [[Gugark]] and [[Utik]] regions{{sfn|Grousset|2008|p=391}} as early as 860.{{sfn|Dorfman-Lazarev|2004|p=65}}\n\nAshot's reach also extended to [[Principality of Iberia|Caucasian Iberia]], where some of his Bargatuni family had settled in the late 7th century. There, around 875, he formed an alliance with [[Bagrat I of Iberia]], his step-brother, against Bagrat's brother, [[Guaram Mampali]].{{sfn|Toumanoff|1990|pp=121, 129}} Together, Ashot and Bagrat defeated Guaram. In 881, Ashot formed an alliance with [[David I of Iberia]] and [[Adarnase IV of Iberia]], Bagrat's son and grandson, respectively, to defeat Guaram's son, [[Nasra of Tao-Klarjeti]].{{sfn|Grousset|2008|p=392}}\n\n===King of Armenia===\n[[File:Caucasus, 884-962.gif|thumb|300px|The borders of Bagratid Armenia from 884 to 962.]]\nSeveral contemporary prominent Armenians, including Grigor-Derenik Vaspurakan, insisted on Ashot's coronation.{{sfn|Grousset|2008|p=394}} Ashot was crowned [[King of Armenia]] through the consent of Caliph [[al-Mu'tamid]] in 885 to prevent intrusion into Armenian territory by [[Basil I]], a [[Byzantine emperor]] of Armenian origin.{{sfn|Garso\u00efan|2007|p=244}} As a result of his coronation, Ashot restored the Armenian monarchy and became the founder of the [[Middle Ages|medieval]] [[Kingdom of Armenia (Middle Ages)|Kingdom of Armenia]], also known as [[Bagratid Armenia]], named after the contemporary rule of the Bagratunis. The Bagratid kingdom lasted until 1045, when it was annexed into the [[Byzantine Empire]].{{sfn|Cheynet|2006|p=41}}\n\nDespite his status, Ashot remained a subordinate to the Caliph and was put under the supervision of the emirs of Azerbaijan.{{sfn|Martin-Hisard|2007|p=238}} Every Armenian prince fell under Ashot's authority (though in the effect of [[primus inter pares]]{{sfn|Martin-Hisard|2007|p=239}}). Dvin and the emirates of Manazkert and [[Erzurum|Karin]] (and, according to [[Constantine VII]], [[Khoy]] and [[Salmas]]){{sfn|Garso\u00efan|2007|p=245}} also fell under Ashot's control, despite the local governments' unwillingness to accept.{{sfn|Martin-Hisard|2007|p=238}} The emir of Manazkert was in this way defeated and was forced to submit to Ashot's rule in 885.{{sfn|Thierry|2007|pp=291-292}}\n\nAshot's influence continued not only in Armenia but also in Iberia. After the death on Grigor-Derenik Artsruni in 887, Ashot placed his own grandson (and Grigor-Derenik's son), Ashot-Sargis Artsruni, under the rule of relative Gagik Aboumerwan Artsruni.{{sfn|Grousset|2008|p=389}} In 887 and 888, Ashot supported his nephew [[Adarnase IV of Iberia]] in overthrowing [[Bagrat I of Abkhazia]].{{sfn|Garso\u00efan|2007|p=245}} Also in 888, Ashot sent his brother Abas to [[Kars]] to stop a rebellion led by Prince Sahak-Mleh of [[Vanand]].{{sfn|Garso\u00efan|2007|p=245}}\n\nAshot travelled to [[Gugark]] to stop another rebellion, fighting alongside his son and heir, [[Smbat I of Armenia|Smbat I]]. He died in 890. Contemporary historian [[Hovhannes Draskhanakerttsi]] gives an account of his death:\n\n{{quotation|Since he died on the road, in an inn at a rocky place called K'arsparn, they carried away his body in a coffin and brought it to the town (awan) of Bagaran, the royal residence, where they covered the coffin with robes and veils interwoven and adorned with gold; and carefully selected detachments of military forces clad in arms and ornaments stood guard. The great katholikos, accompanied by the rest of the clerics of the church, also came forth and solemnly chanted psalms and raised the voice of [their] praise. His three sons, the senior [gaherec'] princes of the royal house and other friends followed the coffin, and thus they arrived at the cemetery....Then, building a tomb [suitable] for royalty, they buried him in the cemetery of his ancestors.{{sfn|Manuk-Khaloyan|2013|p=134}}}}\n\nSmbat I succeeded him.\n\n==Armenian growth under rule==\nAshot's restoration of the Armenian monarchy was accompanied by economic growth{{sfn|Martin-Hisard|2007|p=239}} and a revival of the arts and religion.{{sfn|Redgate|2000|p=196}} Several cultural buildings were restored and renovated. Under Ashot's reign, the first [[khachkar]] was created in 879 as a tribute to Ashot's wife, Katranide.{{sfn|Donab\u00e9dian|Thierry|1987|p=530}} Urban growth began to occur{{sfn|Grousset|2008|p=396}} and agriculture flourished. Vineyards became a very successful industry.{{sfn|Grousset|2008|p=397}}\n\n==Religious affairs==\n[[File:Sevanavank \u00fcber dem Sewansee 03.JPG|thumb|[[Sevanavank|Sevanavank Monastery]], founded in 874 by Ashot's daughter Mariam and endowed by Ashot.{{sfn|Donab\u00e9dian|Thierry|1987|p=573}}]]\nAshot supported the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]] during his reign.{{sfn|Grousset|2008|p=384}} Ashot saw the possibility of the church merging with the [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox Byzantine Church]], due to the Byzantine Empire's influence in the region,{{sfn|Martin-Hisard|2007|p=237}} and feared that the Byzantine Empire would deny him his claim to the throne. In 862, when the [[Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople]] [[Photios I of Constantinople|Photios I]] attempted to unite the Armenian Church by sending two letters to Catholicos [[Zacharias I of Armenia|Zacharias I]] and Ashot, Zacharias and Ashot summoned a council in Yerazgavors;{{sfn|Grousset|2007|p=383}} the ambiguous response{{sfn|Garso\u00efan|2004|p=147}} was formulated by Ashot.{{sfn|Martin-Hisard|2007|p=237}} Ashot continued to receive epistolary communication; in 882, he received a letter with a [[True Cross]] awarded to Catholicos [[Mashdotz I|Mashtots I]], who was a friend of Ashot (the cross has since been lost).{{sfn|Dorfman-Lazarev|2004|p=85}} Ashot also supported the Armenian Church's desire to separate from the [[Church of Caucasian Albania]].{{sfn| Garso\u00efan|2007|p=244}} Ashot donated several treasures to the Armenian Catholicos to distribute to the churches.{{sfn|Durand|2007|p=198}}\n\n==Family==\n{{main|Bagratuni family tree}}\n{{chart/start}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | PR0|y|PR1 | | PR1 = [[Katranide I]] <br /> [[List of Armenian consorts|Queen of Armenia]]<br />(885-890)| PR0= Ashot the Great<br />[[Prince of Princes]], [[sparapet]]<br /> (855-885)<br />[[Kingdom of Armenia (Bagratid)|king of Armenia]]<br />(885-890)}}\n{{chart| | |,|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.|}}\n{{chart| |PR1 | | |!| | | PR2| | |!| | |PR3| | |!| | |PR4| PR1= [[Smbat I of Armenia|Smbat]]<br />[[Kingdom of Armenia (Bagratid)|king of Armenia]]<br />(890-914)| PR2 = Sahak |PR3= David <br />(\u2020902)|PR4=[[Shapuh sparapet|Shapuh]]<br />[[sparapet]]<br />(\u2020912)}}\n{{