c[https://etherzone.com/antony-sutton-a-giant-departs-not-a-real-human-being/ Antony Sutton: A Giant Departs Not A Real Human Being]\u201d. ''Ether Zone'', 2002. [https://etherzone.com/antony-sutton-a-giant-departs-not-a-real-human-being/ Archived link].\n* Millegan, Kris. \u201c[http://antonysutton.com/sutton-memorial/ In Memoriam: Antony C. Sutton, 1925-2002]\u201d. June 17, 2002. [http://archive.is/AqR8V Archived link].\n* Baron, Alexander. \u201c[http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/326318 Op-Ed: The Life and Work of Antony C. Sutton]\u201d ''Digital Journal'', June 17, 2012. [http://archive.is/EtRUw Archived link].\n\n==Interviews==\n\n* Millegan, Kris. [http://www.antonysutton.com/suttoninterview.html \u201c'W', S&B\u2014and the truth... shall set us free! An interview with Antony C. Sutton, Researcher Emeritus]\u201d. ''Little Red Hen'', July 3, 1999. [http://archive.is/oL7Y6 Archive link].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* [[Arms industry]]\n* [[Federal Reserve]]\n* [[Militarism]]\n* [[Military funding of science]]\n* [[Military\u2013industrial\u2013media complex]]\n* [[Military Keynesianism]]\n* [[Permanent war economy]]\n* [[Politico-media complex]]\n* [[Power elite]]\n* [[Prison\u2013industrial complex]]\n*''[[The Power Elite]]'' by [[C. Wright Mills]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.antonysutton.com/ Antony C. Sutton tribute]\n* [http://www.antonysutton.com/suttoninterview.html 1999 e-mail interview with Sutton]\n* [https://oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/kt287033k0/entire_text/ Overview of the Antony C. Sutton papers]\n* {{WorldCat|id=lccn-n79122365|name=Antony C. Sutton}}\n* [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm5508593/ Antony C. Sutton] at [[IMDb]].\n* {{Find a Grave | id=69081522 | name=Antony C. Sutton }}\n* [http://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n79122365/ Antony C. Sutton] at [[WorldCat]]\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sutton, Antony C.}}\n[[Category:English political scientists]]\n[[Category:English economists]]\n[[Category:English engineers]]\n[[Category:English political writers]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:British investigative journalists]]\n[[Category:Monetary reformers]]\n[[Category:Hoover Institution people]]\n[[Category:California State University, Los Angeles faculty]]\n[[Category:British classical liberals]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Southampton]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Skull and Bones Society]]\n[[Category:American anti-communists]]\n[[Category:20th-century English historians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Primary sources|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Antony C. Sutton\n| image        = Antonysutton.jpg\n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name   = Antony Cyril Sutton\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1925|2|14}}\n| birth_place  = London, United Kingdom\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|2002|6|17|1925|2|14}}\n| death_place  = United States\n| occupation   = Writer\n| alma_mater   = [[University of Southampton]], England\n| nationality  = British and American\n| period       = \n| genre        = Non-fiction\n| subject      = history, economics, politics\n| notableworks = America\u2019s Secret Establishment: An Introduction to the Order of Skull & Bones (1983)\n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| signature    = \n| website      = {{url|antonysutton.com}}\n}}\n'''Antony Cyril Sutton''' (February 14, 1925 \u2013 June 17, 2002) was a British and American economist, historian, professor, and writer.\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in London in 1925, Sutton relocated to California in 1957 and became a U.S. citizen in 1962.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5kFLlFCCQAg|title=National Suicide|work=Interview with Prof. Antony C. Sutton|format=video|year=1973|accessdate=2019-02-19}}</ref> he studied at the universities of [[University of London|London]], [[University of G\u00f6ttingen|G\u00f6ttingen]], and [[University of California|California]] and received his [[D.Sc.]] from the [[University of Southampton]]. Sutton then received an economics professorship at [[California State University, Los Angeles]] and a research fellowship at [[Stanford University|Stanford University's]] [[Hoover Institution|Hoover Institution on War, Revolution, and Peace]] from 1968 to 1973. During his time at the Hoover Institution, he wrote the major study ''Western Technology and Soviet Economic Development'' (in three volumes), arguing that the West played a major role in developing the Soviet Union from its very beginnings up until the then-present year of 1970. Sutton argued that the [[Soviet Union]]'s technological and manufacturing base, which was then engaged in supplying the [[Viet Cong]], was built by United States corporations and largely funded by US taxpayers. Steel and iron plants, the [[GAZ]] automobile factory, a [[Ford]] subsidiary in eastern Russia, and many other Soviet industrial enterprises were built with the help or technical assistance of the United States or US corporations. He argued further that the Soviet Union's acquisition of [[MIRV]] technology was made possible by receiving (from US sources) machining equipment for the manufacture of precision [[ball bearings]], necessary to mass-produce MIRV-enabled missiles. He has contributed articles to Human Events, The Review of the News, Triumph, Ordnance, and many other journals.\n \nIn 1973, Sutton published a popularized, condensed version of the sections of the forthcoming third volume relevant to military technology called ''National Suicide: Military Aid to the Soviet Union'' after which he was forced out of the Hoover Institution.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Millegan (ed.)|first1=Kris|title=Fleshing Out Skull and Bones|date=2004|publisher=Trine Day|location=Walterville, OR|isbn=0-9752906-0-6|page=89}}</ref> His conclusion from his research on the issue was that the conflicts of the Cold War were \"not fought to restrain communism\" but were organised in order \"to generate multibillion-dollar armaments contracts\", since the United States, through financing the Soviet Union \"directly or indirectly armed both sides in at least Korea and Vietnam\" \"<ref name=wh12>Wall Street and the Rise of Hitler, Chapter 12</ref>\n\nThe update to the text, ''The Best Enemy Money Can Buy'', looked at the role of military technology transfers up to the 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j3vZNSAi-QM|title=The Best Enemies Money Can Buy|work=Interview with Prof. Antony C. Sutton|format=video|year=1980|accessdate=2016-08-05}}</ref> Appendix B of that text contained the text of his 1972 testimony before Subcommittee VII of the Platform Committee of the Republican Party in which he summarized the essential aspects of his overall research:\n\n{{quote|In a few words: there is no such thing as Soviet technology. Almost all \u2014 perhaps 90\u201395 percent \u2014 came directly or indirectly from the United States and its allies. In effect the United States and the NATO countries have built the Soviet Union. Its industrial and its military capabilities. This massive construction job has taken 50 years. Since the Revolution in 1917. It has been carried out through trade and the sale of plants, equipment and technical assistance.{{cn|date=May 2019}}}}\n\nSutton's next three published books (''Wall Street and the Bolshevik Revolution'', ''Wall Street and FDR'' and ''Wall Street and the Rise of Hitler'') detailed Wall Street's involvement in the [[Bolshevik]] Revolution to destroy Russia as an economic competitor and turn it into \"a captive market and a technical colony to be exploited by a few high-powered American financiers and the corporations under their control\"<ref>Wall Street and the Bolshevik Revolution, Chapter XI</ref> as well as its decisive contributions to the rise of [[Adolf Hitler]] and [[Franklin Delano Roosevelt]], whose policies he assessed as being essentially the same \"corporate socialism,\" planned by the big corporations.<ref>Wall Street and the Rise of Hitler, Chapter 8</ref> Sutton concluded that it was all part of the economic [[power elite]]s' \"long-range program of nurturing collectivism\"<ref name=wh12/> and fostering \"corporate socialism\" in order to ensure \"monopoly acquisition of wealth\" because it \"would fade away if it were exposed to the activity of a free market.\"<ref>Wall Street and FDR, Chapter 12.</ref>\n\nIn his view, the only solution to prevent such abuse in the future was that \"a majority of individuals declares or acts as if it wants nothing from government, declares it will look after its own welfare and interests\" or, specifically, if \"a majority finds the moral courage and the internal fortitude to reject the something-for-nothing con game and replace it by voluntary associations, voluntary communes, or local rule and decentralized societies.\"<ref name=wh12/> In the\n\nIn the early 1980s, Sutton used a combination of public-domain information on [[Skull and Bones]] (such as Yale yearbooks) and previously unreleased documents sent to him by [[Charlotte Thomson Iserbyt]] whose father was a Skull and Bones member to write ''America's Secret Establishment: An Introduction to the Order of Skull and Bones'', which, according to Sutton, was his most important work.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Sutton|first1=Anthony C.|title=America's Secret Establishment:An Introduction to the Order of Skull & Bones|date=1983|publisher=TrineDay|isbn=0972020748|page=Author's Preface|url=https://archive.org/details/AmericasSecretEstablishmentOrderOfSkullbones|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn his book ''Between Two Ages: America's Role in the Technetronic Era'' (New York: Viking Press; 1970),{{page needed|date=August 2019}} [[Zbigniew Brzezinski]] wrote:\n<blockquote>For impressive evidence of Western participation in the early phase of Soviet economic growth, see Antony C. Sutton's ''Western Technology and Soviet Economic Development: 1917\u20131930'', which argues that 'Soviet economic development for 1917\u20131930 was essentially dependent on Western technological aid' (p.283), and that 'at least 95 per cent of the industrial structure received this assistance.' (p. 348).</blockquote>\n\nProfessor [[Richard Pipes]], of [[Harvard University|Harvard]], said in his book, ''Survival Is Not Enough: Soviet Realities and America's Future'' (Simon & Schuster; 1984){{page needed|date=August 2019}}: \n<blockquote>In his three-volume detailed account of Soviet Purchases of Western Equipment and Technology&nbsp;... Sutton comes to conclusions that are uncomfortable for many businessmen and economists. For this reason his work tends to be either dismissed out of hand as 'extreme' or, more often, simply ignored. (p. 290)</blockquote>\n\nThe description on the back flap of the dust jacket of Sutton's 1976 book by \u201876 Press, ''Wall Street and the Rise of Hitler'', reveals that Sutton was then working on a forthcoming two-part study of the Federal Reserve System and the ''War on Gold'' to be published by \u201876 Press in 1977. When ''The War on Gold'' was released the following year in 1977, the dust jacket description announced the follow-up book, ''The Paper Factory'', would be published in 1978, but this book was never released.\n\nArchive footage of Sutton was used in the 2014 documentary, ''JFK to 9/11: Everything Is a Rich Man's Trick''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Full Cast & Crew |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4798606/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm |website=IMDb |accessdate=3 May 2019 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nThe Hoover Institution Archives house four boxes of Sutton\u2019s personal papers from 1920 to 1972. The collection includes writings, clippings, letters, and notes related to the outbreak of wars, civil wars, revolutions and other violent conflicts around the globe from 1820 to 1970. There is a particular emphasis on the life and career of American entrepreneur [[Armand Hammer]], especially as relates to his business investments in the Soviet Union.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sutton |first1=Antony |title=Papers, 1920-1972. |oclc=122385247 }}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n*[[University of Southampton]], [[D.Sc.]] in [[Southampton]], [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n*[[University of G\u00f6ttingen]] in [[G\u00f6ttingen]], [[Lower Saxony]], [[Germany]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Wall Street and the Rise of Hitler|last=Sutton|first=Antony|publisher=\u201876 Press|year=1976|isbn=0892450045|edition=1st|location=Seal Beach, CA|pages=Jacket|quote=Antony C. Sutton was educated at the universities of London, G\u00f6ttingen, and California.|url=https://archive.org/details/wallstreetrise00sutt}}</ref>\n*[[University of California, Los Angeles]] in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States of America]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Employment ==\n*Economics Professor at California State University Los Angeles\n*[[Research Fellow]] at the [[Hoover Institution|Hoover Institution on War, Revolution and Peace]] at [[Stanford University]], 1968 to 1973.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Articles===\n* [https://doi.org/10.1080/0031322X.1979.9969533 \u201cLetters to the Editor\u201d]. ''[[Patterns of Prejudice]]'', Vol. 13, No. 4, 1979. p. 37 {{issn|0031-322X}} {{doi|10.1080/0031322X.1979.9969533}}\n* Memoir Concerning Events at the Hoover Institution, Stanford University in the Period 1968-1974 (Relating to Suppression of Information by Washington, D.C.). February 1996.\n* \u201cThe September 11th Attack, the War on Terror, and the Order of Skull & Bones\u201d. June 2002.\n\n===Books===\n\n[[File:The War on Gold, by Antony C. Sutton (\u201876 Press, 1976).jpg|thumb|Sutton\u2019s 1976 study of \u201cthe past, present, and future of the metal that Keynesian economists and political schemers have denounced as a \u2018barbaric relic.\u2019\u201d<ref name=\":0\">Sutton, Antony C.''The War on Gold''. Seal Beach, California: [['76 Press]], 1976. {{ISBN|0892450088}}. 238 pages.</ref>]]\n\n*''[https://archive.org/details/Sutton--Western-Technology-1917-1930 Western Technology and Soviet Economic Development: 1917\u20131930]''. Stanford, California: [[Hoover Institution]], 1968. {{ISBN|978-0817917913}}\n*''[https://archive.org/details/Sutton--Western-Technology-1930-1945 Western Technology and Soviet Economic Development: 1930\u20131945]''. Stanford, California: Hoover Institution, 1971.\n*''[https://archive.org/details/Sutton--Western-Technology-1945-1965 Western Technology and Soviet Economic Development: 1945\u20131965]''. Stanford, California: Hoover Institution, 1973. {{ISBN|978-0817911317}}. 482 pages.\n*[https://archive.org/download/NationalSuicide1973/national%20suicide%20%281973%29.pdf ''National Suicide: Military Aid to the Soviet Union'']. New Rochelle, New York: [[Arlington House Publishers|Arlington House]], 1973.\n*''What Is Libertarianism?''. Cayman Press, 1973.\n*''Wars and Revolutions, Part One: 1820 to 1900.'' 1973.\n*''Wars and Revolutions, Part Two: 1900 to 1972.'' 1973. \n*''[https://archive.org/download/pdfy-L83jbkzuI6b1FZ2y/Sutton%20-%20Wall%20Street%20and%20the%20Bolshevik%20Revolution%20%281974%29.PDF Wall Street and the Bolshevik Revolution]''. New Rochelle, New York: [[Arlington House Publishers|Arlington House]], 1974. {{ISBN|978-0870002762}} \n** [https://archive.org/download/WallStreetAndTheBolshevikRevolutionRussian/Wall%20Street%20and%20the%20Bolshevik%20Revolution%20%5BRussian%5D.pdf Russian translation available].\n*''[https://archive.org/download/pdfy-FPUkz4pezsfsrVfZ/Antony%20Sutton%20-%20Wall%20Street%20and%20FDR%20%281975%29.pdf Wall Street and FDR]''. New Rochelle, New York: [[Arlington House Publishers|Arlington House]], 1975. {{ISBN|978-0870003288}}. 200 pages.\n*''[https://archive.org/download/WallStreetAndTheRiseOfHitler_20190321/Wall%20Street%20and%20the%20Rise%20of