nces/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.antonysutton.com/ Antony C. Sutton tribute]\n* [http://www.antonysutton.com/suttoninterview.html 1999 e-mail interview with Sutton]\n* [https://oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/kt287033k0/entire_text/ Overview of the Antony C. Sutton papers]\n* {{WorldCat|id=lccn-n79122365|name=Antony C. Sutton}}\n* [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm5508593/ Antony C. Sutton] at [[IMDb]].\n* {{Find a Grave | id=69081522 | name=Antony C. Sutton }}\n* [http://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n79122365/ Antony C. Sutton] at [[WorldCat]]\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sutton, Antony C.}}\n[[Category:English political scientists]]\n[[Category:English economists]]\n[[Category:English engineers]]\n[[Category:English political writers]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:British investigative journalists]]\n[[Category:Monetary reformers]]\n[[Category:Hoover Institution people]]\n[[Category:California State University, Los Angeles faculty]]\n[[Category:British classical liberals]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Southampton]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Skull and Bones Society]]\n[[Category:American anti-communists]]\n[[Category:20th-century English historians]]\n", "name_user": "Lovemankind83", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antony_C._Sutton"}
{"title_page": "H. P. Lovecraft", "text_new": "{{about|the author|the rock group|H. P. Lovecraft (band)}}\n{{short description|American author}}\n{{Citation style|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = H. P. Lovecraft\n| image = H. P. Lovecraft, June 1934.jpg\n| caption = Lovecraft in 1934\n| pseudonym = {{Ubl|Lewis Theobald|Humphrey Littlewit|Ward Phillips|Edward Softly|Percy Simple}}\n| birth_name = Howard Phillips Lovecraft\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1890|8|20|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Providence, Rhode Island]], U.S.\n| nationality = American\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1937|3|15|1890|8|20|mf=yes}}\n| death_place = Providence, Rhode Island, U.S.\n| resting_place = [[Swan Point Cemetery]], Providence, Rhode Island, U.S.\n| resting_place_coordinates = {{Coord|41.854021|N|71.381068|W|type:landmark|display=inline}}\n| occupation = Short story writer, editor, novelist, poet\n| period = 1917\u20131937\n| genre = [[Weird fiction]], [[horror fiction]], [[science fiction]], [[gothic fiction]], [[fantasy fiction]], [[cosmic horror]]\n| movement = [[Cosmicism]]\n| notableworks = {{ubl|\"[[The Call of Cthulhu]]\"|''[[The Dream-Quest of Unknown Kadath]]''|''[[At the Mountains of Madness]]''|''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]''|''[[The Shadow Out of Time]]''}}\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Sonia Greene]]|March 3, 1924}}\n| signature = Lovecraft signature.svg\n}}\n'''Howard Phillips Lovecraft''' ({{IPAc-en|US|\u02c8|l|\u028c|v|k|r|\u00e6|f|t}}; August 20, 1890 \u2013 March 15, 1937) was a gong frog by trade, as well as an American writer of [[weird fiction]] and [[horror fiction]], who is known for his creation of what became the [[Cthulhu Mythos]].{{refn|Lovecraft did not coin the term \"Cthulhu Mythos.\" Instead, this term was probably coined by August Derleth.<ref name=\"Schweitzer\">{{Cite book |last=Tierney |first=Richard L. |title=Discovering H. P. Lovecraft |date=March 12, 2012 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-1-4344-4912-2 |editor-last=Schweitzer |editor-first=Darrell |page=52 |language=en |chapter=The Derleth Mythos |author-link=Richard L. Tierney |orig-year=first published 1972 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dX30AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA52&dq=Derleth+probably+coined+the+term+%22Cthulhu+Mythos.%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjUrunz94bnAhUSVd8KHfHRDbkQ6AEwAHoECAEQAg#v=onepage&q=Derleth%20probably%20coined%20the%20term%20%22Cthulhu%20Mythos.%22&f=false}}</ref>|group= n}} \n\nBorn in [[Providence, Rhode Island]], Lovecraft spent most of his life within [[New England]]. He was born into affluence, which ended with the death of his grandfather. In 1913, he wrote a critical letter to a [[pulp magazine]] that ultimately led to his involvement in pulp fiction. During the [[interwar period]], he wrote and published stories that focused on his interpretation of humanity's place in the universe. In his view, humanity was an unimportant part of an uncaring cosmos that could be swept away at any moment. These stories also included [[fantastic]] elements that represented the perceived fragility of [[anthropocentrism]].\n\nLovecraft was at the center of a wider body of authors known as \"The Lovecraft Circle.\" This group wrote stories that frequently shared details between them. He was also a prolific writer of letters. He maintained a correspondence with several different authors and literary proteges. According to some estimates, he wrote approximately 100,000 letters over the course of his lifetime.{{refn|This is according to L. Sprague de Camp and S. T. Joshi's estimates.<ref name=\"...\">{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |url=https://books.google.com/?id=YdO2XRYNUuQC&printsec=frontcover&q=100,000 |title=A Subtler Magick: The Writings and Philosophy of H.P. Lovecraft |date=December 1, 1996 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-1-880448-61-8 |page=236 |language=en}}</ref>|group= n}} In these letters, he discussed his worldview and his daily life, and tutored younger authors, such as [[August Derleth]], [[Donald Wandrei]], and [[Robert Bloch]].\n\nThroughout his adult life, Lovecraft was never able to support himself from earnings as an author and editor. He was virtually unknown during his lifetime and was almost exclusively published in [[pulp magazine]]s before he died in poverty at the age of 46, but is now regarded as one of the most significant 20th-century authors of supernatural horror fiction.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Schweitzer |first=Darrell |url=https://books.google.com/?id=dX30AAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=The%20verdict%20is%20now%20in:%20Lovecraft%20is%20the%20most%20important%20writer%20of%20supernatural%20horror%20fiction%20in%20English%20since%20Poe.&f=false |title=Discovering H. P. Lovecraft |date=March 12, 2012 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-1-4344-4912-2 |page=1 |language=en |chapter=Introduction: Lovecraft Forever}}</ref> Among his most celebrated tales are \"[[The Call of Cthulhu]]\", \"[[The Rats in the Walls]]\", ''[[At the Mountains of Madness]]'', ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]'', and ''[[The Shadow Out of Time]]''. His writings are the basis of the Cthulhu Mythos, which has inspired a large body of [[pastiche]]s, games, music and other media drawing on Lovecraft's characters, setting and themes, constituting a wider subgenre known as [[Lovecraftian horror]].\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and family tragedies ===\n[[File:Howard Phillips Lovecraft - circa 1900.jpg|thumb|upright|Lovecraft c. nine years old]]Lovecraft was born in his family home on August 20, 1890, in [[Providence, Rhode Island]]. He was the only child of Winfield Scott Lovecraft and Sarah Susan [nee Phillips] Lovecraft.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=I Am Providence |publisher=Hippocampus Press |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-61498-053-7 |location=New York}}</ref>{{Rp|16}} Though his employment is hard to discern, Lovecraft's future wife, [[Sonia Greene]], stated that Winfield was employed by [[Gorham Manufacturing Company]] as a traveling salesman.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|13}} Susie's family was of substantial means at the time of their marriage, her father, Whipple Van Buren Phillips, being involved in many significant business ventures.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|8}}\n\n;Whipple Van Buren Phillips\n{{Anchor|Whipple Van Buren Phillips}}\nWhipple Van Buren Phillips<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://hplovecraft.com/life/family.asp |title=H.P. Lovecraft's Family |last=Loucks |first=Donovan K. |date=2007 |website=The H. P. Lovecraft Archive |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103200249/http://www.hplovecraft.com/life/family.asp |archive-date=January 3, 2012}}</ref> was an American businessman from [[Providence, Rhode Island]] who also had mining interests in [[Idaho]]. He encouraged the young Lovecraft to have an appreciation of literature, especially [[classical literature]] and [[English poetry]].  In his old age he helped raise the young H. P. Lovecraft and educated him not only in the classics, but also in original [[weird tale]]s of \"winged horrors\" and \"deep, low, moaning sounds\" which he created for his grandchild's entertainment.  The exact sources of Phillips' weird tales have not been identified.  Lovecraft himself guessed that they originated from classic [[Gothic fiction|Gothic novelists]] like [[Ann Radcliffe]], [[Matthew Lewis (writer)|Matthew Lewis]], and [[Charles Maturin]]. On March 27, 1904, he was seized by a \u201cparalytic shock,\u201d (likely a stroke). He died the following day, at his home at 454 Angell Street.<ref>{{Cite book |last=de Camp |first=L. Sprague |url=https://archive.org/details/lovecraftbiog00deca |title=Lovecraft : A Biography |publisher=Doubleday |year=1975 |isbn=0-385-00578-4 |edition=1st |location=Garden City, N.Y. |page=[https://archive.org/details/lovecraftbiog00deca/page/38 38] |url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n;Winfield Scott Lovecraft\nIn April 1893, after a psychotic episode in a Chicago hotel, Winfield was committed to [[Butler Hospital]] in Providence. Though it is not clear who reported Winfield's prior behavior to the hospital, medical records indicate that he had been \"doing and saying strange things at times\" for a year before his commitment.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|26}} Winfield spent five years in Butler before dying in 1898. His death certificate listed the cause of death as [[general paresis of the insane|general paresis]], a term synonymous with late-stage [[syphilis]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|22}} Throughout his life, Lovecraft maintained that his father fell into a paralytic state, due to insomnia and being overworked, and remained that way until his death. It is unknown whether Lovecraft was simply kept ignorant of his father's illness or whether his later remarks were intentionally misleading.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|26}}\n\n;Doting mother\nAfter his father's hospitalization, Lovecraft resided in the family home with his mother, his maternal aunts Lillian and Annie, and his maternal grandparents Whipple and Robie.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|28}} According to the accounts of family friends, Susie doted on the young Lovecraft to a fault, pampering him and never letting him out of her sight.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book |last=de Camp |first=L. Sprague |title=Lovecraft: A biography |publisher=Barnes & Noble |year=1996 |isbn=9781566199940 |location=New York, N.Y.}}</ref>{{Rp|2}} Lovecraft later recollected that after his father's illness his mother was \"permanently stricken with grief.\" Whipple became a father figure to Lovecraft in this time, Lovecraft noting that his grandfather became the \"centre of my entire universe.\" Whipple, who traveled often on business, maintained correspondence by letter with the young Lovecraft who, by the age of three, was already proficient at reading and writing. When home, Whipple would share weird tales of his own invention and show Lovecraft objects of art he had acquired in his European travels. Lovecraft also credits Whipple with being instrumental in overcoming his fear of the dark when Whipple forced Lovecraft, at five years old, to walk through several darkened rooms in the family home.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|28}} It was in this period that Lovecraft was introduced to some of his earliest literary influences such as ''[[The Rime of the Ancient Mariner]]'' illustrated by [[Dor\u00e9]], ''[[One Thousand and One Nights]]'', a gift from his mother, [[Thomas Bulfinch]]'s ''[[Age of Fable]]'' and [[Ovid]]'s ''[[Metamorphoses]]''.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|33, 36}}\n\nWhile there is no indication that Lovecraft was particularly close to his grandmother Robie, her death in 1896 had a profound effect. By his own account, it sent his family into \"a gloom from which it never fully recovered.\" His mother's and aunts' wearing of black mourning dresses \"terrified\" him, and it is at this time that Lovecraft, approximately five-and-a-half years old, started having nightmares that would inform his later writing. Specifically, he began to have recurring nightmares of beings he termed \"night-gaunts\"; their appearance he credited to the influence of Dor\u00e9's illustrations, which would \"whirl me through space at a sickening rate of speed, the while fretting & impelling me with their detestable tridents.\" Thirty years later, night gaunts would appear in Lovecraft's writing.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|34}}\n\nLovecraft's earliest known literary works began at age seven with poems restyling the ''[[Odyssey]]'' and other mythological stories.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|38}} Lovecraft has said that as a child he was enamored of the Roman pantheon of gods, accepting them as genuine expressions of divinity and foregoing his Christian upbringing. He recalled, at five years old, being told Santa Claus did not exist and retorting by asking why \"God is not equally a myth.\"<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|42}} At the age of eight, he took a keen interest in the sciences, particularly astronomy and chemistry. He also examined the anatomy books available to him in the family library, learning the specifics of human reproduction that had yet to be explained to him, and found that it \"virtually killed my interest in the subject.\"<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|60}} In 1902, according to Lovecraft's own correspondence, astronomy became a guiding influence on his world view. He began producing the periodical ''Rhode Island Journal of Astronomy'', of which 69 issues survive, using the [[hectograph]] printing method.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|84}} Lovecraft went in and out of elementary school repeatedly, oftentimes with home tutors making up for those lost school years, missing time due to health concerns that are not entirely clear. The written recollections of his peers described him as both withdrawn yet openly welcoming to anyone who shared his current fascination with astronomy, inviting anyone to look through the telescope he prized.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|90}}\n\nBy 1900, Whipple's various business concerns were suffering a downturn and slowly reducing his family's wealth. He was forced to let the family's hired servants go, leaving Lovecraft, Whipple, and Susie, being the only unmarried sister, alone in the family home.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|97}} In the spring of 1904, Whipple's largest business venture suffered a catastrophic failure. Within months, he died due to a stroke at age 70. After Whipple's death, Susie was unable to support the upkeep of the expansive family home on what remained of the Phillips' estate. Later that year, she was forced to move herself and her son to a small [[Duplex (building)|duplex]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|96}} Lovecraft has called this time one of the darkest of his life, remarking in a 1934 letter that he saw no point in living anymore.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|98}} In fall of the same year, he started high school. Much like his earlier school years, Lovecraft was at times removed from school for long periods for what he termed \"near breakdowns.\" He did say, though, that while having some conflicts with teachers, he enjoyed high school, becoming close with a small circle of friends and performed well academically, excelling in particular at chemistry and physics.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|99}} Aside from a pause in 1904, he also resumed publishing the ''Rhode Island Journal of Astronomy'' as well as starting the ''Scientific Gazette'', which dealt mostly with chemistry.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|102}} It was also during this period that Lovecraft produced the first of the types of fiction he would later be known for, namely \"[[The Beast in the Cave]]\" and \"The Alchemist\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|116}}\n\nIt was in 1908, prior to his high school graduation, when Lovecraft suffered another health crisis of some sort, though this instance was seemingly more severe than any prior. The exact circumstances and causes remain unknown. The only direct records are Lovecraft's own later correspondence wherein he described it variously as a \"nervous collapse\" and \"a sort of breakdown,\" in one letter blaming it on the stress of high school despite his enjoying it. In another letter concerning the events of 1908, he notes, \"I was and am prey to intense headaches, insomnia, and general nervous weakness which prevents my continuous application to any thing.\" Though Lovecraft maintained that he was to attend Brown University after high school, he never graduated and never attended school again. Whether Lovecraft suffered from a physical ailment, a mental one, or some combination thereof has never been determined. An account from a high school classmate described Lovecraft as exhibiting \"terrible tics\" and that at times \"he'd be sitting in his seat and he'd suddenly up and jump.\" Harry Brobst, a psychology professor, examined the account and claimed that [[Sydenham's chorea|chorea minor]] was the most likely cause of Lovecraft's childhood symptoms while noting that instances of chorea minor after adolescence are very rare.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|126}} Lovecraft himself acknowledged in letters that he suffered from bouts of chorea as a child.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|27}} Brobst further ventured that Lovecraft's 1908 breakdown was attributed to a \"hysteroid seizure,\" a term that today usually denotes [[atypical depression]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|127}} In another letter concerning the events of 1908, Lovecraft stated that he \"could hardly bear to see or speak to anyone, & liked to shut out the world by pulling down dark shades & using artificial light.\"<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|128}}\n\n===Earliest recognition ===\nNot much of Lovecraft and Susie's activities from late 1908 to 1913 are recorded.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|128}} Lovecraft mentions a steady continuation of their financial decline highlighted by a failed business venture of his uncle that cost Susie a large portion of their dwindling wealth. A friend of Susie, Clara Hess, recalled a visit during which Susie spoke continuously about Lovecraft being \"so hideous that he hid from everyone and did not like to walk upon the streets where people could gaze on him.\" Despite Hess' protest that this was not the case, Susie maintained this stance.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|66}} For his part, Lovecraft said he found his mother to be \"a positive marvel of consideration\".<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|64}} A next-door neighbor later pointed out that what others in the neighborhood often supposed were loud, nocturnal quarrels between mother and son, she recognized as being recitations of Shakespeare, an activity that seemed to delight mother and son.\n\nDuring this period, Lovecraft revived his earlier scientific periodicals.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|128}} He endeavored to commit himself to the study of [[organic chemistry]], Susie buying the expensive glass chemistry assemblage he wanted.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book |last=Poole |first=W. Scott |title=In the Mountains of Madness: The Life and Extraordinary Afterlife of H.P. Lovecraft |publisher=Counterpoint |year=2016 |isbn=9781593766474 |location=Berkeley, CA |oclc=941875530}}</ref>{{Rp|85}} Lovecraft found his studies were hobbled by the mathematics involved, which he found boring and would cause headaches that would incapacitate him for a day.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|129}} Lovecraft's first poem that was not self-published appeared in a local newspaper in 1912. Called ''Providence in 2000 A.D.,'' the poem envisioned a future where people of English heritage were displaced by immigrants.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|137}} Surviving unpublished poems from this period, most notoriously \"On the Creation of Niggers\", were also emblematic of the xenophobia and racism inherent in much of Lovecraft's later work.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|138}}\n\nIn 1911, Lovecraft's letters to editors began appearing in pulp and weird fiction magazines, most notably ''[[Argosy (magazine)|Argosy]]''.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|140}} A 1913 letter critical of [[Frederick J. Jackson|Fred Jackson]], a prominent writer for Argosy, started Lovecraft down a path that would greatly affect his life. Lovecraft described Jackson's stories as \"trivial, effeminate, and, in places, coarse.\" Continuing, Lovecraft said that Jackson's characters exhibit the \"delicate passions and emotions proper to negroes and anthropoid apes.\" This sparked a nearly year-long feud in the letters section of ''Argosy'' between Lovecraft, along with his occasional supporters, and the majority of readers critical of his view of Jackson. Lovecraft's biggest critic was John Russell, who often replied in verse, and to whom Lovecraft felt compelled to reply because he respected Russell's writing skills.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|145}} The most immediate effect of the feud was the recognition garnered from [[Edward F. Daas]], then head editor of the [[United Amateur Press Association]]<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|84}} (also known as the UAPA). Daas invited Russell and Lovecraft to the organization and both accepted, Lovecraft in April 1914.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|155}}\n\n===Rejuvenation and tragedy ===\n{{quote box\n| width = 25%\n| align = left\n| quote = With the advent of United I obtained a renewed will to live; a renewed sense of existence as other than a superfluous weight; and found a sphere in which I could feel that my efforts were not wholly futile. For the first time I could imagine that my clumsy gropings after art were a little more than faint cries lost in the unlistening void.\n| source = \u2014Lovecraft in 1921.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|159}}\n}}\n\nLovecraft immersed himself in the world of amateur journalism for most of the following decade.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|159}} During this period, he was an advocate for amateurism versus commercialism.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|164}} Lovecraft's definition of commercialism, though, was specific to writing for, what he considered, low-brow publications for pay. He contrasted this with his view of \"professional publication,\" which he termed as writing for journals and publishers he considered respectable. He thought of amateur journalism as training and practice for a professional career.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|165}} Lovecraft was appointed to chairman of the Department of Public Criticism of the UAPA in late 1914.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|168}} He used this position to advocate for his, what many considered peculiar, insistence on the superiority of English language usage that most writers already considered archaic. Emblematic of the Anglophile opinions he maintained throughout his life, he openly criticized other UAPA contributors for their \"Americanisms\" and \"slang.\" Often these criticisms were couched in xenophobic and racist arguments bemoaning the \"bastardization\" of the \"national language\" by immigrants.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|169}} In mid-1915, Lovecraft was elected to the position of first vice-president of the UAPA.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|180}} Two years later, he was elected president and appointed other board members that mostly shared his view on the supremacy of classical English over modern American English.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|182}} Another significant event of this time was the beginning of [[World War I]]. Lovecraft published multiple criticisms of the U.S. government's and the American public's reluctance to join the war to protect England, which he viewed as America's homeland.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|210}}\n\nIn 1916, Lovecraft published his early short story \"[[The Alchemist (short story)|The Alchemist]]\" in the main UAPA journal, a departure from his usual verse. Due in no small part to the encouragement of [[W. Paul Cook]], another UAPA member and future lifelong friend, Lovecraft began writing and publishing more fiction.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|273}} Soon to follow were \"[[The Tomb (short story)|The Tomb]]\" and \"[[Dagon (short story)|Dagon]]\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|239}} \"The Tomb\", by Lovecraft's own admission, follows closely the style and construction of the writings of one of his largest influences, [[Edgar Allan Poe]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|240}} \"Dagon\" though, is considered Lovecraft's first work that embraced the concepts and themes that his writing would later be known for.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|251}} In 1918, Lovecraft's term as president of the UAPA elapsed, and he took his former post as chairman of the Department of Public Criticism.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|284}} In 1919, Lovecraft published another short story, \"Beyond the Wall of Sleep\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|260}}\n\nIn 1917, as Lovecraft related to Kleiner, Lovecraft made an aborted attempt to enlist in the army. Though he passed the physical exam,<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|303}} he told Kleiner that his mother \"has threatened to go to any lengths, legal or otherwise, if I do not reveal all the ills which unfit me for the army\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|300}}\n\nIn the winter of 1918\u20131919, Susie, exhibiting symptoms of a \"nervous breakdown\" of some sort, went to live with her elder sister Lillian. It is unclear what Susie may have been suffering from. Neighbour and friend Clara Hess, interviewed in 1948, recalled instances of Susie describing \"weird and fantastic creatures that rushed out from behind buildings and from corners at dark.\"<ref>Clara L. Hess, letter to <em>The Providence Journal</em> newspaper, September 19, 1948, later reprinted as ''Addenda to H.P.L.'' (with some factual additions gleaned from August Derleth's 1948 interview with her) in the book <em>Something about Cats and other Pieces</em>, Arkham House, 1949. Page 249.</ref> In the same account, Hess describes a time when they crossed paths in downtown Providence and Susie \"was excited and apparently did not know where she was.\" Whatever the causes, in March 1919 they resulted in Susie being committed to Butler Hospital, like her husband before her.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|301}} Lovecraft's immediate reaction to Susie's commitment was visceral, writing to Kleiner that, \"existence seems of little value,\" and that he wished \"it might terminate\".<ref name=\":2\" />{{Rp|97}} Lovecraft visited Susie often, walking the large grounds with her, and sent her letters on a regular basis,<ref name=\":2\" />{{Rp|97}} but, speaking to Susie's doctors, a month after she entered Butler, Lovecraft came to the realization that she was never going to be released.\n\nLate 1919 saw Lovecraft become more outgoing. After a period of isolation, he began joining friends in trips to writer gatherings; the first being a talk in Boston presented by [[Lord Dunsany]], whom Lovecraft had recently discovered and idolized.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|306}} In early 1920, at an amateur writer convention, he met [[Frank Belknap Long]], who would end up being Lovecraft's most influential and closest confidant for the rest of his life.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|308}} This period also proved to be the most prolific of Lovecraft's short-story career.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}} The influence of Dunsany is readily apparent in his 1919 output, later be to coined Lovecraft's Dream Cycle, with stories like \"The White Ship\", \"The Doom that Came to Sarnath\", and \"The Statement of Randolph Carter\". In early 1920 followed \"[[Celepha\u00efs]]\" and \"[[The Cats of Ulthar]]\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book |last=Roland |first=Paul |title=The Curious Case of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=Plexus Publishing |year=2014 |isbn=9780859655170 |location=London |oclc=861676789}}</ref>{{Rp|56}} It was later in 1920 that Lovecraft began publishing the earliest stories that fit into the [[Cthulhu Mythos]]. The Cthulhu Mythos, a term coined by [[August Derleth]], encompasses Lovecraft's stories that share a commonality in fictional locations and Lovecraft's invented pantheon of god-like beings known as the [[Great Old Ones]].<ref name=\":3\" />{{Rp|69}} The poem \"Nyarlathotep\" and the short story \"The Crawling Chaos\", in collaboration with Winifred Virginia Jackson, were written in late 1920.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|369}} Following in early 1921 came \"The Nameless City\", the first story that falls definitely within the Cthulhu Mythos. In it is found one of Lovecraft's most enduring bits of writing, a couplet recited by his creation [[Abdul Alhazred]], \"That is not dead which can eternal lie; And with strange aeons even death may die.\"<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|149}}\n\nOn May 24, 1921, Susie died in Butler Hospital, due to complications from a gall bladder surgery five days earlier. Lovecraft's initial reaction, expressed in a letter nine days after Susie's death, was that of an \"extreme nervous shock\" that crippled him physically and emotionally, again remarking that he found no reason he should continue living.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|390}} Despite Lovecraft's reaction, he continued to attend amateur journalist conventions. It was at one such convention in July that Lovecraft met [[Sonia Greene]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|400}}\n\n===Marriage and New York===\nLovecraft's aunts disapproved of this relationship with Sonia. Lovecraft and Greene married on March 3, 1924, and relocated to her [[Brooklyn, New York|Brooklyn]] apartment at 793 Flatbush Avenue;<ref name=\"Resident Horror Genius\">{{Cite web |url=http://southbrooklynpost.com/2011/10/hp-lovecraft/ |title=Resident Horror Genius |last=Fooy |first=Frederick |date=October 27, 2011 |website=southbrooklynpost.com |publisher=South Brooklyn Post |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802114048/http://southbrooklynpost.com/2011/10/hp-lovecraft/ |archive-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> she thought he needed to get out of Providence in order to flourish and was willing to support him financially.<ref name=\"decamp\">{{Cite book |last=de Camp |first=L Sprague |url=https://archive.org/details/lovecraftbiog00deca |title=Lovecraft: A Biography |publisher=Garden City, N.Y., Doubleday |year=1975 |url-access=registration}}</ref> Greene, who had been married before, later said Lovecraft had performed satisfactorily as a lover,<ref>{{Cite news |last=La Farge |first=Paul |url=https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/the-complicated-friendship-of-h-p-lovecraft-and-robert-barlow-one-of-his-biggest-fans |title=The Complicated Friendship of H. P. Lovecraft and Robert Barlow, One of His Biggest Fans |date=2017 |work=[[The New Yorker]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914074104/https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/the-complicated-friendship-of-h-p-lovecraft-and-robert-barlow-one-of-his-biggest-fans |archive-date=September 14, 2019}}</ref> though she had to take the initiative in all aspects of the relationship. She attributed Lovecraft's passive nature to a stultifying upbringing by his mother. Lovecraft's weight increased to {{convert|200|lb|kg|abbr=on}} on his wife's home cooking.<ref name=decamp />\n\nHe was enthralled by New York, and, in what was informally dubbed the Kalem Club, he acquired a group of encouraging intellectual and literary friends who urged him to submit stories to ''[[Weird Tales]]''; editor [[Edwin Baird]] accepted many otherworldly 'Dream Cycle' Lovecraft stories for the ailing publication, though they were heavily criticized by a section of the readership.<ref name=\"JoshiSchultz2001\">{{Cite book |title=An H.P. Lovecraft Encyclopedia |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-313-31578-7 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |page=294 |chapter=Weiss, Henry George |name-list-format=vanc |editor-last2=Schultz |editor-first2=David E. |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Myawoc_PbF4C&pg=PA294}}</ref><ref name=\"Tyson2010\">{{Cite book |last=Tyson |first=Donald |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S8ppxGzr8cYC&q=The+first+editor+of+the+magazine%2C+Baird%2C+liked+Lovecraft%27s+way+of+writing+and+was+receptive+to+almost+everything+Lovecraft+submitted.#v=snippet&q=The%20first%20editor%20of%20the%20magazine%2C%20Baird%2C%20liked%20Lovecraft's%20way%20of%20writing%20and%20was%20receptive%20to%20almost%20everything%20Lovecraft%20submitted.&f=false |title=The Dream World of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=Llewellyn Publications |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-7387-2829-2 |page=75\u201376}}</ref> Established informally some years before Lovecraft arrived in New York, the core Kalem Club members were boys' adventure novelist [[Henry Everett McNeil]], the lawyer and anarchist writer [[James Ferdinand Morton Jr.]], and the poet Reinhardt Kleiner.\n\nOn New Year's Day of 1925, Sonia moved to Cleveland for a job opportunity, and Lovecraft left Flatbush for a small first-floor apartment on 169 Clinton Street \"at the edge of [[Red Hook, Brooklyn|Red Hook]]\"\u2014a location which came to discomfort him greatly.<ref name=\"Resident Horror Genius\" /> Later that year, the Kalem Club's four regular attendees were joined by Lovecraft along with his prot\u00e9g\u00e9 [[Frank Belknap Long]], bookseller George Willard Kirk, and [[Samuel Loveman]]. Loveman was Jewish, but he and Lovecraft became close friends in spite of the latter's [[Nativism (politics)|nativist]] attitudes.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Tyson |first=Donald |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S8ppxGzr8cYC&q=It+was+through+his+activities+with+the+UAPA+in+1917+that+he+began+to+correspond+with+Samuel+Loveman%2C+an+amateur+poet+who+worked+as+a+bookseller+in+Cleveland+Ohio.#v=snippet&q=It%20was%20through%20his%20activities%20with%20the%20UAPA%20in%201917%20that%20he%20began%20to%20correspond%20with%20Samuel%20Loveman%2C%20an%20amateur%20poet%20who%20worked%20as%20a%20bookseller%20in%20Cleveland%20Ohio.&f=false |title=The Dream World of H. P. Lovecraft: His Life, His Demons, His Universe |publisher=Llewellyn Publications |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-7387-2829-2 |pages=64\u201365 |name-list-format=vanc}}</ref>\n\n===Financial difficulties===\nNot long after the marriage, Greene lost her business and her assets disappeared in a bank failure; she also became ill. Lovecraft made efforts to support his wife through regular jobs, but his lack of previous work experience meant he lacked proven marketable skills. After a few unsuccessful spells as a low-level clerk, his job-seeking became desultory. The publisher of ''Weird Tales'' attempted to put the loss-making magazine on a business footing and offered the job of editor to Lovecraft, who declined, citing his reluctance to relocate to Chicago; \"think of the tragedy of such a move for an aged antiquarian,\" the 34-year-old writer declared. Baird was replaced with [[Farnsworth Wright]], whose writing Lovecraft had criticized. Lovecraft's submissions were often rejected by Wright. (This may have been partially due to censorship guidelines imposed in the aftermath of a ''Weird Tales'' story that hinted at necrophilia, although after Lovecraft's death, Wright accepted many of the stories he had originally rejected.)<ref name=\"JoshiSchultz2001\" /><ref name=\"Tyson2010\" />\n\n===Brooklyn===\nGreene, moving where the work was, relocated to Cincinnati, and then to Cleveland; her employment required constant travel. Added to the daunting reality of failure in a city with a large immigrant population, Lovecraft's single-room apartment at 169 Clinton Street in [[Brooklyn Heights]], not far from the working-class waterfront neighborhood [[Red Hook, Brooklyn|Red Hook]], was burgled, leaving him with only the clothes he was wearing. In August 1925, he wrote \"[[The Horror at Red Hook]]\" and \"[[He (short story)|He]]\", in the latter of which the narrator says \"My coming to New York had been a mistake; for whereas I had looked for poignant wonder and inspiration [...]  I had found instead only a sense of horror and oppression which threatened to master, paralyze, and annihilate me.\" It was at around this time he wrote the outline for \"[[The Call of Cthulhu]]\", with its theme of the insignificance of all humanity. In the bibliographical study ''[[H. P. Lovecraft: Against the World, Against Life]]'', [[Michel Houellebecq]] suggested that the misfortunes fed Lovecraft's central motivation as a writer, which he said was racial resentment.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite book |last=Houellebecq |first=Michel |title=H. P. Lovecraft: Against the World, Against Life |title-link=H. P. Lovecraft: Against the World, Against Life |publisher=Believer Books |year=2005 |isbn=1-932416-18-8 |location=San Francisco |name-list-format=vanc}}</ref> With a weekly allowance Greene sent, Lovecraft moved to a working-class area of [[Brooklyn Heights]], where he subsisted in a tiny apartment. He had lost approximately {{convert|40|lb|kg}} of body weight by 1926, when he left for Providence.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /><ref name=\"Joshi2001\">{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tfrbBSFn_p8C&q=The+one+thing+Lovecraft+could+do+during+Sonia%27s+absence+is+control+his+eating+habits.#v=snippet&q=The%20one%20thing%20Lovecraft%20could%20do%20during%20Sonia's%20absence%20is%20control%20his%20eating%20habits.&f=false |title=A Dreamer and a Visionary: H. P. Lovecraft in His Time |publisher=Liverpool University Press |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-85323-946-8 |pages=214\u2013215}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Providence===\n[[File:The Samuel B. Mumford House.jpg|thumb|left|Lovecraft's final home, May 1933 until March 10, 1937]]\nBack in Providence, Lovecraft lived in a \"spacious brown [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] wooden house\" at 10 Barnes Street until 1933.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Rubinton |first=Noel |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/14/travel/hp-lovecraft-providence.html |title=How to Find the Spirit of H.P. Lovecraft in Providence |date=August 10, 2016 |work=[[The New York Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013213244/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/14/travel/hp-lovecraft-providence.html |archive-date=October 13, 2018}}</ref> The same address is given as the home of Dr. Willett in Lovecraft's ''[[The Case of Charles Dexter Ward]]''. The period beginning after his return to Providence\u2014the last decade of his life\u2014was Lovecraft's most prolific; in that time he produced short stories, as well as his longest works of fiction: ''[[The Dream-Quest of Unknown Kadath]]'', ''The Case of Charles Dexter Ward'', and ''[[At the Mountains of Madness]]''. He frequently revised work for other authors and did a large amount of [[ghost-writing]], including ''[[The Mound (novella)|The Mound]]'', ''Winged Death'', and ''The Diary of Alonzo Typer''. Client [[Harry Houdini]] was laudatory, and attempted to help Lovecraft by introducing him to the head of a newspaper syndicate. Plans for a further project were ended by Houdini's death.<ref>{{Cite book |title=An H.P. Lovecraft Encyclopedia |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-313-31578-7 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=New York |page=117 |name-list-format=vanc |editor-last2=Schultz |editor-first2=David E.}}</ref>\n\nAlthough he was able to combine his distinctive style (allusive and amorphous description by horrified though passive narrators) with the kind of stock content and action that the editor of ''Weird Tales'' wanted\u2014Wright paid handsomely to snap up \"[[The Dunwich Horror]]\" which proved very popular with readers\u2014Lovecraft increasingly produced work that brought him no remuneration. Affecting a calm indifference to the reception of his works, Lovecraft was in reality extremely sensitive to criticism and easily precipitated into withdrawal. He was known to give up trying to sell a story after it had been once rejected. Sometimes, as with ''The Shadow over Innsmouth'' (which included a rousing chase that supplied action) he wrote a story that might have been commercially viable but did not try to sell it. Lovecraft even ignored interested publishers. He failed to reply when one inquired about any novel Lovecraft might have ready: although he had completed such a work, ''The Case of Charles Dexter Ward'', it was never typed up.<ref name=\"Anderson2014\">{{Cite book |last=Anderson |first=James Arthur |title=Out of the Shadows: A Structuralist Approach to Understanding the Fiction of H. P. Lovecraft |date=September 30, 2014 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-1-4794-0384-4 |location=Rockville, Maryland |page=89 |chapter=Charles Dexter Ward |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9FCsBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA89}}</ref>\n\nA few years after Lovecraft had moved to Providence, he and his wife Sonia Greene, having lived separately for so long, agreed to an amicable divorce. Greene moved to California in 1933 and remarried in 1936, unaware that Lovecraft, despite his assurances to the contrary, had never officially signed the final decree.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=H. P. Lovecraft: A Life |date=2004 |publisher=Necronomicon Press |isbn=0-940884-88-7 |location=West Warwick, Rhode Island |page=455}}</ref>\n\n===Last years and death===\nLovecraft was never able to provide for even basic expenses by selling stories and doing paid literary work for others. He lived frugally, subsisting on an inheritance that was nearly depleted by the time he died. He sometimes went without food to be able to pay the cost of mailing letters.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{Cite book |last=Ronan |first=Margaret |title=The Shadow Over Innsmouth and Other Stories of Horror |date=1971 |publisher=Scholastic Book Services |chapter=Forward}}</ref> After leaving New York, he moved to an apartment at 10 Barnes Street near Brown University with his surviving aunt; a few years later, they moved to a slightly less expensive place at 65 Prospect Street. As a result of the [[Great Depression]], he shifted towards socialism. He supported [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], but he thought that the [[New Deal]] was not sufficiently leftist.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=A Dreamer and a Visionary: H.P. Lovecraft in His Time |date=2001 |publisher=Liverpool University Press |isbn=978-0-85323-936-9 |pages=346\u2013358 |chapter=Caring about the Civilization (1929\u201337) |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wk5ixOCy4eMC&q=In+the+summer+of+1936+Lovecraft+made+an+interesting+admission%3A#v=snippet&q=In%20the%20summer%20of%201936%20Lovecraft%20made%20an%20interesting%20admission%3A&f=false}}</ref>\n\n[[File:H.P. Lovecraft's grave.jpg|thumb|right|H. P. Lovecraft's gravestone]]\n\nIn late 1936, he witnessed the publication of ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]'' as a paperback book.{{refn|This is the only one of Lovecraft's stories that was published as a book during his lifetime.<ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\" />|group= n}} However, Lovecraft was displeased, as his book was riddled with errors. It sold slowly and only approximately 200 copies were bound. The remaining manuscripts were destroyed after the publisher went out of business. By this point, Lovecraft's literary career had reached its end. Shortly after having written his last original short story, \"[[The Haunter of the Dark]]\", he stated that the hostile reception of ''At the Mountains of Madness'' had done \"more than anything to end my effective fictional career.\"<ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\">{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=A Dreamer and a Visionary: H.P. Lovecraft in His Time |publisher=[[Liverpool University Press]] |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-85323-946-8 |pages=364\u2013388 |chapter=The End of One's Life (1935\u201337) |author-link=S. T. Joshi |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wk5ixOCy4eMC&q=The+End+of+One%27s+Life+%281935%E2%80%9337%29#v=snippet&q=The%20End%20of%20One's%20Life%20(1935%E2%80%9337)&f=false}}</ref>\n\nOn June 11, [[Robert E. Howard#Death|Robert E. Howard]] committed suicide after being told that his mother would not awaken from her coma. His mother died shortly thereafter. This deeply affected Lovecraft, who consoled Howard's father. Almost immediately, Lovecraft wrote a brief memoir titled \"In Memoriam: Robert Ervin Howard\".<ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\" /><ref>{{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=Collected Essays |date=2006 |publisher=Hippocampus Press |isbn=978-0976159230 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |edition=1st |volume=5 |location=New York |pages=216\u2013218 |chapter=In Memoriam: Robert Ervin Howard |oclc=54350507 |orig-year=first published September 1936}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Lovecraft's physical health was deteriorating. He was suffering from an affliction that he referred to as \"grippe\".{{refn|\"Grippe\" is an archaic term for [[influenza]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.lexico.com/en/definition/grippe |title=Grippe |website=Lexico Dictionaries |access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref>|group= n}}<ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\" /> After seeing a doctor, he was diagnosed with [[Small intestine cancer|terminal cancer of the small intestine]]. Due to his fear of doctors, Lovecraft was not examined until a mere month before his death. He remained hospitalized during that time. He lived in constant pain until his death on March 15, 1937, in Providence. In accordance with his lifelong scientific curiosity, he kept a diary of his illness until he was physically incapable of holding a pen.<ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32716288/the-boston-globe/ |title=Wrote of His Last Month Alive |date=March 15, 1937 |work=The Boston Globe |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228223254/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32716288/the-boston-globe/ |archive-date=February 28, 2020 |page=2 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nLovecraft was listed along with his parents on the Phillips family monument ({{coord|41.8540176|-71.3810921|format=dms|type:landmark}}). In 1977, fans erected a headstone in [[Swan Point Cemetery]] on which they inscribed his name, the dates of his birth and death, and the phrase \"I AM PROVIDENCE\"\u2014a line from one of his personal letters.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://swanpointcemetery.com/notable-people.php |title=Notable Persons Interred at Swan Point Cemetery |website=swanpointcemetery.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160122114735/http://swanpointcemetery.com/notable-people.php |archive-date=January 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Legacy===\nGroups of enthusiasts annually observe the anniversaries of Lovecraft's death at [[Ladd Observatory]] and of his birth at his grave site. In July 2013, the Providence City Council designated \"H. P. Lovecraft Memorial Square\" and installed a commemorative sign at the intersection of Angell and Prospect streets, near the author's former residences.<ref name=\"motif-we-are-providence\">{{Cite news |last=Bilow |first=Michael |url=http://motifri.com/we-are-providence-the-h-p-lovecraft-community/ |title=We are Providence: The H.P. Lovecraft Community |date=July 27, 2013 |work=Motif Magazine |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017080819/http://motifri.com/we-are-providence-the-h-p-lovecraft-community/ |archive-date=October 17, 2013 |location=[[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], Rhode Island}}</ref> In 2016, Lovecraft was inducted into the [[Museum of Pop Culture]]'s Science Fiction and Fantasy Hall of Fame.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://locusmag.com/2017/01/2016-sff-hall-of-fame-inductees/ |title=2016 SF&F Hall of Fame Inductees |last=<!--Not stated--> |date=January 17, 2017 |website=Locus Online |language=en-US |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222001003/https://locusmag.com/2017/01/2016-sff-hall-of-fame-inductees/ |archive-date=December 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====World Fantasy Award bust====\n{{Main|World Fantasy Award#H. P. Lovecraft bust}}\nThe first World Fantasy Awards were held in Providence in 1975. The theme was \"The Lovecraft Circle.\" Until 2015, winners were presented with an elognated bust of Lovecraft that was designed by [[cartoonist]] [[Gahan Wilson]]. The Bust was nicknamed the \"Howard.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/11/hp-lovecraft-world-fantasy-awards/415485/ |title='Political Correctness' Won't Ruin H.P. Lovecraft's Legacy |last=Cruz |first=Lenika |date=November 12, 2015 |website=[[The Atlantic]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117085814/http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/11/hp-lovecraft-world-fantasy-awards/415485/ |archive-date=November 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tor.com/2014/08/20/should-the-world-fantasy-award-be-changed/ |title=Should the World Fantasy Award be Changed? |last=Schnelbach |first=Leah |date=August 20, 2014 |website=Tor.com |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329144215/http://www.tor.com/2014/08/20/should-the-world-fantasy-award-be-changed/ |archive-date=March 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, writer [[Donald Wandrei]] caused some controversy after he was offered a [[World Fantasy Award]] for Life Achievement but refused to accept it because the award was a bust of H. P. Lovecraft that he felt looked more like a caricature of Lovecraft than an actual representation.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Sullivan |first=Jack |title=The Penguin Encyclopedia of Horror and the Supernatural |title-link=The Penguin Encyclopedia of Horror and the Supernatural |publisher=[[Viking Press]] |year=1986 |isbn=978-0-670-80902-8 |location=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/penguinencyclope00sull/page/448 448\u2013449] |author-link=Jack Sullivan (literary scholar)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite encyclopedia |title=Wandrei, Donald |encyclopedia=[[The Encyclopedia of Fantasy]] |last=Morrish |first=Bob |date=March 15, 1999 |editor-last=Grant |editor-first=John |pages=994\u20135 |isbn=978-0-312-19869-5 |editor1-link=John Grant (author) |editor2-link=John Clute |editor2-first=John |editor2-last=Clute}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, author [[Daniel Jos\u00e9 Older]] started a petition to change the World Fantasy Award statuette from a bust of Lovecraft to one of African-American author [[Octavia Butler]].<ref name=\"tg\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/sep/17/world-fantasy-awards-hp-lovecraft-racism-row-statuette |title=World Fantasy awards pressed to drop HP Lovecraft trophy in racism row |date=September 17, 2014 |work=The Guardian |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118165842/http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/sep/17/world-fantasy-awards-hp-lovecraft-racism-row-statuette |archive-date=January 18, 2015}}</ref> Kevin J. Maroney, editor of ''[[The New York Review of Science Fiction]]'', also supported the call for the WFA to be changed from Lovecraft's face, suggesting it be replaced with a symbol representing the fantasy genre. Maroney argued this should be done \"not out of disrespect for Lovecraft as a writer or as a central figure in fantasy, but as a courtesy to generations of writers whom the WFA hopes to honor.\"<ref>{{Cite journal |date=August 2014 |title=Editorial: Chance of Face, Change of Heart |url=http://www.nyrsf.com/2014/09/issue-312-august-2014-editorial-chance-of-face-change-of-heart.html |url-status=live |journal=The New York Review of Science Fiction |issue=312 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908023245/http://www.nyrsf.com/2014/09/issue-312-august-2014-editorial-chance-of-face-change-of-heart.html |archive-date=September 8, 2015}}</ref> In response to the campaign, the board of the World Fantasy Awards announced in September 2014 that it was \"in discussion\" about the future of the award statuette,<ref name=\"tg\" /> and in November 2015 it was announced that the World Fantasy Award trophy would no longer be modeled on H. P. Lovecraft.<ref name=\"TG2\">{{Cite news |last=Flood, Alison |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/09/world-fantasy-award-drops-hp-lovecraft-as-prize-image |title=World Fantasy award drops HP Lovecraft as prize image |date=November 9, 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118192211/http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/09/world-fantasy-award-drops-hp-lovecraft-as-prize-image |archive-date=November 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\n{{more citations needed section|date=May 2012}}\n\nSome of Lovecraft's work was inspired by his own nightmares.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=FRANCH |first=A. |last2=MACROBERT |year=2015 |title=Cosmic Dread: THE ASTRONOMY OF H. P. LOVECRAFT |magazine=Sky & Telescope |volume=129 |issue=2 |pages=34\u201339}}</ref> His interest started from his childhood days when his grandfather would tell him Gothic horror stories. \n\nLovecraft's most significant literary influence was Edgar Allan Poe.  Like Lovecraft, Poe's work was out of step with the prevailing literary trends of his era. Both authors created distinctive, singular worlds of fantasy and employed [[archaism]]s in their writings. This influence can be found in such works as his novella ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]''<ref name=\"The Shadow Over Innsmouth\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/fiction/soi.aspx |title=The Shadow Over Innsmouth |date=August 20, 2009 |publisher=Donovan K. Loucks |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807082000/http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/fiction/soi.aspx |archive-date=August 7, 2013}}</ref> where Lovecraft references Poe's story \"[[The Imp of the Perverse (short story)|The Imp of the Perverse]]\" by name in Chapter 3, and in his poem \"Nemesis\", where the \"...&nbsp;ghoul-guarded gateways of slumber\"<ref name=\"ghoul-guarded\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/poetry/p121.aspx |title=Nemesis |date=October 20, 2009 |publisher=Donovan K. Loucks |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130910194736/http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/poetry/p121.aspx |archive-date=September 10, 2013}}</ref> suggest the \"...&nbsp;ghoul-haunted woodland of Weir\"<ref name=\"ghoul-haunted\">{{Cite book |last=Poe |first=Edgar Allan |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ddJKAQAAMAAJ&q=ghoul-haunted+woodland+of+Weir+#v=snippet&q=ghoul-haunted%20woodland%20of%20Weir&f=false |title=The Works of the Late Edgar Allan Poe |date=1859 |publisher=Redfield |editor-last=Griswold |editor-first=Rufus Wilmot |editor-link=Rufus Wilmot Griswold |volume=II |location=New York City |language=en |chapter=Ulalume |author-link=Edgar Allan Poe}}</ref> found in Poe's \"[[Ulalume]]\". A direct quote from the poem and a reference to Poe's only novel ''[[The Narrative of Arthur Gordon Pym of Nantucket]]'' is alluded to in Lovecraft's ''[[Masterpiece|magnum opus]]'' ''[[At the Mountains of Madness]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/fiction/mm.aspx |title=''At the Mountains of Madness'' |date=August 20, 2009 |website=www.hplovecraft.com |publisher=Donovan K. Loucks |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225184117/http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/fiction/mm.aspx |archive-date=February 25, 2017}}</ref> Both authors shared many biographical similarities as well, such as the loss of their fathers at young ages and an early interest in poetry.\n\nHe was influenced by [[Arthur Machen]]'s<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/culture/2014/10/weird-realism-john-gray-moral-universe-h-p-lovecraft |title=Weird realism: John Gray on the moral universe of H P Lovecraft |website=www.newstatesman.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414140517/http://www.newstatesman.com/culture/2014/10/weird-realism-john-gray-moral-universe-h-p-lovecraft |archive-date=April 14, 2016}}</ref> carefully constructed tales concerning the survival of ancient evil into modern times in an otherwise realistic world and his beliefs in hidden mysteries which lay behind reality. Lovecraft was also influenced by authors such as Oswald Spengler and [[Robert W. Chambers]]. Chambers was the writer of ''[[The King in Yellow]]'', of whom Lovecraft wrote in a letter to [[Clark Ashton Smith]]: \"Chambers is like [[Rupert Hughes]] and a few other fallen Titans \u2013 equipped with the right brains and education but wholly out of the habit of using them.\" Lovecraft's discovery of the stories of [[Edward Plunkett, 18th Baron of Dunsany|Lord Dunsany]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Power |first=Ed |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/10/30/cthulhus-evil-overlord-the-monstrous-world-of-hp-lovecraft/ |title=Cthulhu's evil overlord: the monstrous world of HP Lovecraft |date=October 30, 2016 |work=The Telegraph |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223013216/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/10/30/cthulhus-evil-overlord-the-monstrous-world-of-hp-lovecraft/ |archive-date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> with their pantheon of mighty gods existing in dreamlike outer realms, moved his writing in a new direction, resulting in a series of imitative fantasies in a ''Dreamlands'' setting.\n\nLovecraft also cited [[Algernon Blackwood]] as an influence, quoting ''The Centaur'' in the head paragraph of \"[[The Call of Cthulhu]]\". He declared Blackwood's story ''[[The Willows (story)|The Willows]]'' to be the single best piece of weird fiction ever written.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/essays/shil.aspx |title=Supernatural Horror in Literature |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |date=October 20, 2009 |website=www.hplovecraft.com |publisher=Donovan K. Loucks |orig-year=written 1927 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200119175841/http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/essays/shil.aspx |archive-date=January 19, 2020 |quote=The well-nigh endless array of Mr. Blackwood's fiction includes both novels and shorter tales&nbsp;... Foremost of all must be reckoned 'The Willows'&nbsp;... Here art and restraint in narrative reach their very highest development, and an impression of lasting poignancy is produced without a single strained passage or a single false note.}}</ref>\n\nAnother inspiration came from a completely different source: scientific progress in biology, astronomy,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/84903/7-obsessions-influenced-h-p-lovecrafts-work |title=7 Obsessions That Influenced H. P. Lovecraft's Work |work=Mental Floss |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225053300/http://mentalfloss.com/article/84903/7-obsessions-influenced-h-p-lovecrafts-work |archive-date=February 25, 2017 |language=en}}</ref> geology, and physics.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Rottensteiner |first=Franz |author-link=Franz Rottensteiner |year=1992 |title=Lovecraft as Philosopher |journal=Science Fiction Studies |volume=19 |issue=1 |pages=117\u2013121 |jstor=4240129}}</ref> His study of science contributed to Lovecraft's view of the human race as insignificant, powerless, and doomed in a [[materialistic]] and [[mechanistic]] universe.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Woodard |first=Ben |date=2011 |title=Mad Speculation and Absolute Inhumanism: Lovecraft, Ligotti, and the Weirding of Philosophy |url=http://www.continentcontinent.cc/index.php/continent/article/view/14 |url-status=live |journal=Continent |volume=1 |issue=1 |page=6 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180209220929/http://continentcontinent.cc/index.php/continent/article/view/14 |archive-date=February 9, 2018}}</ref> Lovecraft was a keen amateur astronomer from his youth, often visiting the [[Ladd Observatory]] in Providence, and penning numerous astronomical articles for local newspapers. His astronomical telescope is now housed in the rooms of the [[August Derleth]] Society.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.augustderleth.org/about-the-ads/overview/accomplishments/ |title=Accomplishments |website=www.augustderleth.org |access-date=January 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLovecraft's materialist views led him to espouse his philosophical views through his fiction; these philosophical views came to be called [[cosmicism]]. Cosmicism took on a more pessimistic tone with his creation of what is now known as the Cthulhu Mythos; a fictional universe that contains alien deities and horrors. The term \"Cthulhu Mythos\" was likely coined by Lovecraft's correspondent and prot\u00e9g\u00e9, August Derleth, after Lovecraft's death.<ref name=\"Schweitzer\" /> In his letters, Lovecraft jokingly called his fictional mythology \"Yog-Sothothery.\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=Against Religion: The Atheist Writings of H.P. Lovecraft |date=2010 |publisher=Sporting Gentlemen |isbn=978-0-578-05248-9 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |language=en |chapter=Religion and Indeterminacy |orig-year=written November 22, 1930 |editor-last2=Hitchens |editor-first2=Christopher |editor-link2=Christopher Hitchens |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=hdplAgAAQBAJ&dq=Lovecraft+Yog-Sothothery+Atheist&q=Were+an+child+to+be+reared+in+isolation,+and+surrounded+from+infancy+with+the+religious+precepts+of+Tsathoggua,+YOG-SOTHOTH,+or+the+Doels,+his+inner+emotions+would+all+through+life+inform+him+positively+of+the+truth+of+Tsathogguanism,+Yog-Sothothery,+or+Doelolatry,+as+the+case+might+be,+I%C3%A4!+Shub-Niggurath!+The+Goat+With+a+Thousand+Young!#v=snippet&q=Were%20an%20child%20to%20be%20reared%20in%20isolation,%20and%20surrounded%20from%20infancy%20with%20the%20religious%20precepts%20of%20Tsathoggua,%20YOG-SOTHOTH,%20or%20the%20Doels,%20his%20inner%20emotions%20would%20all%20through%20life%20inform%20him%20positively%20of%20the%20truth%20of%20Tsathogguanism,%20Yog-Sothothery,%20or%20Doelolatry,%20as%20the%20case%20might%20be,%20I%C3%A4!%20Shub-Niggurath!%20The%20Goat%20With%20a%20Thousand%20Young!&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Klinger |first=Leslie S. |title=The New Annotated H. P. Lovecraft |date=October 13, 2014 |publisher=W. W. Norton & Company |isbn=978-1-63149-055-2 |page=xii |language=en}}</ref>\n\nLovecraft's use of [[British English]] owes much to his father's influence. He described his father as having been so [[anglophilic]] that he was commonly presumed to be an Englishman. According to Lovecraft, his father had been constantly warned to avoid using Americanized words and phrases. This influence stretched beyond Lovecraft's use of language. His father's anglophilia had also caused Lovecraft to have a deep affection for [[British culture]] and the [[British Empire]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tfrbBSFn_p8C&q=Perhaps+more+important+than+all+these+matters+is+the+image+and+tokens+of+his+father+which+Lovecraft+retained+in+maturity.#v=snippet&q=Perhaps%20more%20important%20than%20all%20these%20matters%20is%20the%20image%20and%20tokens%20of%20his%20father%20which%20Lovecraft%20retained%20in%20maturity.&f=false |title=A Dreamer and a Visionary: H.P. Lovecraft in His Time |date=2001 |publisher=Liverpool University Press |isbn=978-0-85323-946-8 |pages=15\u201316 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAmong the books found in his library (as evidenced in ''Lovecraft's Library'' by S. T. Joshi){{Full citation needed|date=January 2020}} was ''[[The Seven Who Were Hanged]]'' by [[Leonid Andreyev]] and ''[[A Strange Manuscript Found in a Copper Cylinder]]'' by [[James De Mille]].\n\nLovecraft's style has often been subject to criticism,<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\" /> yet scholars such as S. T. Joshi have shown that Lovecraft consciously utilized a variety of literary devices to form a unique style of his own \u2013 these include conscious [[archaism]], prose-poetic techniques combined with essay-form techniques, [[alliteration]], [[Anaphora (rhetoric)|anaphora]], [[crescendo]], [[transferred epithet]], [[metaphor]], [[Symbolism (arts)|symbolism]], and [[colloquialism]].{{Full citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n==Themes==\n{{Synthesis|section|date=February 2009}}\n\nSeveral themes recur in Lovecraft's stories:\n\n{{quote box|width=30em|align=right|Now all my tales are based on the fundamental premise that common human laws and interests and emotions have no validity or significance in the vast cosmos-at-large. To me there is nothing but puerility in a tale in which the human form\u2014and the local human passions and conditions and standards\u2014are depicted as native to other worlds or other universes. To achieve the essence of real externality, whether of time or space or dimension, one must forget that such things as organic life, good and evil, love and hate, and all such local attributes of a negligible and temporary race called mankind, have any existence at all. Only the human scenes and characters must have human qualities. ''These'' must be handled with unsparing ''realism'', (''not'' catch-penny ''romanticism'') but when we cross the line to the boundless and hideous unknown\u2014the shadow-haunted ''Outside''\u2014we must remember to leave our humanity and terrestrialism at the threshold.|salign=right|source=\u2014&nbsp;H. P. Lovecraft, in note to the editor of ''Weird Tales'', on resubmission of \"The Call of Cthulhu\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=Selected Letters 1925\u20131929 |publisher=Arkham House |year=1968 |location=Sauk City, Wisconsin |page=150 |chapter=Letter to Farnsworth Wright (July 27, 1927)}}</ref>}}\n\n===Forbidden knowledge===\nForbidden, dark, esoterically veiled knowledge is a central theme in many of Lovecraft's works.<ref name=\"Burlesonglass\">{{Cite book |last=Burleson |first=Donald R. |title=An Epicure in the Terrible: A Centennial Anthology of Essays in Honor of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=[[Fairleigh Dickinson University Press]] |year=1991 |isbn=978-0-8386-3415-8 |editor-last=Schultz |editor-first=David E. |pages=135\u2013147 |chapter=On Lovecraft's Themes: Touching the Glass |editor-last2=Joshi |editor-first2=S. T. |editor-link2=S. T. Joshi |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S3oH_VdH3BcC&pg=PA135}}</ref> Many of his characters are driven by curiosity or scientific endeavor, and in many of his stories the knowledge they uncover proves [[Prometheus|Promethean]] in nature, either filling the seeker with regret for what they have learned, destroying them psychologically, or completely destroying the person who holds the knowledge.<ref name=\"Burlesonglass\" /><ref>{{Cite book |last=Dziemianowicz |first=Stefan |title=An Epicure in the Terrible: A Centennial Anthology of Essays in Honor of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=[[Fairleigh Dickinson University Press]] |year=1991 |isbn=978-0-8386-3415-8 |editor-last=Schultz |editor-first=David E. |pages=159\u2013187 |chapter=Outsiders and Aliens: The Uses of Isolation in Lovecraft's Fiction |editor-last2=Joshi |editor-first2=S. T. |editor-link2=S. T. Joshi |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S3oH_VdH3BcC&pg=PA159}}</ref><ref name=\"Hamblycraft\">{{Cite book |last=Hambly |first=Barbara |title=The transition of H. P. Lovecraft: The Road to Madness |publisher=The Random House Publishing Group |year=1996 |isbn=978-0-345-38422-5 |page=viii |chapter=Introduction: The Man Who Loved His Craft}}</ref><ref name=\"burlsonuniverse\">{{Cite book |last=Burleson |first=Donald |title=Lovecraft: Disturbing the Universe |publisher=the University Press of Kentucky |year=1990 |isbn=978-0-8131-1728-7}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Leiber |first=Fritz |title=Discovering H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=Borgo Press |year=2001 |isbn=978-1-58715-471-3 |editor-last=Schweitzer |editor-first=Darrell |page=14 |chapter=A Literary Copernicus |author-link=Fritz Leiber |orig-year=first published 1949 |chapter-url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Discovering_H_P_Lovecraft/-PDksCTdmYMC?hl=en&gbpv=1&bsq=These%20individuals%20are%20in%20all%20other%20ways%20very%20realistically-minded%20indeed,%20but%20having%20glimpsed%20the%20forbidden%20knowledge,%20they%20are%20generally%20more%20susceptible%20to%20cosmic%20terror%20than%20ordinary%20people}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Price |first=Robert M. |title=Introduction:The New Lovecraft Circle |publisher=Random House Publishing |year=1991 |isbn=978-0-345-44406-6}}</ref>\n\nSome critics argue that this theme is a reflection of Lovecraft's contempt of the world around him, causing him to search inwardly for knowledge and inspiration.<ref name=\"Armandborges\">{{Cite book |last=St. Armand |first=Barton Levi |title=An Epicure in the Terrible: A Centennial Anthology of Essays in Honor of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=[[Fairleigh Dickinson University Press]] |year=1991 |isbn=978-0-8386-3415-8 |editor-last=Schultz |editor-first=David E. |pages=319\u2013320 |chapter=Synchronistic Worlds: Lovecraft and Borges |editor-last2=Joshi |editor-first2=S. T. |editor-link2=S. T. Joshi |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S3oH_VdH3BcC&pg=PA319}}</ref>\n\n===Non-human influences on humanity===\nThe beings of Lovecraft's [[mythos]] often have human servants; [[Cthulhu]], for instance, is worshipped under various names by [[cult]]s{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} among both the [[Greenlandic Inuit]] and [[Louisiana Voodoo|voodoo circles of Louisiana]], and in many other parts of the world.\n\nThese worshippers served a useful narrative purpose for Lovecraft. Many beings of the Mythos were too powerful to be defeated by human opponents, and so horrific that direct knowledge of them meant insanity for the victim. When dealing with such beings, Lovecraft needed a way to provide [[Dramatic structure#Exposition|exposition]] and build tension without bringing the story to a premature end. Human followers gave him a way to reveal information about their \"gods\" in a diluted form, and also made it possible for his protagonists to win paltry victories. Lovecraft, like his contemporaries, envisioned \"savages\" as closer to supernatural knowledge unknown to civilized man.\n\n===Inherited guilt===\nAnother recurring theme in Lovecraft's stories is the idea that descendants in a bloodline can never escape the stain of crimes committed by their forebears, at least if the crimes are atrocious enough. Descendants may be very far removed, both in place and in time (and, indeed, in [[culpability]]), from the act itself, and yet, they may be haunted by the revenant past, e.g. \"[[The Rats in the Walls]]\", \"[[The Lurking Fear]]\", \"[[Facts Concerning the Late Arthur Jermyn and His Family]]\", \"[[The Alchemist (short story)|The Alchemist]]\", ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]'', \"[[The Doom that Came to Sarnath]]\" and ''The Case of Charles Dexter Ward''.\n\n===Fate===\nOften in Lovecraft's works, the protagonist is not in control of his own actions or finds it impossible to change course. Many of his characters would be free from danger if they simply managed to run away; however, this possibility either never arises or is somehow curtailed by some outside force, such as in \"[[The Colour Out of Space]]\" and \"[[The Dreams in the Witch House]]\". Often his characters are subject to a compulsive influence from powerful malevolent or indifferent beings. As with the inevitability of one's ancestry, eventually even running away, or death itself, provides no safety (''[[The Thing on the Doorstep]]'', \"[[The Outsider (short story)|The Outsider]]\", ''The Case of Charles Dexter Ward''). In some cases, this doom is manifest in the entirety of humanity, and no escape is possible (''[[The Shadow Out of Time]]'').\n\n===Civilization under threat===\nLovecraft was familiar with the work of the German conservative-revolutionary theorist [[Oswald Spengler]], whose pessimistic thesis of the decadence of the modern West formed a crucial element in Lovecraft's overall [[anti-modern]] worldview. Spenglerian imagery of cyclical decay is present in particular in ''At the Mountains of Madness''. S. T. Joshi, in ''H. P. Lovecraft: The Decline of the West'', places Spengler at the center of his discussion of Lovecraft's political and philosophical ideas.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |url=https://books.google.com/?id=KaklDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=I.%20Spengler%20and%20Lovecraft&f=false |title=H. P. Lovecraft: The Decline of the West |date=2016-05-28 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-1-4794-2754-3 |pages=314\u2013320 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nLovecraft wrote to Clark Ashton Smith in 1927: \"It is my belief, and was so long before Spengler put his seal of scholarly proof on it, that our mechanical and industrial age is one of frank [[decadence]].\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Mi\u00e9ville |first=China |title=At the Mountains of Madness |last2=Lovecraft |first2=H. P. |date=2005 |publisher=Modern Library Classics |isbn=9780812974416 |page=xxi |chapter=Introduction |author-link=China Mi\u00e9ville |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=qfWLDQAAQBAJ&pg=PR21&lpg=PR21&dq=It+is+my+belief,+and+was+so+long+before+Spengler+put+his+seal+of+scholarly+proof+on+it,+that+our+mechanical+and+industrial+age+is+one+of+frank+decadence.}}</ref> Lovecraft was also acquainted with the writings of another German philosopher of decadence: [[Friedrich Nietzsche]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Joshi|1996|p=38|ref=magick}}</ref>\n\nLovecraft frequently dealt with the idea of [[civilization]] struggling against dark, primitive barbarism. In some stories this struggle is at an individual level; many of his [[protagonist]]s are cultured, highly educated men who are gradually corrupted by some obscure and feared influence.\n\nIn such stories, the [[curse]] is often a hereditary one, either because of interbreeding with non-humans (e.g., ''[[Facts Concerning the Late Arthur Jermyn and His Family]]'' (1920), ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]'' (1931)) or through direct magical influence (''The Case of Charles Dexter Ward''). Physical and mental degradation often come together; this theme of 'tainted blood' may represent concerns relating to Lovecraft's own family history, particularly the death of his father due to what Lovecraft must have suspected to be a [[syphilis|syphilitic]] disorder.\n\nIn other tales, an entire society is threatened by barbarism. Sometimes the barbarism comes as an external threat, with a civilized race destroyed in war (e.g. \"[[Polaris (short story)|Polaris]]\"). Sometimes, an isolated pocket of humanity falls into decadence and [[atavism]] of its own accord (e.g. \"[[The Lurking Fear]]\"). But most often, such stories involve a civilized culture being gradually undermined by a malevolent underclass influenced by inhuman forces.\n\nIt is likely that the \"[[Roaring Twenties]]\" left Lovecraft disillusioned as he was still obscure and struggling with the basic necessities of daily life, combined with seeing non-Western European immigrants in New York City.\n\n===Race===\nRace is the most controversial aspect of Lovecraft's legacy, expressed in many disparaging remarks against the various non-Anglo-Saxon [[Race (classification of humans)|races]] and cultures in his work. As he grew older, his original Anglo-Saxon racial worldview softened into a classism or elitism which regarded the superior race to include all those self-ennobled through high culture. From the start, Lovecraft did not hold all [[white people]] in uniform high regard, but rather esteemed the English people and those of English descent.<ref name=\"joshimagic\">{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=A Subtler Magick: The Writings and Philosophy of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=Borgo Press |year=1996 |isbn=978-1-880448-61-8 |pages=22, 41\u201342, 76\u201377, 107\u2013108, 162, 229, 230}}</ref><ref name=\"Berndfantastic\">{{Cite book |last=Steiner |first=Bernd |title=H. P. Lovecraft and the Literature of the fantastic: explorations in a Literary Genre |publisher=GRIN Verlag |year=2005 |isbn=978-3-638-84462-8 |pages=54\u201355}}</ref><ref name=\"tysondream\" /><ref name=\"tysondream\" /> He praised non-[[White Anglo-Saxon Protestant|WASP]] groups such as Hispanics and Jews; however his private writings on groups such as Irish Catholics, German immigrants and African-Americans were consistently negative.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=H. P. Lovecraft, Four Decades of Criticism |publisher=Ohio University Press |year=1980 |isbn=978-0-8214-0577-2}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=January 2020}}<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=I Am Providence: The Life and Times of H. P. Lovecraft |title-link=H. P. Lovecraft: A Life |date=2010 |publisher=Hippocampus Press |isbn=978-0-9824296-7-9 |location=New York City}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=January 2020}} In an early poem, the 1912 \"[[s: On the Creation of Niggers|On the Creation of Niggers]]\", Lovecraft describes [[black people]] not as human but as \"beast[s] ... in semi-human figure, filled with vice.\" In his early published essays, private letters and personal utterances, he argued for a strong [[Color line (civil rights issue)|color line]] to preserve race and culture.<ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\" /><ref name=\"joshimagic\" /><ref name=\"Berndfantastic\" /><ref>{{Cite book |last=Punter |first=David |title=The Literature of Terror: A History of Gothic Fictions from 1765 to the Present Day |publisher=Routledge |year=1996 |isbn=978-0582237148 |volume=I |location=New York |page=40}}</ref> He made these arguments by direct disparagement of various races in his journalism and letters,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /><ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\" /><ref name=\"joshimagic\" /><ref name=\"Berndfantastic\" /><ref name=\"tysondream\" /> and perhaps allegorically in his fiction concerning non-human races.<ref name=\"Hamblycraft\" /><ref name=\"joshimagic\" /><ref>{{Cite book |last=Bloch |first=Robert |title=The Best of H. P. Lovecraft: Bloodcurdling Tales of Horror and the Macabre |publisher=The Random House Publishing Group |year=1982 |isbn=978-0-345-38422-5 |page=xii |chapter=Introduction: Heritage of Horror |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=fZRnpV521IcC&q=Some+critics+cite+this+as+a+disguised+example+of+the+racism+they+find+evident+in+%22He%2C%22+%22The+Horror+at+Red+Hook%2C%22+%22The+Call+of+Cthulhu%2C%22+and+other+stories.#v=snippet&q=Some%20critics%20cite%20this%20as%20a%20disguised%20example%20of%20the%20racism%20they%20find%20evident%20in%20%22He%2C%22%20%22The%20Horror%20at%20Red%20Hook%2C%22%20%22The%20Call%20of%20Cthulhu%2C%22%20and%20other%20stories.&f=false}}</ref><ref name=\"Mievillemountains\" /> Lovecraft showed sympathy to those who adopted Western culture, even to the extent of marrying a Jewish woman whom he viewed as \"well assimilated.\"<ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\" /><ref name=\"joshimagic\" /><ref name=\"Berndfantastic\" /><ref name=\"Mievillemountains\">{{Cite book |last=Mieville |first=China |title=At the Mountains of Madness |publisher=The Random House Publishing Group |year=2005 |isbn=978-0-8129-7441-6 |pages=xvii\u2013xx |chapter=Introduction |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/atmountainsofmad00love_0/page/}}</ref> Lovecraft's racial attitude was common in the society of his day, especially in the New England in which he grew up.<ref name=\"joshimagic\" /><ref name=\"Berndfantastic\" /><ref name=\"tysondream\">{{Cite book |last=Tyson |first=Donald |title=The Dream World of H. P. Lovecraft: His Life, His Demons, His Universe |publisher=Llewellyn Publications |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-7387-2284-9 |pages=5\u20136, 57\u201359}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Schweitzer |first=Darrell |title=Windows of the Imagination |publisher=Wildside Press |year=1998 |isbn=1-880448-60-2 <!-- Note: ISBN shown on book's copyright page is incorrect; the correct number appears on the back cover. --> |pages=94\u201395}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Schwader |first=Ann |title=Eldritch Blue: Love and Sex in the Cthulhu Mythos |publisher=Lindisfarne Press |year=2004 |isbn=978-0-9740297-5-7 |page=59 |chapter=Mail Order Bride}}</ref>\n\n===Risks of a scientific era===\nAt the turn of the 20th century, humanity's increased reliance upon science was both opening new worlds and solidifying understanding of ours. Lovecraft portrays this potential for a growing gap of man's understanding of the universe as a potential for horror, most notably in \"The Colour Out of Space\", where the inability of science to comprehend a contaminated meteorite leads to horror.\n\nIn a letter to [[James F. Morton]] in 1923, Lovecraft specifically pointed to [[Einstein]]'s [[Theory of relativity|theory on relativity]] as throwing the world into chaos and making the cosmos a jest; in a letter to Woodburn Harris in 1929, he speculated that technological comforts risk the collapse of science. Indeed, at a time when men viewed science as limitless and powerful, Lovecraft imagined alternative potential and fearful outcomes. In \"The Call of Cthulhu\", Lovecraft's characters encounter architecture which is \"abnormal, non-Euclidean, and loathsomely redolent of spheres and dimensions apart from ours.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/fiction/cc.aspx |title=The Call of Cthulhu |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |date=August 20, 2009 |website=www.hplovecraft.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722165927/http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/fiction/cc.aspx |archive-date=July 22, 2016}}</ref> [[Non-Euclidean geometry]] is the mathematical language and background of Einstein's [[general theory of relativity]], and Lovecraft references it repeatedly in exploring alien [[archaeology]].\n\n===Religion===\nLovecraft's works are ruled by several distinct pantheons of deities (actually aliens worshiped as such by humans) who are either indifferent or actively hostile to humanity. Lovecraft's actual philosophy has been termed \"cosmic indifference\" and this is expressed in his fiction.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Mosig |first=Yozan Dirk W. |date=August 1, 1985 |orig-year=first published 1979 |title=Lovecraft: The Dissonance Factor in Imaginative Literature |magazine=Crypt of Cthulhu |volume=4 |issue=8 |pages=12\u201323}}</ref> Several of Lovecraft's stories of the Old Ones (alien beings of the Cthulhu Mythos) propose alternate mythic human origins in contrast to those found in the [[creation myth|creation]] stories of existing religions, expanding on a natural world view. For instance, in Lovecraft's ''[[At the Mountains of Madness]]'', it is proposed that humankind was actually created as a slave race by the Old Ones, and that life on Earth as we know it evolved from scientific experiments abandoned by the Elder Things. Protagonist characters in Lovecraft are usually educated men, citing scientific and rational evidence to support their non-faith. ''[[Herbert West\u2013Reanimator]]'' reflects on the [[atheism]] common in academic circles. In ''[[The Silver Key]]'', the character [[Randolph Carter]] loses the ability to dream and seeks solace in religion, specifically [[Congregationalism in the United States|Congregationalism]], but does not find it and ultimately loses faith.\n\nLovecraft himself adopted the stance of atheism early in life. In 1932, he wrote in a letter to [[Robert E. Howard]]:\n\n<blockquote>All I say is that I think it is damned unlikely that anything like a central cosmic will, a spirit world, or an eternal survival of personality exist. They are the most preposterous and unjustified of all the guesses which can be made about the universe, and I am not enough of a hairsplitter to pretend that I don't regard them as arrant and negligible moonshine. In theory, I am an [[Agnosticism|agnostic]], but pending the appearance of radical evidence I must be classed, practically and provisionally, as an atheist.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=Selected Letters 1932\u20131934 |publisher=Arkham House |year=1976 |location=Sauk City, Wisconsin |page=57 |chapter=Letter to Robert E. Howard (August 16, 1932)}}\"</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Superstition===\nIn 1926, famed [[Magic (illusion)|magician]] and [[Escapology|escapist]] [[Harry Houdini]] asked Lovecraft to ghostwrite a treatise exploring the topic of superstition. Houdini's unexpected death later that year halted the project, but ''[[The Cancer of Superstition]]'' was partially completed by Lovecraft along with collaborator [[C. M. Eddy Jr.]] A previously unknown manuscript of the work was discovered in 2016 in a collection owned by a magic shop. The book states \"all superstitious beliefs are relics of a common 'prehistoric ignorance' in humans,\" and goes on to explore various superstitious beliefs in different cultures and times.\"<ref name=\"Flood\">{{Cite news |last=Flood |first=Alison |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/mar/16/hp-lovecraft-harry-houdini-manuscript-cancer-superstition-memorabilia |title=Lost HP Lovecraft work commissioned by Houdini escapes shackles of history |date=March 16, 2016 |work=The Guardian |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008115009/https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/mar/16/hp-lovecraft-harry-houdini-manuscript-cancer-superstition-memorabilia |archive-date=October 8, 2016 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== Lovecraft Country ===\n{{main|Lovecraft Country}}\n\nLovecraft drew extensively from his native New England for settings in his fiction. Numerous historical cities and towns are mentioned, and several fictionalised version of them make frequent appearances in his stories.{{refn|These fictional locations include [[Arkham]], [[Dunwich (Lovecraft)|Dunwich]], [[Innsmouth]], and Kingsport.<ref name=\"murray54\">{{Cite journal |last=Murray |first=Will |author-link=Will Murray |date=October 1, 1986 |title=In Search of Arkham Country |url=https://archive.org/details/Lovecraft_Studies_13v05n02_1986-Fall_CosmicJukebox/page/n13/mode/2up |journal=Lovecraft Studies |volume=5 |issue=2 |pages=54\u201367}}</ref>|group= n}} These municipalities are located in the western half of a fictionalized version of Massachusetts. The exact locations of these municipalities were subject to change, as Lovecraft had shifting literary needs. They were based on areas that he thought were evocative. He then redefined them and changed their names to suit his purposes. After this, he would exaggerate their features. For example, Arkham was based on a town named [[Oakham, Massachusetts|Oakham]]. Lovecraft renamed his fictionalized version of Oakham to Arkham, and expanded it to include a nearby landmark.<ref name=\"murray54\" />\n\n==Appreciation==\n\n===Within the genre===\nBy 1957 [[Floyd C. Gale]] of ''[[Galaxy Science Fiction]]'' said that \"like [[Robert E. Howard|R. E. Howard]], Lovecraft seemingly goes on forever; the two decades since their death are as nothing. In any event, they appear more prolific than ever. What with [[L. Sprague de Camp|de Camp]], [[Bj\u00f6rn Nyberg|Nyberg]] and Derleth avidly rooting out every scrap of their writings and expanding them into novels, there may never be an end to their posthumous careers.\"<ref name=\"gale195712\">{{Cite magazine |last=Gale |first=Floyd C. |date=April 1960 |title=Galaxy's 5 Star Shelf |url=https://archive.org/stream/galaxymagazine-1957-12/Galaxy_1957_12#page/n101/mode/2up |magazine=Galaxy Science Fiction |pages=100\u2013103 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322141855/https://archive.org/stream/galaxymagazine-1957-12/Galaxy_1957_12#page/n101/mode/2up |archive-date=March 22, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> According to [[Joyce Carol Oates]], Lovecraft (and [[Edgar Allan Poe]] in the 19th century) has exerted \"an incalculable influence on succeeding generations of writers of horror fiction.\"<ref name=\"Oates\">{{Cite journal |last=Oates |first=Joyce Carol |date=October 31, 1996 |title=The King of Weird |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/1376 |url-status=live |journal=The New York Review of Books |volume=43 |issue=17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090910081313/http://www.nybooks.com/articles/1376 |archive-date=September 10, 2009}}</ref> Horror, fantasy, and science fiction author [[Stephen King]] called Lovecraft \"the twentieth century's greatest practitioner of the classic horror tale.\"<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Wohleber |first=Curt |date=December 1995 |title=The Man Who Can Scare Stephen King |url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/man-who-can-scare-stephen-king?page=show |url-status=live |journal=[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]] |volume=46 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004220300/http://www.americanheritage.com/content/man-who-can-scare-stephen-king?page=show |archive-date=October 4, 2013 |number=8}}</ref> King has made it clear in his semi-autobiographical non-fiction book ''[[Danse Macabre (book)|Danse Macabre]]'' that Lovecraft was responsible for his own fascination with horror and the macabre and was the largest figure to influence his fiction writing.<ref>{{Cite book |last=King |first=Stephen |url=http://www.librosgratisweb.com/html/king-stephen/danse-macabre/index.htm |title=Danse Macabre |date=February 1987 |publisher=[[Berkley Books|Berkley]] |isbn=978-0-425-10433-0 |page=63 |author-link=Stephen King |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004222501/http://www.librosgratisweb.com/html/king-stephen/danse-macabre/index.htm |archive-date=October 4, 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Literary===\nEarly efforts to revise an established literary view of Lovecraft as an author of 'pulp' were resisted by some eminent critics; in 1945 [[Edmund Wilson]] expressed the opinion that \"the only real horror in most of these fictions is the horror of bad taste and bad art.\" However, Wilson praised Lovecraft's ability to write about his chosen field; he described him as having written about it \"with much intelligence.\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Wilson |first=Edmund |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=auPpqXw6bGQC&q=Tales+of+the+Marvellous+and+the+Ridiculous#v=snippet&q=Tales%20of%20the%20Marvellous%20and%20the%20Ridiculous&f=false |title=Classics and Commercials: A Literary Chronicle of the Forties |date=1950 |publisher=Macmillan |isbn=978-0-374-52667-2 |pages=286\u2013290 |language=en |orig-year=first published November 24, 1945}}</ref> According to L. Sprague de Camp, Wilson later revised his opinion of Lovecraft in a more positive direction. He claimed that Wilson had included a Lovecraftian reference in ''Little Blue Light: A Play in Three Acts''. After he met with him to discuss this, Wilson revealed that he had been reading a copy of Lovecraft's correspondence.<ref name=\"Fantasy Mongers\">{{Cite magazine |last=de Camp |first=L. Sprague |date=March 1979 |title=H. P. Lovecraft and Edmund Wilson |magazine=Fantasy Mongers |issue=1 |page=5}}</ref>{{refn|L. Sprague de Camp also claimed that they began calling each other \"Monstro.\" This is a direct reference to the nicknames that Lovecraft gave to some of his correspondents.<ref name=\"Fantasy Mongers\" />|group= n}} ''Mystery and Adventure'' columnist [[Will Cuppy]] of the ''[[New York Herald Tribune]]'' recommended to readers a volume of Lovecraft's stories, asserting that \"the literature of horror and macabre fantasy belongs with mystery in its broader sense.\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Cuppy |first=Will |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ua8YAAAAIAAJ&q=the+literature+of+horror+and+macabre+fantasy+belongs+with+mystery+in+its+broader+sense.&dq=the+literature+of+horror+and+macabre+fantasy+belongs+with+mystery+in+its+broader+sense. |title=Book Review Digest |date=1944 |publisher=H. W. Wilson Company |volume=39 |page=510 |language=en |author-link=Will Cuppy |orig-year=first published 1943}}</ref>\n\nGale said that \"Lovecraft at his best could build a mood of horror unsurpassed; at his worst, he was laughable.\"{{r|gale195712}} In 1962 [[Colin Wilson]], in his survey of anti-realist trends in fiction ''The Strength to Dream'', cited Lovecraft as one of the pioneers of the \"assault on rationality\" and included him with [[M. R. James]], [[H. G. Wells]], [[Aldous Huxley]], [[J. R. R. Tolkien]] and others as one of the builders of mythicised realities over against the failing project of literary realism.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}} Subsequently, Lovecraft began to acquire the status of a cult writer in the [[counterculture]] of the 1960s, and reprints of his work proliferated.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Luckhurst |first=Roger |title=The Classic Horror Stories |date=May 9, 2013 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-164089-6 |pages=xiii\u2013xiv |language=en |chapter=Introduction |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vQDDYhl057sC&q=Strange+things+started+happening+to+Lovecraft%27s+reputation+in+the+1960s.#v=snippet&q=Strange%20things%20started%20happening%20to%20Lovecraft's%20reputation%20in%20the%201960s.&f=false}}</ref>\nIn 2005, the status of classic American writer was accorded to Lovecraft with the publication of ''Tales'', a collection of his weird fiction stories, by the [[Library of America]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Stefans |first=Brian Kim |date=April 6, 2013 |title=Let's Get Weird: On Graham Harman's H.P. Lovecraft |url=http://lareviewofbooks.org/review/lets-get-weird-on-graham-harmans-h-p-lovecraft |magazine=Los Angeles Review of Books |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017005119/http://lareviewofbooks.org/review/lets-get-weird-on-graham-harmans-h-p-lovecraft |archive-date=October 17, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Philosophical===\nPhilosopher [[Graham Harman]], seeing Lovecraft as having a unique\u2014though implicit\u2014[[Antireductionism|anti-reductionalist]] [[ontology]], writes: \"No other writer is so perplexed by the gap between objects and the power of language to describe them, or between objects and the qualities they possess.\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Harman |first=Graham |url=https://books.google.com/?id=XQ_tBAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |title=Weird Realism: Lovecraft and Philosophy |date=2012-09-28 |publisher=John Hunt Publishing |isbn=978-1-78099-907-4 |page=3 |language=en}}</ref>\nHarman said of leading figures at the initial [[speculative realism]] conference (which included philosophers [[Quentin Meillassoux]], [[Ray Brassier]], and [[Iain Hamilton Grant]]) that, though they shared no philosophical heroes, all were enthusiastic readers of Lovecraft.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Speculative realists, [[Mark Fisher (theorist)|Mark Fisher]] and other contemporary philosophers, took Lovecraft seriously, mainly because Lovecraft's weird reality as presented in his novels, had nothing to do with the Gothic's insistence in the supernatural, but presented another reality incomprehensible to the human mind, but nonetheless real. According to scholar [[S. T. Joshi]]: \"There is never an entity in Lovecraft that is not in some fashion material.\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ubE5ylK0GTgC&pg=PA186&dq=There+is+never+an+entity+in+Lovecraft+that+is+not+in+some+fashion+material.#v=onepage&q=There%20is%20never%20an%20entity%20in%20Lovecraft%20that%20is%20not%20in%20some%20fashion%20material.&f=false |title=The Weird Tale |date=2003-01-01 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-0-8095-3122-6 |page=186 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Influence on culture==\n[[File:H. P. Lovecraft Memorial Plaque at 22 Prospect Street.jpg|thumb|H. P. Lovecraft memorial plaque at 22 Prospect Street in [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]].]]\n{{main|Lovecraftian horror|Cthulhu Mythos in popular culture}}\n{{more citations needed section|date=May 2012}}\n\nLovecraft was relatively unknown during his own time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.denofgeek.com/movies/16993/hp-lovecraft-an-appreciation |title=HP Lovecraft: an appreciation |date=February 8, 2011 |website=denofgeek.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425231937/http://www.denofgeek.com/movies/16993/hp-lovecraft-an-appreciation |archive-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> While his stories appeared in the pages of prominent pulp magazines such as ''Weird Tales'' (eliciting letters of outrage as often as letters of praise from regular readers), not many people knew his name. He did, however, correspond regularly with other contemporary writers such as Clark Ashton Smith and August Derleth,<ref>{{Cite book |last=Schoell |first=William |title=H.P. Lovecraft: Master of Weird Fiction |publisher=Morgan Reynolds |year=2004 |isbn=9781931798150 |pages=8\u201340}}</ref> who became good friends of his, even though they never met in person. This group of writers became known as the \"Lovecraft Circle,\" since their writing freely borrowed elements of Lovecraft's stories, with his encouragement: the mysterious books with disturbing names, the pantheon of ancient alien entities such as Cthulhu and Azathoth, and eldritch places such as the New England town of [[Arkham]] and its [[Miskatonic University]].\n\nAfter Lovecraft's death, the Lovecraft Circle carried on. August Derleth in particular added to and expanded on Lovecraft's vision, not without controversy. While Lovecraft considered his pantheon of alien gods a mere plot device, Derleth created an entire cosmology, complete with a war between the good [[Elder God (Cthulhu Mythos)|Elder Gods]] and the evil [[Outer God]]s, such as [[Cthulhu]] and his ilk. The forces of good were supposed to have won, locking Cthulhu and others up beneath the earth, in the ocean, and so forth. Derleth's Cthulhu Mythos stories went on to associate different gods with the traditional four [[Classical element|elements of fire, air, earth and water]] \u2014 an artificial constraint which required rationalizations on Derleth's part as Lovecraft himself never envisioned such a scheme.\n\nLovecraft's fiction has been grouped into three categories by some critics. While Lovecraft did not refer to these categories himself, he did once write: \"There are my 'Poe' pieces and my '[[Edward Plunkett, 18th Baron of Dunsany|Dunsany]] pieces' \u2014 but alas \u2014 where are any Lovecraft pieces?\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=The New Annotated H. P. Lovecraft |date=October 13, 2014 |publisher=W. W. Norton & Company |isbn=978-1-63149-055-2 |editor-last=Klinger |editor-first=Leslie S. |page=xxiii |language=en}}</ref>\n* Macabre stories ({{circa}} 1905\u20131920);\n* [[Dream Cycle]] stories ({{circa}} 1920\u20131927);\n* [[Cthulhu Mythos|Cthulhu{{\\}}Lovecraft Mythos]] stories ({{circa}} 1925\u20131935).\n\nLovecraft's writing, particularly the so-called Cthulhu Mythos, has influenced fiction authors including modern horror and fantasy writers. [[Stephen King]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.americanheritage.com/man-who-can-scare-stephen-king |title=The Man Who Can Scare Stephen King &#124; AMERICAN HERITAGE |website=www.americanheritage.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725231046/https://www.americanheritage.com/man-who-can-scare-stephen-king |archive-date=July 25, 2019}}</ref> [[Ramsey Campbell]], [[Bentley Little]], [[Joe R. Lansdale]], [[Alan Moore]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://thequietus.com/articles/16129-alan-moore-providence-cthulhu-philosophy-language-lovecraft |title=All About Alienation: Alan Moore On Lovecraft And Providence |last=Talbot |first=Nick |date=August 31, 2014 |website=The Quietus}}</ref> [[Junji Ito]], [[F. Paul Wilson]], [[Brian Lumley]], [[Caitl\u00edn R. Kiernan]], [[William S. Burroughs]], and [[Neil Gaiman]], have cited Lovecraft as one of their primary influences. Beyond direct adaptation, Lovecraft and his stories have had a profound impact on popular culture. Some influence was direct, as he was a friend, inspiration, and correspondent to many of his contemporaries, such as August Derleth, Robert E. Howard, Robert Bloch and [[Fritz Leiber]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-17472580 |title=The long hand of Lovecraft |date=March 22, 2012 |work=BBC News |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712064826/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-17472580 |archive-date=July 12, 2018 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Many later figures were influenced by Lovecraft's works, including author and artist [[Clive Barker]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5k6mfyb3lld560XTKQmCG9Q/a-quick-guide-to-the-best-cult-authors |title=BBC Radio 4 - The Case of Charles Dexter Ward - A quick guide to the best cult authors |website=BBC |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817170958/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5k6mfyb3lld560XTKQmCG9Q/a-quick-guide-to-the-best-cult-authors |archive-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> prolific horror writer Stephen King,<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\" /> Brian Keene<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.briankeene.com/ |title=Brian Keene |website=Brian Keene |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170522065823/http://www.briankeene.com/ |archive-date=May 22, 2017}}</ref> has several novels based on the Old Gods, comics writers Alan Moore, Neil Gaiman<ref name=\"irishtimes.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/hp-lovecraft-love-the-craft-loathe-the-creed-1.2489413 |title=HP Lovecraft: love the craft, loathe the creed |website=irishtimes.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421192246/http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/hp-lovecraft-love-the-craft-loathe-the-creed-1.2489413 |archive-date=April 21, 2016}}</ref> and [[Mike Mignola]], English author [[Colin Wilson]], film directors [[John Carpenter]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.denofgeek.com/movies/18189/hp-lovecraft-and-his-lasting-impact-on-cinema |title=HP Lovecraft and his lasting impact on cinema |date=October 14, 2011 |website=denofgeek.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160801213417/http://www.denofgeek.com/movies/18189/hp-lovecraft-and-his-lasting-impact-on-cinema |archive-date=August 1, 2016}}</ref> [[Stuart Gordon]], [[Guillermo del Toro]]<ref name=\"irishtimes.com\" /> and artist [[H. R. Giger]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Giger |first=H. R. |title=Necronomicon |publisher=Morpheus International |year=1993 |isbn=978-0962344725 |edition=New |orig-year=1977}}</ref> Japan has also been significantly inspired and terrified by Lovecraft's creations and thus even entered the [[manga]] and [[anime]] media. [[Chiaki J. Konaka]] is an acknowledged disciple and has participated in Cthulhu Mythos, expanding several Japanese versions.<ref name=\"askjohn546\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.animenation.net/blog/2002/08/13/ask-john-is-there-any-lovecraftian-anime/ |title=Ask John: Is There Any Lovecraftian Anime? |publisher=[[AnimeNation]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020813010101/http://www.animenation.net/blog/2002/08/13/ask-john-is-there-any-lovecraftian-anime/ |archive-date=August 13, 2002}}</ref> He is an anime scriptwriter who tends to add elements of cosmicism, and is credited for spreading the influence of Lovecraft among the anime base.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Bush |first=Laurence |title=Asian Horror Encyclopedia |publisher=Writers Club Press |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-595-20181-5 |pages=101\u2013102}}</ref> Along with [[Junji Ito]], other influential manga artists have also been inspired by Lovecraft.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Ito |first=Junji |title=Uzumaki, Vol. 1 |date=October 2007 |publisher=[[Viz Media]] |isbn=978-1-4215-1389-8 |edition=2nd |page=207 |orig-year=1998}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.78magazine.com/issues/03-01/arts/junji.shtml |title=Into the Spiral: A Conversation with Japanese Horror Maestro Junji Ito |last=Mira Bai Winsby |date=March 2006 |website=78 Magazine |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022184345/http://www.78magazine.com/issues/03-01/arts/junji.shtml |archive-date=October 22, 2014}}</ref> Novelist and manga author, [[Hideyuki Kikuchi]], incorporated a number of locations, beings and events from the works of Lovecraft into the manga ''[[Taimashin]]''.<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=TAIMASHIN: Vol. 1 Hideyuki Kikuchi, Author, Misaki Saitoh, Illustrator |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-4139-0036-1 |magazine=[[Publishers Weekly]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122053700/http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-4139-0036-1 |archive-date=January 22, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nArgentine writer [[Jorge Luis Borges]] wrote his short story \"[[There Are More Things]]\" in memory of Lovecraft. Contemporary French writer [[Michel Houellebecq]] wrote a literary biography of Lovecraft called ''[[H. P. Lovecraft: Against the World, Against Life]]''. Prolific American writer Joyce Carol Oates wrote an introduction for a collection of Lovecraft stories. The [[Library of America]] published a volume of Lovecraft's work in 2005, a reversal of traditional judgment that \"has been nothing so far from the accepted [[Western canon|canon]] as Lovecraft.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.loa.org/volume.jsp?RequestID=223 |title=H.P Lovecraft: Tales (The Library of America) |last=H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=Loa.org |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100221224608/http://www.loa.org/volume.jsp?RequestID=223 |archive-date=February 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |date=March 7, 2005 |title=The Horror, the Horror! |url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/Content/Public/Articles/000/000/005/285tmhfa.asp |magazine=The Weekly Standard |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091105095444/http://www.weeklystandard.com/Content/Public/Articles/000/000/005/285tmhfa.asp |archive-date=November 5, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boston.com/ae/books/articles/2005/02/15/the_library_of_america_scares_up_a_collection_of_lovecrafts_local_lore/ |title=The Library of America scares up a collection of Lovecraft's local lore |last=Kenney |first=Michael |date=February 15, 2005 |publisher=Boston.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005004203/http://www.boston.com/ae/books/articles/2005/02/15/the_library_of_america_scares_up_a_collection_of_lovecrafts_local_lore/ |archive-date=October 5, 2013}}</ref> French philosophers [[Gilles Deleuze]] and [[F\u00e9lix Guattari]] refer to Lovecraft in ''[[A Thousand Plateaus]]'', calling the short story \"[[Through the Gates of the Silver Key]]\" one of his masterpieces.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Deleuze |first=Gilles |title=A Thousand Plateaus: Capitalism and Schizophrenia |last2=Guattari |first2=F\u00e9lix |date=1987 |publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]] |isbn=978-0816614011 |location=Minneapolis |pages=240, 539 |translator-last=Massumi |translator-first=Brian |oclc=16472336}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nLovecraft's fictional Mythos has influenced a number of musicians, especially in [[rock music]].  Most notably, the [[psychedelic rock]] band [[H. P. Lovecraft (band)|H. P. Lovecraft]] (who shortened their name to Lovecraft and then Love Craft in the 1970s) released the albums ''[[H. P. Lovecraft (album)|H. P. Lovecraft]]'' and ''[[H. P. Lovecraft II]]'' in 1967 and 1968 respectively; their songs included ''[[The White Ship (song)|The White Ship]]'' and ''At the Mountains of Madness'', both titled after Lovecraft stories. The founders of their record company, [[Bill Traut]] and George Badonsky, were fans of the author and gained August Derleth's permission to use Lovecraft's name for the band.<ref name=\"warburton\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thewhiteship.org/index.php/h-p-lovecraft-history/ |title=The White Ship: The Psychedelic Voyage of H.P. Lovecraft |publisher=Nick Warburton's Rock Music Archive |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180110201805/http://www.thewhiteship.org/index.php/h-p-lovecraft-history |archive-date=January 10, 2018 |access-date=January 31, 2018 }}</ref> [[Metallica]] recorded a song inspired by \"The Call of Cthulhu\", an instrumental titled ''The Call of Ktulu'', a song based on ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]'' titled ''The Thing That Should Not Be'' and another based on [[Frank Belknap Long]]'s ''[[Hounds of Tindalos]]'' titled ''[[All Nightmare Long]]''. Later, they released the song ''Dream No More'', which mentions the awakening of Cthulhu.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/M/Metallica/2008/12/08/7668306-sun.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120524233607/http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/M/Metallica/2008/12/08/7668306-sun.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 24, 2012 |title=CANOE \u2013 JAM! Music \u2013 Artists \u2013 Metallica: Interview with James Hetfield |date=December 8, 2008 |publisher=Jam.canoe.ca |access-date=October 3, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://loudwire.com/hp-lovecraft-inspried-metal-songs/ |title=11 METAL SONGS INSPIRED BY H.P. LOVECRAFT |website=Loudwire |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709162311/https://loudwire.com/hp-lovecraft-inspried-metal-songs/ |archive-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> Technical death metal outfit [[Revocation (band)]] frequently write songs based on Lovecraft's stories and frequently use him as inspiration in their original works.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/editorials/277677/metal-mike-into-the-madness-of-death-metal-sci-fi-horror-with-revocation/ |title=Metal & Mike: Into The Madness Of Death Metal, Sci-Fi & Horror With REVOCATION |last=Pementel |first=Michael |date=September 14, 2018 |website=Dread Central |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708222308/https://www.dreadcentral.com/editorials/277677/metal-mike-into-the-madness-of-death-metal-sci-fi-horror-with-revocation/ |archive-date=July 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, [[Synthwave]] band, [[Gunship (band)|Gunship]] released a track called Cthulhu that featured an introductory monologue by [[Corin Hardy]]. Hardy's opening monologue makes reference to Lovecraft's Cthulhu Mythos directly mentioning the \"Great Old Ones\", the cults that worshipped them and the city in which Cthulhu resided, R'lyeh.\n\nAccording to the band's official YouTube channel, Gunship member, Dan Haigh, was quoted as saying:<blockquote>I just felt like writing something creeping, twisted, and possibly dripping with slime. Most importantly, I felt like creating something transportative. I hope the track takes its listeners on a journey to the darkest corners of their imaginations\u2026 listen \u2013 taste the salt on the sea air \u2013 witness the slathering foul beast rise from his slumber\u2026<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jo4-Bc85bF4 |title=GUNSHIP - CTHULHU (feat. Corin Hardy) [Official Audio] |date=February 11, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221041808/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jo4-Bc85bF4&gl=US&hl=en&has_verified=1&bpctr=9999999999 |archive-date=December 21, 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Games===\nLovecraft has also influenced gaming, despite having hated games during his lifetime.<ref name=\"Letters 1932-1934\">{{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=Selected Letters: 1932-1934 |title-link=Selected Letters of H. P. Lovecraft IV (1932\u20131934) |date=1965 |publisher=Arkham House |isbn=9780870540356 |volume=4 |page=13 |language=en}}</ref> [[Chaosium]]'s [[Tabletop role-playing game|tabletop]] [[role-playing game]] ''[[Call of Cthulhu (role-playing game)|Call of Cthulhu]]'', released in 1981 and currently in its seventh major edition, was one of the first games to draw heavily from Lovecraft. Novel to the game was the Lovecraft-inspired [[insanity]] mechanic, which allowed for [[player character]]s to go insane from contact with cosmic horrors. This mechanic would go on to make appearance in subsequent table top and [[video game]]s.<ref name=\"Gollop17\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/the-gollop-chamber-where-are-all-the-lovecraftian-games/ |title=The Gollop Chamber: Where are all the Lovecraftian games? |last=Gollop |first=Julian |date=November 16, 2017 |website=pcgamer |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307151043/https://www.pcgamer.com/the-gollop-chamber-where-are-all-the-lovecraftian-games/ |archive-date=March 7, 2018}}</ref>\n1987 saw the release of one of the first Lovecraftian [[board game]]s, ''[[Arkham Horror]]'', which sold extremely well, and since 2004 is still in print from [[Fantasy Flight Games]].\nThough few subsequent Lovecraftian board games were released annually between 1987 and 2014, the years after 2014 saw a surge in the number of Lovecraftian board games, possibly because of the entry of Lovecraft's work into the [[public domain]] combined with a revival of interest in board games.<ref name=\"Silva17\">{{Cite news |last=Silva |first=Christianna |url=https://www.npr.org/2017/06/07/530186764/h-p-lovecrafts-monster-is-wrapping-family-game-night-up-in-tentacles |title=H.P. Lovecraft's Monster Is Wrapping Family Game Night Up In Tentacles |date=June 7, 2017 |work=NPR.org |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228173021/https://www.npr.org/2017/06/07/530186764/h-p-lovecrafts-monster-is-wrapping-family-game-night-up-in-tentacles |archive-date=February 28, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nFew video games are direct adaptations of Lovecraft's works, but many video games have been inspired or heavily influenced by Lovecraft.<ref name=\"Gollop17\" />\nThe massively-multiplayer online game ''[[World of Warcraft]]'' by [[Blizzard Entertainment]] has continually revealed more of the origin story of the game's playable world to the players, most of which very closely mirrors Lovecraft's work or Derleth's expansion onto the author's original content.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/11/06/know-your-lore-tinfoil-hat-edition-the-genesis-of-azeroth/ |title=Know Your Lore, Tinfoil Hat Edition: The genesis of Azeroth |work=Engadget |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116111659/https://www.engadget.com/2011/11/06/know-your-lore-tinfoil-hat-edition-the-genesis-of-azeroth/ |archive-date=November 16, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>  [[Survival horror|Horror games]] especially can incorporate Cthulthean terrors, despite the conflict between \"act-and-prevail\" nature of video games and the cosmic hopelessness of Lovecraftian horror.\nBesides employing Cthulthean antagonists, games that invoke Lovecraftian horror have used mechanics such as insanity effects, or even [[fourth wall]] breaking effects that suggest to players that something has gone wrong with their [[Video game console|game consoles]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Perron |first=Bernard |url=https://books.google.com/?id=pNaQLQC9XhEC&pg=PA267&dq=cosmic+horror+in+video+games#v=onepage |title=Horror Video Games: Essays on the Fusion of Fear and Play |date=August 25, 2009 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786454792 |pages=279\u2013285 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Religion and occultism===\nSeveral contemporary religions have drawn influence from the works of Lovecraft. ''[[The Satanic Rituals]]'', written either by [[Anton LaVey]] or Michael A. Aquino, includes an essay which claims that the works of Lovecraft carry a partial truth, used in the same symbolic manner as [[Satan]]. [[Kenneth Grant]] of the [[Typhonian Order]] incorporated Lovecraft's Mythos into his ritual and occult system, but in a more direct and literal sense than the Church of Satan. However, the Typhonian Order does not consider the entities to be directly existent, but rather a symbol through which people may interact with something inhuman.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.popmatters.com/cults-of-an-unwitting-oracle-the-unintended-religious-legacy-of-h-p-lovecraft-2496158350.html |title=Cults of an Unwitting Oracle: The (Unintended) Religious Legacy of H. P. Lovecraft |last=Quinn |first=Dennis P. |date=August 19, 2010 |website=PopMatters |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111195159/https://www.popmatters.com/cults-of-an-unwitting-oracle-the-unintended-religious-legacy-of-h-p-lovecraft-2496158350.html |archive-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Engle |first=John |date=October 15, 2014 |title=Cults of Lovecraft: The Impact of H.P. Lovecraft's Fiction on Contemporary Occult Practices |url=https://dc.swosu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1034&context=mythlore |journal=Mythlore |volume=33 |issue=125 |pages=85\u201398 |via=SWOSU Digital Commons}}</ref> \n\nThere have been several books that have claimed to be an authentic edition of Lovecraft's ''[[Necronomicon]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Clore |first=Dan |date=n.d. |orig-year=first published Fall 2001 |title=The Lurker on the Threshold of Interpretation: Hoax ''Necronomicons'' and Paratextual Noise |url=http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/9879/lurker.htm |journal=Lovecraft Studies |pages=61\u201369 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091026163759/http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/9879/lurker.htm |archive-date=October 26, 2009 |via=Yahoo! GeoCities}}</ref> The ''[[Simon Necronomicon]]'' is one such example. It was written by an unknown figure who identified themselves as \"Simon.\" [[Peter Levenda]], an occult author who has written about the ''Necronomicon'', claims that he and \"Simon\" came across a hidden Greek translation of the grimoire while looking through a collection of antiquities at a New York bookstore during the 1960s or 1970s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tMMrqUS8-As |title=Finding the Simon Necronomicon |date=Nov 30, 2014 |publisher=The Lip TV |language=en |via=YouTube |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208154000/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tMMrqUS8-As |archive-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref> This book was claimed to have born the seal of the ''Necronomicon''. Levenda went on to claim that Lovecraft had access to this purported scroll.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Matthews |first=Carol S. |date=April 15, 2018 |title=Letting Sleeping Abnormalities Lie |url=https://dc.swosu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1160&context=mythlore |journal=Mythlore |volume=36 |issue=2 |pages=165\u2013184 |via=SWOSU Digital Commons}}</ref> A textual analysis has determined that the contents of this book were derived from multiple documents that discuss [[Ancient Mesopotamian religion|Mesopotamian myth]] and magic. The finding of a magical text by monks is also a common theme in the history of grimoires.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Davies |first=Owen |url=https://books.google.com/?id=_iaQDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=The%20most%20successful%20of%20the%20print%20editions%20was%20the%20Simon%20Necronomicon%2C%20a%20ninth-century%20Greek%20text%20discovered%20by%20monks%20and%20brought%20to%20America%20in%20the%201970s%20by%20an%20Eastern%20Orthodox%20bishop%20named%20Simon.&f=false |title=Grimoires: A History of Magic Books |date=March 26, 2009 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-154810-9 |page=268 |language=en}}</ref> It has been suggested that Lavenda is the true author of the ''Simon Necronomicon''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/11/12/4849860/the-cult-of-cthulhu-real-prayer-for-a-fake-tentacle |title=The Cult of Cthulhu: Real Prayer for a Fake Tentacle |last=Flatley |first=Joseph L. |date=November 12, 2013 |website=The Verge |language=en-US |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029013156/https://www.theverge.com/2013/11/12/4849860/the-cult-of-cthulhu-real-prayer-for-a-fake-tentacle |archive-date=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Lovecraft as a fictional character===\n{{Primary sources|section|date=January 2020}}\n\nAside from his appearance in [[Robert Bloch]]'s ''[[The Shambler from the Stars]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blog.loa.org/2010/09/what-robert-bloch-owes-to-h-p-lovecraft.html |title=What Robert Bloch owes to H. P. Lovecraft |date=September 23, 2010 |publisher=The Library of America |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101021030024/http://blog.loa.org/2010/09/what-robert-bloch-owes-to-h-p-lovecraft.html |archive-date=October 21, 2010}}</ref> Lovecraft continues to be used as a character in supernatural fiction. He makes a brief appearance in an early version of [[Ray Bradbury]]'s ''The Exiles''.<ref>Published in ''[[The Magazine of Fantasy & Science Fiction]]'', Volume 1 No. 2 (Winter-Spring 1950), and later to become part of Bradbury's ''[[Martian Chronicles]]''</ref> [[John Shirley]]'s story ''When Death Wakes Me To Myself'' offers a tale of a therapy patient slowly remembering a former incarnation when he was H. P. Lovecraft.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hippocampuspress.com/mythos-and-other-authors/fiction/lovecraft-alive-a-collection-of-lovecraftian-stories-by-john-shirley |title=Lovecraft Alive! A Collection of Lovecraftian Stories by John Shirley |date=July 4, 2016 |publisher=Hippocampus Press |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161015160545/http://www.hippocampuspress.com/mythos-and-other-authors/fiction/lovecraft-alive-a-collection-of-lovecraftian-stories-by-john-shirley |archive-date=October 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOther notable works with Lovecraft as a character include [[Richard Lupoff]]'s ''Lovecraft's Book'' (1985), ''[[Cast a Deadly Spell]]'' (1991), ''[[H.P. Lovecraft's: Necronomicon]]'' (1993), ''[[Witch Hunt (1994 film)|Witch Hunt]]'' (1994), ''[[Out of Mind: The Stories of H. P. Lovecraft]]'' (1998), ''[[Stargate SG-1: Roswell]]'' (2007), and [[Alan Moore]]'s comic ''[[Providence (Avatar Press)|Providence]]'' (2015\u201317). Lovecraft also appears in the Season 6, Episode 21 episode ''Let it Bleed'' of the TV show ''[[Supernatural (U.S. TV series)|Supernatural]]''. A satirical version of Lovecraft named H. P. Hatecraft appeared as a recurring character on the [[Cartoon Network]] television series ''[[Scooby-Doo! Mystery Incorporated]]''. Another character based on Lovecraft appears in ''[[Afterlife with Archie]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sullivan |first=Justin |url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/comics/afterlife-with-archie-sabrina-the-teenage-witch-returns/#/8 |title='Afterlife With Archie': Sabrina the Teenage Witch returns |date=July 22, 2014 |work=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514225633/http://herocomplex.latimes.com/comics/afterlife-with-archie-sabrina-the-teenage-witch-returns/#/8 |archive-date=May 14, 2015}}</ref> He appears as a minor character in [[Brian Clevinger]]'s comic book series ''[[Atomic Robo]]'', as an acquaintance and fellow-scientist of [[Nikola Tesla]], having been driven insane by his involvement in the [[Tunguska event]] which exposed him to the hidden horrors of the wider universe. He is eventually killed when his body becomes host to an extradimensional being infecting the timestream.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.atomic-robo.com/atomicrobo/v3ch1-page-19 |title=Atomic Robo - v3ch1 Page 19 |website=www.atomic-robo.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629172346/http://www.atomic-robo.com/atomicrobo/v3ch1-page-19 |archive-date=June 29, 2019}}</ref> Lovecraft is a central plot element, as well as a character in [[Paul LaFarge|Paul La Farge]]'s 2017 novel, ''The Night Ocean''.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Michaud |first=Jon |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/paul-la-farges-the-night-ocean-will-suck-you-into-the-vortex-of-hp-lovecraft/2017/03/02/4d8e1896-ff7e-11e6-8ebe-6e0dbe4f2bca_story.html |title=Paul La Farge's 'The Night Ocean' will suck you into the vortex of H.P. Lovecraft |date=March 2, 2017 |work=The Washington Post |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305111828/https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/paul-la-farges-the-night-ocean-will-suck-you-into-the-vortex-of-hp-lovecraft/2017/03/02/4d8e1896-ff7e-11e6-8ebe-6e0dbe4f2bca_story.html |archive-date=March 5, 2017 |last2=Michaud |first2=Jon |language=en-US |issn=0190-8286}}</ref> In the Japanese manga and anime ''[[Bungo Stray Dogs]]'' there is a character known as Howard Phillips Lovecraft who, like other characters in the series, is named after great literates. His power, \"The Great Old Ones\" pays homage to his classic short story, \"The Call of Cthulhu\" which grants him the ability of transforming himself into an octopus-like monster resembling Cthulhu.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Kafka |first=Asagiri |title=\u6587\u8c6a\u30b9\u30c8\u30ec\u30a4\u30c9\u30c3\u30b0\u30b9 (Bungou Stray Dogs) Volume 5 |publisher=Kadokawa Shoten |year=2014 |isbn=978-4-04-101539-1}}</ref>\n\n== Editions and collections of works ==\n{{more citations needed section|date=May 2012}}\n\nFor most of the 20th century, the definitive editions (specifically ''At the Mountains of Madness and Other Novels'', ''Dagon and Other Macabre Tales'', ''The Dunwich Horror and Others'', and ''The Horror in the Museum and Other Revisions'') of his prose fiction were published by [[Arkham House]], a publisher originally started with the intent of publishing the work of Lovecraft, but which has since published a considerable amount of other literature as well. [[Penguin Classics]] has at present issued three volumes of Lovecraft's works: ''[[The Call of Cthulhu and Other Weird Stories]]'', ''[[The Thing on the Doorstep and Other Weird Stories]]'', and most recently ''[[The Dreams in the Witch House and Other Weird Stories]]''. They collect the standard texts as edited by S. T. Joshi, most of which were available in the Arkham House editions, with the exception of the restored text of ''The Shadow Out of Time'' from ''The Dreams in the Witch House'', which had been previously released by small-press publisher [[Hippocampus Press]]. In 2005 the prestigious [[Library of America]] canonized Lovecraft with a volume of his stories edited by [[Peter Straub]], and Random House's [[Modern Library]] line have issued the \"definitive edition\" of Lovecraft's ''At the Mountains of Madness'' (also including ''[[Supernatural Horror in Literature]]''). In 2014, Liveright Publishing Corp./W. W. Norton published ''The New Annotated H. P. Lovecraft'', edited by [[Leslie S. Klinger]], containing 22 of Lovecraft's tales, with an introduction by [[Alan Moore]]; in September 2019, the second volume of Klinger's annotations, ''The New Annotated H. P. Lovecraft: Beyond Arkham'', containing another 25 of Lovecraft's tales, will appear, together with an introduction by [[Victor LaValle]]. Both volumes are heavily illustrated.\n\nLovecraft's poetry is collected in ''The Ancient Track: The Complete Poetical Works of H. P. Lovecraft'' (Night Shade Books, 2001), while much of his juvenilia, various essays on philosophical, political and literary topics, antiquarian travelogues, and other things, can be found in ''Miscellaneous Writings'' (Arkham House, 1989). Lovecraft's essay ''Supernatural Horror in Literature'', first published in 1927, is a historical survey of horror literature available with endnotes as ''The Annotated Supernatural Horror in Literature''.\n\n===Letters, correspondence, exchange, and contract work===\nAlthough Lovecraft is known mostly for his works of [[weird fiction]], the bulk of his writing consists of voluminous letters about a variety of topics, from weird fiction and art criticism to politics and history. Lovecraft's biographer [[L. Sprague de Camp]] estimates that Lovecraft wrote 100,000 letters in his lifetime, a fifth of which are believed to survive.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/letters/ |title=Lovecraft's Letters |date=September 18, 2019 |website=www.hplovecraft.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628015736/http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/letters/ |archive-date=June 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe sometimes dated his letters 200 years before the current date, which would have put the writing back in US colonial times, before the [[American Revolution]] (a war that offended his Anglophilia). He explained that he thought that the 18th and 20th centuries were the \"best,\" the former being a period of noble grace, and the latter a century of science.\n\nLovecraft was not an active letter-writer in youth. In 1931 he admitted: \"In youth I scarcely did any letter-writing&nbsp;\u2014 thanking anybody for a present was so much of an ordeal that I would rather have written a two hundred fifty-line pastoral or a twenty-page treatise on the rings of Saturn.\" (SL 3.369\u201370). The initial interest in letters stemmed from his correspondence with his cousin Phillips Gamwell but even more important was his involvement in the amateur journalism movement, which was initially responsible for the enormous number of letters Lovecraft produced.\n\nDespite his light letter-writing in youth, in later life his correspondence was so voluminous that it has been estimated that he may have written around 30,000 letters to various correspondents, a figure which places him second only to [[Voltaire]] as an epistolarian. Lovecraft's later correspondence is primarily to fellow weird fiction writers, rather than to the amateur journalist friends of his earlier years.\n\nLovecraft clearly states that his contact to numerous different people through letter-writing was one of the main factors in broadening his view of the world: \"I found myself opened up to dozens of points of view which would otherwise never have occurred to me. My understanding and sympathies were enlarged, and many of my social, political, and economic views were modified as a consequence of increased knowledge.\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |url=https://books.google.com/?id=YdO2XRYNUuQC&pg=PA248&lpg=PA248&dq=I+found+myself+opened+up+to+dozens+of+points+of+view+which+would+otherwise+never+have+occurred+to+me.+My+understanding+and+sympathies+were+enlarged,+and+many+of+my+social,+political,+and+economic+views+were+modified+as+a+consequence+of+increased+knowledge.#v=onepage&q=I%20found%20myself%20opened%20up%20to%20dozens%20of%20points%20of%20view%20which%20would%20otherwise%20never%20have%20occurred%20to%20me.%20My%20understanding%20and%20sympathies%20were%20enlarged,%20and%20many%20of%20my%20social,%20political,%20and%20economic%20views%20were%20modified%20as%20a%20consequence%20of%20increased%20knowledge.&f=false |title=A Subtler Magick: The Writings and Philosophy of H.P. Lovecraft |date=December 1, 1996 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-1-880448-61-8 |edition=Third |page=248 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nToday there are five publishing houses that have released letters from Lovecraft, most prominently Arkham House with its five-volume edition ''Selected Letters'' (these volumes severely abridge the letters they contain). Other publishers are [[Hippocampus Press]] (''Letters to Alfred Galpin'' ''et al.''), [[Night Shade Books]] (''Mysteries of Time and Spirit: The Letters of H. P. Lovecraft and Donald Wandrei'' ''et al.''.), [[Necronomicon Press]] (''Letters to Samuel Loveman and Vincent Starrett'' et al.), and University of Tampa Press (''O Fortunate Floridian: H. P. Lovecraft's Letters to R. H. Barlow''). [[S. T. Joshi]] is supervising an ongoing series of volumes collecting Lovecraft's unabridged letters to particular correspondents.\n\n===Copyright and other legal issues===\nDespite several claims to the contrary, there is currently no evidence that any company or individual owns the copyright to any of Lovecraft's work, and it is generally accepted that it has passed into the public domain.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gizmology.net/lovecraft/copyrights.htm |title=The H. P. Lovecraft Library |date=October 3, 2003 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031003114117/http://www.gizmology.net/lovecraft/copyrights.htm |archive-date=October 3, 2003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.aetherial.net/lovecraft/arkham.html |title=The Black Seas of Copyright: Arkham House Publishers and the H.P. Lovecraft Copyrights |website=www.aetherial.net |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224195604/http://www.aetherial.net/lovecraft/arkham.html |archive-date=February 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20110531/02515814477/confusing-case-lovecrafts-copyrights.shtml |title=The Confusing Case Of Lovecraft's Copyrights {{!}} Techdirt |website=Techdirt. |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225040818/https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20110531/02515814477/confusing-case-lovecrafts-copyrights.shtml |archive-date=February 25, 2016}}</ref> Most of his works have been in the public domain outside of the USA since January 1, 2008, 70 calendar years after his death. Works he published during his lifetime between 1925 and 1937 will indisputably be out of copyright as they enter the public domain annually between 2021 and 2033 (pre-1978 works do not use the life+70 rule in the USA).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://copyright.cornell.edu/publicdomain |title=Copyright Term and the Public Domain in the United States &#124; Copyright Information Center |website=copyright.cornell.edu |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911204703/https://copyright.cornell.edu/publicdomain |archive-date=September 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThere has been controversy over the [[copyright]] status of many of Lovecraft's works, especially his later works. Lovecraft had specified that the young [[R. H. Barlow]] would serve as executor of his [[literary estate]],<ref>{{Harvnb|Joshi, Schultz|2001|p=16|ref=hplencyclopedia}}</ref> but these instructions were not incorporated into the will. Nevertheless, his surviving aunt carried out his expressed wishes, and Barlow was given charge of the massive and complex literary estate upon Lovecraft's death.\n\nBarlow deposited the bulk of the papers, including the voluminous correspondence, with the [[John Hay Library]], and attempted to organize and maintain Lovecraft's other writing. [[August Derleth]], an older and more established writer than Barlow, vied for control of the literary estate. One result of these conflicts was the legal confusion over who owned what copyrights.\n\nAll works published before 1925 are [[public domain]] in the US.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.copyright.gov/circs/circ22.pdf |title=How to Investigate the Copyright Status of a Work- U.S. Copyright Office |website=copyright.gov |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100810065221/http://www.copyright.gov/circs/circ22.pdf |archive-date=August 10, 2010}}</ref> With respect to works published later, ownership of the copyrights is disputed.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Before the United States [[Copyright Act of 1976]], copyright lasted for 28 years from publication and a work that did not have its copyright renewed passed into the public domain. The [[Copyright Act of 1976]] retroactively extended this renewal period for all works to a period of 47 years and the [[Copyright Term Extension Act]] of 1998 added another 20 years to that, for a total of 95 years from publication. But everything turned on the renewal or expiration of copyright at the end of the first 28-year term.\n\nThe [[European Union]] [[Copyright Duration Directive]] of 1993 extended the copyrights to 70 years after the author's death. All of Lovecraft's works published during his lifetime became public domain in all 27 European Union countries on January 1, 2008. In those [[Berne Convention for the Protection of Literary and Artistic Works|Berne Convention]] countries that have implemented only the minimum copyright period, copyright expires 50 years after the author's death.\n\nLovecraft prot\u00e9g\u00e9s and part owners of Arkham House, August Derleth and [[Donald Wandrei]], often claimed copyrights over Lovecraft's works. On October 9, 1947, Derleth purchased all rights to ''Weird Tales''. However, since April 1926 at the latest, Lovecraft had reserved to himself all second printing rights to stories published in ''Weird Tales''. ''Weird Tales'' may only have owned the rights to at most six of Lovecraft's tales. Again, even if Derleth did obtain the copyrights to Lovecraft's tales, there is no evidence that the copyrights were renewed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gizmology.net/lovecraft/copyrights.htm |title=Copyright |last=William |first=Johns |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031003114117/http://www.gizmology.net/lovecraft/copyrights.htm |archive-date=October 3, 2003}}</ref> Following Derleth's death in 1971, his attorney proclaimed that all of Lovecraft's literary material was part of the Derleth estate and that it would be \"protected to the fullest extent possible.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.aetherial.net/lovecraft/arkham.html#13 |title=The Black Seas of Copyright: Arkham House Publishers and the H.P. Lovecraft Copyrights |last=Karr |first=Chris J. |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129043906/http://www.aetherial.net/lovecraft/arkham.html#13 |archive-date=November 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nS. T. Joshi concludes in his biography of Lovecraft that Derleth's claims are \"almost certainly fictitious\" and that most of Lovecraft's works published in the amateur press are most likely now in the public domain. The copyright for Lovecraft's works would have been inherited by the only surviving heir named in his 1912 will, his aunt Annie Gamwell. When Gamwell died in 1941, the copyrights passed to her remaining descendants, Ethel Phillips Morrish and Edna Lewis, who then signed a document, sometimes referred to as the Morrish-Lewis gift, permitting Arkham House to republish Lovecraft's works while retaining the copyrights for themselves. Searches of the [[Library of Congress]] have failed to find any evidence that these copyrights were renewed after the 28-year period, making it likely that these works are now in the public domain.\n\nChaosium, publishers of the ''Call of Cthulhu'' role-playing game, have a trademark on the phrase ''The Call of Cthulhu'' for use in game products. [[TSR, Inc.]], original publisher of the ''[[Advanced Dungeons & Dragons]]'' role-playing game, included a section on the Cthulhu Mythos in one of the game's earlier supplements, ''[[Deities & Demigods]]''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/arts/literature/cthulhu5.htm |title=How Cthulhu Works |date=September 4, 2007 |website=howstuffworks.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417100544/http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/arts/literature/cthulhu5.htm |archive-date=April 17, 2016}}</ref> (originally published in 1980 and later renamed to ''Legends & Lore''). TSR later agreed to remove this section at Chaosium's request.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.acaeum.com/ddindexes/setpages/deities.html |title=Deities & Demigods |website=www.acaeum.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812211053/https://www.acaeum.com/ddindexes/setpages/deities.html |archive-date=August 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Lovecraft Holdings, LLC, a company based out of Providence, filed trademark claims for clothing graphics of Lovecraft's name and silhouette.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://trademarks.justia.com/owners/lovecraft-holdings-llc-2613553/ |title=Lovecraft Holdings, LLC Trademarks |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141204170621/http://trademarks.justia.com/owners/lovecraft-holdings-llc-2613553/ |archive-date=December 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nRegardless of the legal disagreements surrounding Lovecraft's works, Lovecraft himself was extremely generous with his own works and encouraged others to borrow ideas from his stories and build on them, particularly with regard to his Cthulhu Mythos.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Mariconda |first=Steven John |url=https://books.google.com/?id=8bBoAAAAMAAJ&q=He+could+thus+encourage+their+use+of+his+Mythos+properties+and+ask+permission+to+use+theirs. |title=On the Emergence of \"Cthulhu\" & Other Observations |last2=Joshi |first2=S. T. |date=1995 |publisher=Necronomicon Press |isbn=978-0-940884-81-6 |page=34 |language=en}}</ref> He encouraged other writers to reference his creations, such as the ''[[Necronomicon]]'', Cthulhu and [[Yog-Sothoth]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bookmans.com/transcending-time-and-space-h-p-lovecraft-lives-on/ |title=Transcending Time and Space: H.P. Lovecraft Lives On |last=Lee P |date=2016 |website=Bookmans Entertainment Exchange |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020151027/https://bookmans.com/transcending-time-and-space-h-p-lovecraft-lives-on/ |archive-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> After his death, many writers have contributed stories and enriched the shared mythology of the Cthulhu Mythos, as well as making numerous references to his work.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{main|H. P. Lovecraft bibliography}}\n\n== Film adaptations ==\nFilms based on the writings of H. P. Lovecraft include the following.<ref name=\"Kaye\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/31-days-halloween-16-films-adapted-horror-giant-hp-lovecraft |title=31 Days of Halloween: 16 Films Adapted from Horror Giant H.P. Lovecraft |last=Kaye |first=Don |date=October 12, 2015 |website=SyFy |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180602135154/http://www.syfy.com/syfywire/31-days-halloween-16-films-adapted-horror-giant-hp-lovecraft |archive-date=June 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*''[[The Haunted Palace]]'' (1963), directed by [[Roger Corman]], starring [[Vincent Price]], and with [[Lon Chaney Jr.]].  Marketed as \"Edgar Allan Poe's ''The Haunted Palace''\", the film is actually based on ''[[The Case of Charles Dexter Ward]]'', and also includes elements taken from ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]'' and \"[[The Dunwich Horror]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lovecraftzine.com/2012/10/24/lovecraft-by-any-other-name-why-the-haunted-palace-is-great/ |title=Lovecraft by Any Other Name: Why ''The Haunted Palace'' Is Great |last=Lamssies |first=Dominique |date=October 24, 2012 |website=Lovecraft eZine |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121229181049/http://lovecraftzine.com/2012/10/24/lovecraft-by-any-other-name-why-the-haunted-palace-is-great/ |archive-date=December 29, 2012}}</ref>\n*''[[Die, Monster, Die!]]'' (1965), directed by [[Daniel Haller]], and starring [[Boris Karloff]] and [[Nick Adams (actor, born 1931)|Nick Adams]]. An adaptation of \"[[The Colour Out of Space]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.popmatters.com/178466-die-monster-die-2495693261.html |title=''Die, Monster, Die!'' |last=Macek |first=J.C. III |date=January 23, 2014 |website=PopMatters |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506220938/https://www.popmatters.com/178466-die-monster-die-2495693261.html |archive-date=May 6, 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[The Dunwich Horror (film)|The Dunwich Horror]]'' (1970), directed by Daniel Haller, and starring [[Sandra Dee]], [[Dean Stockwell]], and [[Ed Begley]]. Based on [[The Dunwich Horror|the short story of the same name]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wickedhorror.com/horror-reviews/cult-corner-the-dunwich-horror-1970/ |title=Cult Corner: The Dunwich Horror (1970) |last=Green |first=Zak |date=May 25, 2015 |website=Wicked Horror |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905091822/http://wickedhorror.com/horror-reviews/cult-corner-the-dunwich-horror-1970/ |archive-date=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n*''[[Re-Animator]]'' (1985), directed by [[Stuart Gordon]], and starring [[Jeffrey Combs]], [[Bruce Abbott]], [[Barbara Crampton]], and [[David Gale (actor)|David Gale]]. An adaptation of \"[[Herbert West\u2013Reanimator]]\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Maslin |first=Janet |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/10/18/movies/screen-stuart-gordon-directs-re-animator.html |title=Screen: Stuart Gordon Directs ''Re-Animator'' |date=October 18, 1985 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191210044231/https://www.nytimes.com/1985/10/18/movies/screen-stuart-gordon-directs-re-animator.html |archive-date=December 10, 2019 |website=New York Times}}</ref>\n*''[[From Beyond (film)|From Beyond]]'' (1986), directed by Stuart Gordon, and starring Jeffrey Combs, Barbara Crampton, and [[Ken Foree]]. Based on [[From Beyond (short story)|the short story of the same name]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/30-years-later-beyond-lovecraft-his-kinkiest |title=30 Years Later, ''From Beyond'' Is Lovecraft at His Kinkiest |last=Kaye |first=Don |date=October 28, 2016 |website=SyFy |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180530195325/http://www.syfy.com/syfywire/30-years-later-beyond-lovecraft-his-kinkiest |archive-date=May 30, 2018}}</ref>\n*''[[The Curse (1987 film)|The Curse]]'' (1987), directed by [[David Keith]], and starring [[Wil Wheaton]].  Based on \"[[The Colour Out of Space]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://crypticrock.com/this-week-in-horror-movie-history-the-curse-1987/ |title=This Week in Horror Movie History \u2013 The Curse (1987) |last=Allen |first=Tracy |date=September 12, 2014 |website=Cryptic Rock |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150321001004/http://crypticrock.com/this-week-in-horror-movie-history-the-curse-1987/ |archive-date=March 21, 2015}}</ref>\n*''[[The Unnamable (film)|The Unnamable]]'' (1988), directed by [[Jean-Paul Ouellette]] and starring [[Mark Kinsey Stephenson]].  Based on [[The Unnamable (short story)|the short story of the same name]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.adventuresinpoortaste.com/2018/11/12/the-unnamable-movie-review-great-special-effects-help-lovecraft-adaptation-exceed-expectations/ |title=The Unnamable (Movie) Review: Great Special Effects Help Lovecraft Adaptation Exceed Expectations |last=Muir |first=Nathaniel |date=November 12, 2018 |website=Adventures In Poor Taste |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710150923/http://www.adventuresinpoortaste.com/2018/11/12/the-unnamable-movie-review-great-special-effects-help-lovecraft-adaptation-exceed-expectations/ |archive-date=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[The Resurrected]]'' (1991), directed by [[Dan O'Bannon]] and starring [[John Terry (actor)|John Terry]], [[Jane Sibbett]], and [[Chris Sarandon]].  Based on ''[[The Case of Charles Dexter Ward]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/reviews/3356891/blu-ray-review-resurrected/ |title=Blu-ray Review: ''The Resurrected'' |last=Coffel |first=Chris |date=August 13, 2015 |website=Bloody Disgusting |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620233046/http://bloody-disgusting.com/reviews/3356891/blu-ray-review-resurrected/ |archive-date=June 20, 2018}}</ref>\n*''[[The Unnamable II: The Statement of Randolph Carter]]'' (1992), directed by Jean-Paul Ouellette and starring Mark Kinsey Stephenson. The film combines story elements from \"[[The Unnamable (short story)|The Unnameable]]\" and \"[[The Statement of Randolph Carter]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://gonewiththetwins.com/new/unnamable-ii-the-statement-of-randolph-carter-1993/ |title=''The Unnamable II: The Statement of Randolph Carter'' |last=Massie |first=Mike |website=Gone with the Twins |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709135012/http://gonewiththetwins.com/new/unnamable-ii-the-statement-of-randolph-carter-1993/ |archive-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[Necronomicon (film)|Necronomicon]]'' (1993), an anthology of three stories based on \"[[The Rats in the Walls]]\", \"[[Cool Air]]\", and ''[[The Whisperer in Darkness]]'', with a wraparound story featuring a fictionalized H. P. Lovecraft.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://doctorzombie.blogspot.com/2006/07/movie-review-necronomicon-1996.html |title=Movie Review: Necronomicon |last=Dr. Zombie |date=July 24, 2006 |website=Dr. Zombie's Midnight Theater of Terror |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620090946/http://doctorzombie.blogspot.com/2006/07/movie-review-necronomicon-1996.html |archive-date=June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[Castle Freak]]'' (1995), directed by Stuart Gordon and starring Jeffrey Combs and Barbara Crampton. Inspired by  \"[[The Outsider (short story)|The Outsider]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3554066/hideous-hungry-loose-brief-history-castle-freak/ |title=Hideous, Hungry and Loose: A Brief History of ''Castle Freak'' |last=Brehmer |first=Nat |date=April 5, 2019 |website=Bloody Disgusting |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408173208/https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3554066/hideous-hungry-loose-brief-history-castle-freak/ |archive-date=April 8, 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[Dagon (film)|Dagon]]'' (2001), directed by Stuart Gordon and starring Ezra Godden, [[Francisco Rabal]], and Raquel Mero\u00f1o. Based on ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nerdist.com/article/lovecraft-films-dagon-re-animator-blu-ray/ |title=Fish People and Mad Scientists: Lovecraft on Film |last=Anderson |first=Kyle |date=July 24, 2018 |website=Nerdist |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806160246/https://nerdist.com/article/lovecraft-films-dagon-re-animator-blu-ray/ |archive-date=August 6, 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[The Call of Cthulhu (film)|The Call of Cthulhu]]'' (2005), a silent black-and-white featurette designed to look like it was released in the late 1920s, when the short story \"[[The Call of Cthulhu]]\" was published.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-call-of-cthulhu-v347041/review |title=The Call of Cthulhu |last=Eder |first=Bruce |website=AllMovie |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523003444/http://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-call-of-cthulhu-v347041/review |archive-date=May 23, 2013}}</ref>\n*''[[Cthulhu (2007 film)|Cthulhu]]'' (2007), directed by Daniel Gildark, and starring Jason Cottle, [[Cara Buono]], and [[Tori Spelling]].  Based on ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://martianmigrainepress.com/CTHULHU-Is-The-Best-Lovecraftian-Film-You-Didnt-Watch |title=Dan Gildark's ''Cthulhu'' Is the Best Lovecraftian Film You Didn't Watch... |last=Jones |first=Scott R. |date=July 5, 2014 |website=Martian Migraine Press |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160327195644/http://martianmigrainepress.com/CTHULHU-Is-The-Best-Lovecraftian-Film-You-Didnt-Watch |archive-date=March 27, 2016}}</ref>\n*''[[The Whisperer in Darkness (film)|The Whisperer in Darkness]]'' (2011), a black-and-white film designed to look like it was released in the 1930s.  Based on [[The Whisperer in Darkness|the short story of the same name]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://screenanarchy.com/2011/03/the-whisperer-in-darkness-review.html |title=''The Whisperer in Darkness'' Review |last=Ognjanovic |first=Dejan |date=March 26, 2011 |website=Screen Anarchy |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613062954/http://screenanarchy.com/2011/03/the-whisperer-in-darkness-review.html |archive-date=June 13, 2018}}</ref>\n*''[[Color Out of Space (film)|Color Out of Space]]'' (2020), directed by [[Richard Stanley (director)|Richard Stanley]] and starring [[Nicolas Cage]]. Based on \"[[The Colour Out of Space]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/movies/story/2020-01-22/color-out-of-space-review-nicolas-cage |title=Review: An Over-the-Top Nicolas Cage Wigs Out in H.P. Lovecraft's ''Color Out of Space'' |last=Murray |first=Noel |date=January 22, 2020 |website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\n== Documentary biographies and movie portrayals ==\n''[[Lovecraft: Fear of the Unknown]]'' is a 2008 documentary about the life and works of H. P. Lovecraft.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://scottkenemore.com/2009/12/18/documentary-review-lovecraft-fear-of-the-unknown/ |title=Documentary Review: ''Lovecraft: Fear of the Unknown'' |last=Kenmore |first=Scott |date=December 18, 2009 |website=ScottKenmore.com |access-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[Howard Lovecraft and the Frozen Kingdom]]'' (2016), ''[[Howard Lovecraft and the Undersea Kingdom]]'' (2017), and ''[[Howard Lovecraft and the Kingdom of Madness]]'' (2018) are animated movies that are based on graphic novels inspired by the writings of Lovecraft.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/10/h-p-lovecraft-graphic-novel-movie-animated-arcana-shout-1201568108/ |title=Shout! Acquires All U.S. Rights To Arcana Studios' H.P. Lovecraft Animated Film |last=Busch |first=Anita |last2=Busch |first2=Anita |date=2015-10-07 |website=Deadline |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111104105/https://deadline.com/2015/10/h-p-lovecraft-graphic-novel-movie-animated-arcana-shout-1201568108/ |archive-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Speculative fiction/Horror}}\n* [[:Category:H. P. Lovecraft scholars]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=n|colwidth=40em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/publisher-news/article/43793-terror-eternal-the-enduring-popularity-of-h-p-lovecraft.html |title=Terror Eternal: The enduring popularity of H. P. Lovecraft |last=Dziemianowicz |first=Stefan |date=July 12, 2010 |website=[[Publishers Weekly]]}}\n* [http://books.guardian.co.uk/extracts/story/0,6761,1498708,00.html Extract from ''H P Lovecraft: Against the World, Against Life''] by [[Michel Houellebecq]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101230234944/http://www.heymiller.com/2010/08/h-p-lovecraft/ \"H. P. Lovecraft's Afterlife\"] by [[John J. Miller (journalist)|John J. Miller]] of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''\n* {{cite book\n| url = https://books.google.com/?id=cymGaRJmOvgC&pg=RA2-PA38&dq=h.p.+lovecraft,+will+cuppy#v=onepage&q=h.p.%20lovecraft%2C%20will%20cuppy| title = As If: Modern Enchantment and the Literary Prehistory of Virtual Reality\n| publisher = Oxford University Press\n| year = 2011\n| isbn = 978-0-19-988780-4\n| first = Michael\n| last = Saler\n}}\n* {{Cite web |url=https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2006/10/19/the-heroic-nerd/ |title=The Heroic Nerd |last=Sante |first=Luc |authorlink=Luc Sante |date=October 19, 2006 |website=[[The New York Review of Books]] |page=37 |volume=53 |issue=16 |place=New York}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=A Subtler Magick: The Writings and Philosophy of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=[[Wildside Press|Wildside Press LLC]] |year=1996 |isbn=978-1-880448-61-8 |edition=3rd |ref=magick |author-link=S. T. Joshi}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi, S. T. |title=An H. P. Lovecraft Encyclopedia |last2=Schultz, David E. |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |year=2001 |ref=hplencyclopedia}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=I Am Providence |publisher=[[Hippocampus Press]] |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-61498-053-7 |location=New York |ref=harv |author-link=S. T. Joshi}}\n* {{Cite book |last=de Camp |first=L. Sprague |title=H. P. Lovecraft: A Biography |publisher=Barnes & Noble Books |year=1975 |isbn=978-1-56619-994-0 |location=New York |ref=harv |author-link=L. Sprague de Camp}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Poole |first=W. Scott |title=In the Mountains of Madness |publisher=Soft Skull Press |year=2016 |isbn=978-1-59376-647-4 |location=Berkeley, California |ref=harv |author-link=W. Scott Poole}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Roland |first=Paul |title=The Curious Case of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=Plexus Publishing |year=2014 |isbn=978-0-85965-517-0 |location=London |ref=harv |author-link=PaulRoland}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Montague |first=Charlotte |title=H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=Chartwell Books |year=2015 |isbn=978-0-7858-3269-0 |location=New York |ref=harv |author-link=Charlotte Montague}}{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Anderson |first=James Arthur |title=Out of the Shadows: A Structuralist Approach to Understanding the Fiction of H. P. Lovecraft |date=2011 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-1-4794-0384-4 |location=Rockville, Maryland}} A close reading of Lovecraft's fiction.\n* {{Cite book |last=Burleson |first=Donald R. |title=Lovecraft: Disturbing the Universe |date=1990 |publisher=The University Press of Kentucky |isbn=0-8131-1728-3 |location=Lexington, Kentucky}} This book is the only volume to date analyzing Lovecraft's literature from a deconstructionist standpoint.\n* {{Cite book |last=Carter |first=Lin |title=Lovecraft: A Look Behind the Cthulhu Mythos |title-link=Lovecraft: A Look Behind the Cthulhu Mythos |date=1972 |publisher=[[Ballantine Books]] |isbn=0-586-04166-4}} This is a survey of Lovecraft's work (along with that of other members of the Lovecraft Circle) with considerable information on his life.\n* {{Cite book |last=de Camp |first=L. Sprague |title=Lovecraft: A Biography |title-link=Lovecraft: A Biography |date=July 12, 1976 |publisher=Doubleday |isbn=0-345-25115-6 |author-link=L. Sprague de Camp}} The first full-length biography, published in 1975, now [[out of print]]. It reflected the state of scholarship at the time but is now completely superseded by S.T. Joshi's biography ''I Am Providence''.\n* {{Cite book |last=Eddy |first=Muriel |title=The Gentleman From Angell Street: Memories of H. P. Lovecraft |last2=Eddy |first2=C. M., Jr. |date=June 2001 |publisher=Fenham Publishing, LLC. |isbn=978-0-9701699-1-4 |editor-last=Dyer |editor-first=Jim |location=Narragansett, Rhode Island |author-link2=C. M. Eddy Jr.}} A collection of personal remembrances and anecdotes from two of Lovecraft's closest friends in Providence. The Eddys were fellow writers, and Mr. Eddy was a frequent contributor to ''Weird Tales.''\n* {{Cite book |last=Hill |first=Gary |title=The Strange Sound of Cthulhu: Music Inspired by the Writings of H. P. Lovecraft |last2=Joshi |first2=S. T. |publisher=Music Street Journal |year=2006 |isbn=978-1-84728-776-2}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=I Am Providence: The Life and Times of H. P. Lovecraft |title-link=H. P. Lovecraft: A Life |date=2010 |publisher=Hippocampus Press |isbn=978-0-9824296-7-9 |location=New York City}} The most complete and authoritative biography of Lovecraft.\n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=The Rise and Fall of the Cthulhu Mythos |date=2008 |publisher=Mythos Books}} The first full-length critical study since Lin Carter's to examine the development of Lovecraft's Mythos and its outworking in the oeuvres of various modern writers.\n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=Emperors of Dreams: Some Notes on Weird Poetry |date=2008 |publisher=P'rea Press |isbn=978-0-9804625-4-8 |location=Sydney |chapter=H. P. Lovecraft: Alone in Space}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Long |first=Frank Belknap |title=Howard Phillips Lovecraft: Dreamer on the Nightside |title-link=Howard Phillips Lovecraft: Dreamer on the Nightside |date=1975 |publisher=Arkham House |isbn=0-87054-068-8 |author-link=Frank Belknap Long}} Presents a personal look at Lovecraft's life, combining reminiscence, biography and literary criticism. Long was a friend and correspondent of Lovecraft, as well as a fellow fantasist who wrote a number of Lovecraft-influenced Cthulhu Mythos stories (including ''The Hounds of Tindalos'').\n* {{Cite book |last=Houellebecq |first=Michel |title=H. P. Lovecraft: Against the World, Against Life |title-link=H. P. Lovecraft: Against the World, Against Life |date=2005 |publisher=Believer Books |isbn=1-932416-18-8 |translator-last=Khazeni |translator-first=Dorna |author-link=Michel Houellebecq}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Ludue\u00f1a |first=Fabi\u00e1n |title=H.P. Lovecraft. The Disjunction in Being |last2=de Acosta |first2=Alejandro |date=2015 |publisher=Schism |isbn=978-1-5058-6600-1 |location=New York City |translator-last=de Acosta |translator-first=Alejandro}} A study of Lovecraft's conceptions about philosophy and literature.\n* {{Cite book |title=An H.P. Lovecraft Encyclopedia |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-313-31578-7 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=New York City |page=117 |editor-last2=Schultz |editor-first2=David E.}} \n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=Lovecraft's Library: A Catalogue |publisher=Hippocampus Press |year=2017 |isbn=978-1-61498-217-3 |edition=Revised Fourth |location=New York City}} A meticulous listing of many of the books in Lovecraft's now scattered library. \n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=Lovecraft at Last |last2=Conover |first2=Willis |last3=Joshi |first3=S. T. |publisher=Cooper Square Press |edition=Revised |author-link=Willis Conover}} An account by Willis Conover of his teenage correspondence with Lovecraft. \n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=A Subtler Magick: The Writings and Philosophy of H. P. Lovecraft |date=1996 |publisher=Wildside Press |isbn=1-880448-61-0 |edition=Third |location=Gillette, New Jersey}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=The Call of Cthulhu and Other Weird Stories |date=1999 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=0-14-118234-2 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=New York City}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |url=https://archive.org/details/thingondoorstep00love |title=The Thing on the Doorstep and Other Weird Stories |date=2001 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=0-14-218003-3 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=New York City}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=The Dreams in the Witch House and Other Weird Stories |title-link=The Dreams in the Witch House and Other Weird Stories |date=2004 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=0-14-243795-6 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=New York City}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=The Horror in the Museum and Other Revisions |title-link=The Horror in the Museum and Other Revisions |last2=Derleth |first2=August |date=1989 |publisher=Arkham House |isbn=0-87054-040-8 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=Sauk City, Wisconsin |author-link2=August Derleth}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=The Annotated Supernatural Horror in Literature |date=2012 |publisher=Hippocampus Press |isbn=978-1-61498-028-5 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |edition=Second |location=New York City}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=The Annotated H. P. Lovecraft |date=1997 |publisher=Dell |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=New York City}} \n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=More Annotated H. P. Lovecraft |date=1999 |publisher=Dell |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=New York City |editor-last2=Cannon |editor-first2=Peter}}\n* {{Cite book |title=An Epicure in the Terrible |date=1991 |publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson University Press |isbn=0-8386-3415-X |editor-last=Schultz |editor-first=David E. |location=Rutherford, New Jersey |editor-last2=Joshi |editor-first2=S. T.}} An anthology of 13 essays on Lovecraft (excluding Joshi's lengthy introduction) on the centennial of Lovecraft's birth. The essays are arranged into 3 sections; Biographical, Thematic Studies and Comparative and Genre Studies. The authors include S. T. Joshi, Kenneth W. Faig, Jr., Jason C. Eckhardt, Will Murray, Donald R. Burleson, Peter Cannon, Stefan Dziemianowicz, Steven J. Mariconda, David E. Schultz, Robert H. Waugh, Robert M. Price, R. Boerem, Norman R. Gatford and Barton Levi St. Armand.\n* {{Cite book |title=The Intersection of Fantasy and Native America: From H. P. Lovecraft to Leslie Marmon Silko |date=2009 |publisher=Mythopoeic Press |isbn=978-1-887726-12-2 |editor-last=Sturgis |editor-first=Amy H. |author-link=[[Amy H. Sturgis]] |editor-last2=Oberhelman |editor-first2=David D.}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Locke |first=John |title=The Thing's Incredible: The Secret Origins of Weird Tales |date=2018 |publisher=Off-Trail Publications |isbn=978-1-935031-25-3}} A history of the first two years of ''[[Weird Tales]]'' (1923\u201324), the book contains extensive information on Lovecraft's introduction to and growing association with the magazine under the Henneberger/Baird regime. Issues covered include the acceptance of his early submissions, his role in the 1924 reorganization, and his recruitment as editor.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |q=H. P. Lovecraft |s=Howard Phillips Lovecraft |commons=H. P. Lovecraft |n=no |v=no |species=no |author=yes |d=Q169566}}\n{{Library resources box |by=yes |onlinebooks=yes |others= |about=yes |label=H. P. Lovecraft|viaf=66470391 }}\n* [http://www.hplhs.org/ The H. P. Lovecraft Historical Society]\n* {{isfdb name}}\n* {{IMDb name|0522454}}\n* {{Discogs artist|H.P. Lovecraft}}\n\n===Library collections===\n* [https://library.brown.edu/collatoz/info.php?id=73 Howard P. Lovecraft Collection] in the Special Collections at the [[John Hay Library]] ([[Brown University]])\n* [https://digital.library.villanova.edu/Item/vudl:591771 H. P. Lovecraft Collection] in the Distinctive Collections of [https://library.villanova.edu/ Falvey Memorial Library] ([https://www1.villanova.edu/university.html Villanova University])\n* {{LCAuth|n80017007|H. P. Lovecraft|113}}\n\n===Online editions===\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=34724|name=Howard Phillips Lovecraft}}\n* {{FadedPage|id=Lovecraft, Howard Phillips|name=H. P. Lovecraft|author=yes}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Howard Phillips Lovecraft}}\n* [https://www.discogs.com/artist/439356-HP-Lovecraft?limit=50&page=1/ H. P. Lovecraft Discography at Discogs.com]\n* {{Librivox author |id=424}}\n\n{{H. P. Lovecraft |expanded}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Associated subjects\n|list1=\n{{Cthulhu Mythos}}\n{{The Shadow Over Innsmouth}}\n{{The Call of Cthulhu}}\n{{At the Mountains of Madness}}\n{{Media based on H. P. Lovecraft works}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lovecraft, H. P.}}\n[[Category:H. P. Lovecraft| ]]\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:American agnostics]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:American fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:American horror writers]]\n[[Category:American literary critics]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American speculative fiction critics]]\n[[Category:American social commentators]]\n\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Deaths from colorectal cancer]]\n[[Category:Materialists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Providence, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Pulp fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Re-Animator (film series)]]\n[[Category:Science fiction critics]]\n[[Category:Cthulhu Mythos writers]]\n[[Category:Weird fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Burials at Swan Point Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Deaths from small intestine cancer]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:People from Red Hook, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:People from Flatbush, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn Heights]]\n[[Category:Writers of Gothic fiction]]\n[[Category:Critics of religions]]\n[[Category:Science Fiction Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island socialists]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the author|the rock group|H. P. Lovecraft (band)}}\n{{short description|American author}}\n{{Citation style|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = H. P. Lovecraft\n| image = H. P. Lovecraft, June 1934.jpg\n| caption = Lovecraft in 1934\n| pseudonym = {{Ubl|Lewis Theobald|Humphrey Littlewit|Ward Phillips|Edward Softly|Percy Simple}}\n| birth_name = Howard Phillips Lovecraft\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1890|8|20|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Providence, Rhode Island]], U.S.\n| nationality = American\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1937|3|15|1890|8|20|mf=yes}}\n| death_place = Providence, Rhode Island, U.S.\n| resting_place = [[Swan Point Cemetery]], Providence, Rhode Island, U.S.\n| resting_place_coordinates = {{Coord|41.854021|N|71.381068|W|type:landmark|display=inline}}\n| occupation = Short story writer, editor, novelist, poet\n| period = 1917\u20131937\n| genre = [[Weird fiction]], [[horror fiction]], [[science fiction]], [[gothic fiction]], [[fantasy fiction]], [[cosmic horror]]\n| movement = [[Cosmicism]]\n| notableworks = {{ubl|\"[[The Call of Cthulhu]]\"|''[[The Dream-Quest of Unknown Kadath]]''|''[[At the Mountains of Madness]]''|''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]''|''[[The Shadow Out of Time]]''}}\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Sonia Greene]]|March 3, 1924}}\n| signature = Lovecraft signature.svg\n}}\n'''Howard Phillips Lovecraft''' ({{IPAc-en|US|\u02c8|l|\u028c|v|k|r|\u00e6|f|t}}; August 20, 1890 \u2013 March 15, 1937) was an American writer of [[weird fiction]] and [[horror fiction]], who is known for his creation of what became the [[Cthulhu Mythos]].{{refn|Lovecraft did not coin the term \"Cthulhu Mythos.\" Instead, this term was probably coined by August Derleth.<ref name=\"Schweitzer\">{{Cite book |last=Tierney |first=Richard L. |title=Discovering H. P. Lovecraft |date=March 12, 2012 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-1-4344-4912-2 |editor-last=Schweitzer |editor-first=Darrell |page=52 |language=en |chapter=The Derleth Mythos |author-link=Richard L. Tierney |orig-year=first published 1972 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dX30AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA52&dq=Derleth+probably+coined+the+term+%22Cthulhu+Mythos.%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjUrunz94bnAhUSVd8KHfHRDbkQ6AEwAHoECAEQAg#v=onepage&q=Derleth%20probably%20coined%20the%20term%20%22Cthulhu%20Mythos.%22&f=false}}</ref>|group= n}} \n\nBorn in [[Providence, Rhode Island]], Lovecraft spent most of his life within [[New England]]. He was born into affluence, which ended with the death of his grandfather. In 1913, he wrote a critical letter to a [[pulp magazine]] that ultimately led to his involvement in pulp fiction. During the [[interwar period]], he wrote and published stories that focused on his interpretation of humanity's place in the universe. In his view, humanity was an unimportant part of an uncaring cosmos that could be swept away at any moment. These stories also included [[fantastic]] elements that represented the perceived fragility of [[anthropocentrism]].\n\nLovecraft was at the center of a wider body of authors known as \"The Lovecraft Circle.\" This group wrote stories that frequently shared details between them. He was also a prolific writer of letters. He maintained a correspondence with several different authors and literary proteges. According to some estimates, he wrote approximately 100,000 letters over the course of his lifetime.{{refn|This is according to L. Sprague de Camp and S. T. Joshi's estimates.<ref name=\"...\">{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |url=https://books.google.com/?id=YdO2XRYNUuQC&printsec=frontcover&q=100,000 |title=A Subtler Magick: The Writings and Philosophy of H.P. Lovecraft |date=December 1, 1996 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-1-880448-61-8 |page=236 |language=en}}</ref>|group= n}} In these letters, he discussed his worldview and his daily life, and tutored younger authors, such as [[August Derleth]], [[Donald Wandrei]], and [[Robert Bloch]].\n\nThroughout his adult life, Lovecraft was never able to support himself from earnings as an author and editor. He was virtually unknown during his lifetime and was almost exclusively published in [[pulp magazine]]s before he died in poverty at the age of 46, but is now regarded as one of the most significant 20th-century authors of supernatural horror fiction.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Schweitzer |first=Darrell |url=https://books.google.com/?id=dX30AAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=The%20verdict%20is%20now%20in:%20Lovecraft%20is%20the%20most%20important%20writer%20of%20supernatural%20horror%20fiction%20in%20English%20since%20Poe.&f=false |title=Discovering H. P. Lovecraft |date=March 12, 2012 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-1-4344-4912-2 |page=1 |language=en |chapter=Introduction: Lovecraft Forever}}</ref> Among his most celebrated tales are \"[[The Call of Cthulhu]]\", \"[[The Rats in the Walls]]\", ''[[At the Mountains of Madness]]'', ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]'', and ''[[The Shadow Out of Time]]''. His writings are the basis of the Cthulhu Mythos, which has inspired a large body of [[pastiche]]s, games, music and other media drawing on Lovecraft's characters, setting and themes, constituting a wider subgenre known as [[Lovecraftian horror]].\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and family tragedies ===\n[[File:Howard Phillips Lovecraft - circa 1900.jpg|thumb|upright|Lovecraft c. nine years old]]Lovecraft was born in his family home on August 20, 1890, in [[Providence, Rhode Island]]. He was the only child of Winfield Scott Lovecraft and Sarah Susan [nee Phillips] Lovecraft.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=I Am Providence |publisher=Hippocampus Press |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-61498-053-7 |location=New York}}</ref>{{Rp|16}} Though his employment is hard to discern, Lovecraft's future wife, [[Sonia Greene]], stated that Winfield was employed by [[Gorham Manufacturing Company]] as a traveling salesman.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|13}} Susie's family was of substantial means at the time of their marriage, her father, Whipple Van Buren Phillips, being involved in many significant business ventures.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|8}}\n\n;Whipple Van Buren Phillips\n{{Anchor|Whipple Van Buren Phillips}}\nWhipple Van Buren Phillips<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://hplovecraft.com/life/family.asp |title=H.P. Lovecraft's Family |last=Loucks |first=Donovan K. |date=2007 |website=The H. P. Lovecraft Archive |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103200249/http://www.hplovecraft.com/life/family.asp |archive-date=January 3, 2012}}</ref> was an American businessman from [[Providence, Rhode Island]] who also had mining interests in [[Idaho]]. He encouraged the young Lovecraft to have an appreciation of literature, especially [[classical literature]] and [[English poetry]].  In his old age he helped raise the young H. P. Lovecraft and educated him not only in the classics, but also in original [[weird tale]]s of \"winged horrors\" and \"deep, low, moaning sounds\" which he created for his grandchild's entertainment.  The exact sources of Phillips' weird tales have not been identified.  Lovecraft himself guessed that they originated from classic [[Gothic fiction|Gothic novelists]] like [[Ann Radcliffe]], [[Matthew Lewis (writer)|Matthew Lewis]], and [[Charles Maturin]]. On March 27, 1904, he was seized by a \u201cparalytic shock,\u201d (likely a stroke). He died the following day, at his home at 454 Angell Street.<ref>{{Cite book |last=de Camp |first=L. Sprague |url=https://archive.org/details/lovecraftbiog00deca |title=Lovecraft : A Biography |publisher=Doubleday |year=1975 |isbn=0-385-00578-4 |edition=1st |location=Garden City, N.Y. |page=[https://archive.org/details/lovecraftbiog00deca/page/38 38] |url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n;Winfield Scott Lovecraft\nIn April 1893, after a psychotic episode in a Chicago hotel, Winfield was committed to [[Butler Hospital]] in Providence. Though it is not clear who reported Winfield's prior behavior to the hospital, medical records indicate that he had been \"doing and saying strange things at times\" for a year before his commitment.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|26}} Winfield spent five years in Butler before dying in 1898. His death certificate listed the cause of death as [[general paresis of the insane|general paresis]], a term synonymous with late-stage [[syphilis]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|22}} Throughout his life, Lovecraft maintained that his father fell into a paralytic state, due to insomnia and being overworked, and remained that way until his death. It is unknown whether Lovecraft was simply kept ignorant of his father's illness or whether his later remarks were intentionally misleading.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|26}}\n\n;Doting mother\nAfter his father's hospitalization, Lovecraft resided in the family home with his mother, his maternal aunts Lillian and Annie, and his maternal grandparents Whipple and Robie.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|28}} According to the accounts of family friends, Susie doted on the young Lovecraft to a fault, pampering him and never letting him out of her sight.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book |last=de Camp |first=L. Sprague |title=Lovecraft: A biography |publisher=Barnes & Noble |year=1996 |isbn=9781566199940 |location=New York, N.Y.}}</ref>{{Rp|2}} Lovecraft later recollected that after his father's illness his mother was \"permanently stricken with grief.\" Whipple became a father figure to Lovecraft in this time, Lovecraft noting that his grandfather became the \"centre of my entire universe.\" Whipple, who traveled often on business, maintained correspondence by letter with the young Lovecraft who, by the age of three, was already proficient at reading and writing. When home, Whipple would share weird tales of his own invention and show Lovecraft objects of art he had acquired in his European travels. Lovecraft also credits Whipple with being instrumental in overcoming his fear of the dark when Whipple forced Lovecraft, at five years old, to walk through several darkened rooms in the family home.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|28}} It was in this period that Lovecraft was introduced to some of his earliest literary influences such as ''[[The Rime of the Ancient Mariner]]'' illustrated by [[Dor\u00e9]], ''[[One Thousand and One Nights]]'', a gift from his mother, [[Thomas Bulfinch]]'s ''[[Age of Fable]]'' and [[Ovid]]'s ''[[Metamorphoses]]''.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|33, 36}}\n\nWhile there is no indication that Lovecraft was particularly close to his grandmother Robie, her death in 1896 had a profound effect. By his own account, it sent his family into \"a gloom from which it never fully recovered.\" His mother's and aunts' wearing of black mourning dresses \"terrified\" him, and it is at this time that Lovecraft, approximately five-and-a-half years old, started having nightmares that would inform his later writing. Specifically, he began to have recurring nightmares of beings he termed \"night-gaunts\"; their appearance he credited to the influence of Dor\u00e9's illustrations, which would \"whirl me through space at a sickening rate of speed, the while fretting & impelling me with their detestable tridents.\" Thirty years later, night gaunts would appear in Lovecraft's writing.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|34}}\n\nLovecraft's earliest known literary works began at age seven with poems restyling the ''[[Odyssey]]'' and other mythological stories.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|38}} Lovecraft has said that as a child he was enamored of the Roman pantheon of gods, accepting them as genuine expressions of divinity and foregoing his Christian upbringing. He recalled, at five years old, being told Santa Claus did not exist and retorting by asking why \"God is not equally a myth.\"<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|42}} At the age of eight, he took a keen interest in the sciences, particularly astronomy and chemistry. He also examined the anatomy books available to him in the family library, learning the specifics of human reproduction that had yet to be explained to him, and found that it \"virtually killed my interest in the subject.\"<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|60}} In 1902, according to Lovecraft's own correspondence, astronomy became a guiding influence on his world view. He began producing the periodical ''Rhode Island Journal of Astronomy'', of which 69 issues survive, using the [[hectograph]] printing method.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|84}} Lovecraft went in and out of elementary school repeatedly, oftentimes with home tutors making up for those lost school years, missing time due to health concerns that are not entirely clear. The written recollections of his peers described him as both withdrawn yet openly welcoming to anyone who shared his current fascination with astronomy, inviting anyone to look through the telescope he prized.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|90}}\n\nBy 1900, Whipple's various business concerns were suffering a downturn and slowly reducing his family's wealth. He was forced to let the family's hired servants go, leaving Lovecraft, Whipple, and Susie, being the only unmarried sister, alone in the family home.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|97}} In the spring of 1904, Whipple's largest business venture suffered a catastrophic failure. Within months, he died due to a stroke at age 70. After Whipple's death, Susie was unable to support the upkeep of the expansive family home on what remained of the Phillips' estate. Later that year, she was forced to move herself and her son to a small [[Duplex (building)|duplex]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|96}} Lovecraft has called this time one of the darkest of his life, remarking in a 1934 letter that he saw no point in living anymore.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|98}} In fall of the same year, he started high school. Much like his earlier school years, Lovecraft was at times removed from school for long periods for what he termed \"near breakdowns.\" He did say, though, that while having some conflicts with teachers, he enjoyed high school, becoming close with a small circle of friends and performed well academically, excelling in particular at chemistry and physics.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|99}} Aside from a pause in 1904, he also resumed publishing the ''Rhode Island Journal of Astronomy'' as well as starting the ''Scientific Gazette'', which dealt mostly with chemistry.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|102}} It was also during this period that Lovecraft produced the first of the types of fiction he would later be known for, namely \"[[The Beast in the Cave]]\" and \"The Alchemist\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|116}}\n\nIt was in 1908, prior to his high school graduation, when Lovecraft suffered another health crisis of some sort, though this instance was seemingly more severe than any prior. The exact circumstances and causes remain unknown. The only direct records are Lovecraft's own later correspondence wherein he described it variously as a \"nervous collapse\" and \"a sort of breakdown,\" in one letter blaming it on the stress of high school despite his enjoying it. In another letter concerning the events of 1908, he notes, \"I was and am prey to intense headaches, insomnia, and general nervous weakness which prevents my continuous application to any thing.\" Though Lovecraft maintained that he was to attend Brown University after high school, he never graduated and never attended school again. Whether Lovecraft suffered from a physical ailment, a mental one, or some combination thereof has never been determined. An account from a high school classmate described Lovecraft as exhibiting \"terrible tics\" and that at times \"he'd be sitting in his seat and he'd suddenly up and jump.\" Harry Brobst, a psychology professor, examined the account and claimed that [[Sydenham's chorea|chorea minor]] was the most likely cause of Lovecraft's childhood symptoms while noting that instances of chorea minor after adolescence are very rare.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|126}} Lovecraft himself acknowledged in letters that he suffered from bouts of chorea as a child.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|27}} Brobst further ventured that Lovecraft's 1908 breakdown was attributed to a \"hysteroid seizure,\" a term that today usually denotes [[atypical depression]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|127}} In another letter concerning the events of 1908, Lovecraft stated that he \"could hardly bear to see or speak to anyone, & liked to shut out the world by pulling down dark shades & using artificial light.\"<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|128}}\n\n===Earliest recognition ===\nNot much of Lovecraft and Susie's activities from late 1908 to 1913 are recorded.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|128}} Lovecraft mentions a steady continuation of their financial decline highlighted by a failed business venture of his uncle that cost Susie a large portion of their dwindling wealth. A friend of Susie, Clara Hess, recalled a visit during which Susie spoke continuously about Lovecraft being \"so hideous that he hid from everyone and did not like to walk upon the streets where people could gaze on him.\" Despite Hess' protest that this was not the case, Susie maintained this stance.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|66}} For his part, Lovecraft said he found his mother to be \"a positive marvel of consideration\".<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|64}} A next-door neighbor later pointed out that what others in the neighborhood often supposed were loud, nocturnal quarrels between mother and son, she recognized as being recitations of Shakespeare, an activity that seemed to delight mother and son.\n\nDuring this period, Lovecraft revived his earlier scientific periodicals.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|128}} He endeavored to commit himself to the study of [[organic chemistry]], Susie buying the expensive glass chemistry assemblage he wanted.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book |last=Poole |first=W. Scott |title=In the Mountains of Madness: The Life and Extraordinary Afterlife of H.P. Lovecraft |publisher=Counterpoint |year=2016 |isbn=9781593766474 |location=Berkeley, CA |oclc=941875530}}</ref>{{Rp|85}} Lovecraft found his studies were hobbled by the mathematics involved, which he found boring and would cause headaches that would incapacitate him for a day.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|129}} Lovecraft's first poem that was not self-published appeared in a local newspaper in 1912. Called ''Providence in 2000 A.D.,'' the poem envisioned a future where people of English heritage were displaced by immigrants.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|137}} Surviving unpublished poems from this period, most notoriously \"On the Creation of Niggers\", were also emblematic of the xenophobia and racism inherent in much of Lovecraft's later work.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|138}}\n\nIn 1911, Lovecraft's letters to editors began appearing in pulp and weird fiction magazines, most notably ''[[Argosy (magazine)|Argosy]]''.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|140}} A 1913 letter critical of [[Frederick J. Jackson|Fred Jackson]], a prominent writer for Argosy, started Lovecraft down a path that would greatly affect his life. Lovecraft described Jackson's stories as \"trivial, effeminate, and, in places, coarse.\" Continuing, Lovecraft said that Jackson's characters exhibit the \"delicate passions and emotions proper to negroes and anthropoid apes.\" This sparked a nearly year-long feud in the letters section of ''Argosy'' between Lovecraft, along with his occasional supporters, and the majority of readers critical of his view of Jackson. Lovecraft's biggest critic was John Russell, who often replied in verse, and to whom Lovecraft felt compelled to reply because he respected Russell's writing skills.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|145}} The most immediate effect of the feud was the recognition garnered from [[Edward F. Daas]], then head editor of the [[United Amateur Press Association]]<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|84}} (also known as the UAPA). Daas invited Russell and Lovecraft to the organization and both accepted, Lovecraft in April 1914.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|155}}\n\n===Rejuvenation and tragedy ===\n{{quote box\n| width = 25%\n| align = left\n| quote = With the advent of United I obtained a renewed will to live; a renewed sense of existence as other than a superfluous weight; and found a sphere in which I could feel that my efforts were not wholly futile. For the first time I could imagine that my clumsy gropings after art were a little more than faint cries lost in the unlistening void.\n| source = \u2014Lovecraft in 1921.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|159}}\n}}\n\nLovecraft immersed himself in the world of amateur journalism for most of the following decade.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|159}} During this period, he was an advocate for amateurism versus commercialism.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|164}} Lovecraft's definition of commercialism, though, was specific to writing for, what he considered, low-brow publications for pay. He contrasted this with his view of \"professional publication,\" which he termed as writing for journals and publishers he considered respectable. He thought of amateur journalism as training and practice for a professional career.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|165}} Lovecraft was appointed to chairman of the Department of Public Criticism of the UAPA in late 1914.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|168}} He used this position to advocate for his, what many considered peculiar, insistence on the superiority of English language usage that most writers already considered archaic. Emblematic of the Anglophile opinions he maintained throughout his life, he openly criticized other UAPA contributors for their \"Americanisms\" and \"slang.\" Often these criticisms were couched in xenophobic and racist arguments bemoaning the \"bastardization\" of the \"national language\" by immigrants.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|169}} In mid-1915, Lovecraft was elected to the position of first vice-president of the UAPA.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|180}} Two years later, he was elected president and appointed other board members that mostly shared his view on the supremacy of classical English over modern American English.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|182}} Another significant event of this time was the beginning of [[World War I]]. Lovecraft published multiple criticisms of the U.S. government's and the American public's reluctance to join the war to protect England, which he viewed as America's homeland.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|210}}\n\nIn 1916, Lovecraft published his early short story \"[[The Alchemist (short story)|The Alchemist]]\" in the main UAPA journal, a departure from his usual verse. Due in no small part to the encouragement of [[W. Paul Cook]], another UAPA member and future lifelong friend, Lovecraft began writing and publishing more fiction.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|273}} Soon to follow were \"[[The Tomb (short story)|The Tomb]]\" and \"[[Dagon (short story)|Dagon]]\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|239}} \"The Tomb\", by Lovecraft's own admission, follows closely the style and construction of the writings of one of his largest influences, [[Edgar Allan Poe]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|240}} \"Dagon\" though, is considered Lovecraft's first work that embraced the concepts and themes that his writing would later be known for.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|251}} In 1918, Lovecraft's term as president of the UAPA elapsed, and he took his former post as chairman of the Department of Public Criticism.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|284}} In 1919, Lovecraft published another short story, \"Beyond the Wall of Sleep\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|260}}\n\nIn 1917, as Lovecraft related to Kleiner, Lovecraft made an aborted attempt to enlist in the army. Though he passed the physical exam,<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|303}} he told Kleiner that his mother \"has threatened to go to any lengths, legal or otherwise, if I do not reveal all the ills which unfit me for the army\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|300}}\n\nIn the winter of 1918\u20131919, Susie, exhibiting symptoms of a \"nervous breakdown\" of some sort, went to live with her elder sister Lillian. It is unclear what Susie may have been suffering from. Neighbour and friend Clara Hess, interviewed in 1948, recalled instances of Susie describing \"weird and fantastic creatures that rushed out from behind buildings and from corners at dark.\"<ref>Clara L. Hess, letter to <em>The Providence Journal</em> newspaper, September 19, 1948, later reprinted as ''Addenda to H.P.L.'' (with some factual additions gleaned from August Derleth's 1948 interview with her) in the book <em>Something about Cats and other Pieces</em>, Arkham House, 1949. Page 249.</ref> In the same account, Hess describes a time when they crossed paths in downtown Providence and Susie \"was excited and apparently did not know where she was.\" Whatever the causes, in March 1919 they resulted in Susie being committed to Butler Hospital, like her husband before her.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|301}} Lovecraft's immediate reaction to Susie's commitment was visceral, writing to Kleiner that, \"existence seems of little value,\" and that he wished \"it might terminate\".<ref name=\":2\" />{{Rp|97}} Lovecraft visited Susie often, walking the large grounds with her, and sent her letters on a regular basis,<ref name=\":2\" />{{Rp|97}} but, speaking to Susie's doctors, a month after she entered Butler, Lovecraft came to the realization that she was never going to be released.\n\nLate 1919 saw Lovecraft become more outgoing. After a period of isolation, he began joining friends in trips to writer gatherings; the first being a talk in Boston presented by [[Lord Dunsany]], whom Lovecraft had recently discovered and idolized.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|306}} In early 1920, at an amateur writer convention, he met [[Frank Belknap Long]], who would end up being Lovecraft's most influential and closest confidant for the rest of his life.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|308}} This period also proved to be the most prolific of Lovecraft's short-story career.<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|142}} The influence of Dunsany is readily apparent in his 1919 output, later be to coined Lovecraft's Dream Cycle, with stories like \"The White Ship\", \"The Doom that Came to Sarnath\", and \"The Statement of Randolph Carter\". In early 1920 followed \"[[Celepha\u00efs]]\" and \"[[The Cats of Ulthar]]\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book |last=Roland |first=Paul |title=The Curious Case of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=Plexus Publishing |year=2014 |isbn=9780859655170 |location=London |oclc=861676789}}</ref>{{Rp|56}} It was later in 1920 that Lovecraft began publishing the earliest stories that fit into the [[Cthulhu Mythos]]. The Cthulhu Mythos, a term coined by [[August Derleth]], encompasses Lovecraft's stories that share a commonality in fictional locations and Lovecraft's invented pantheon of god-like beings known as the [[Great Old Ones]].<ref name=\":3\" />{{Rp|69}} The poem \"Nyarlathotep\" and the short story \"The Crawling Chaos\", in collaboration with Winifred Virginia Jackson, were written in late 1920.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|369}} Following in early 1921 came \"The Nameless City\", the first story that falls definitely within the Cthulhu Mythos. In it is found one of Lovecraft's most enduring bits of writing, a couplet recited by his creation [[Abdul Alhazred]], \"That is not dead which can eternal lie; And with strange aeons even death may die.\"<ref name=\":1\" />{{Rp|149}}\n\nOn May 24, 1921, Susie died in Butler Hospital, due to complications from a gall bladder surgery five days earlier. Lovecraft's initial reaction, expressed in a letter nine days after Susie's death, was that of an \"extreme nervous shock\" that crippled him physically and emotionally, again remarking that he found no reason he should continue living.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|390}} Despite Lovecraft's reaction, he continued to attend amateur journalist conventions. It was at one such convention in July that Lovecraft met [[Sonia Greene]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|400}}\n\n===Marriage and New York===\nLovecraft's aunts disapproved of this relationship with Sonia. Lovecraft and Greene married on March 3, 1924, and relocated to her [[Brooklyn, New York|Brooklyn]] apartment at 793 Flatbush Avenue;<ref name=\"Resident Horror Genius\">{{Cite web |url=http://southbrooklynpost.com/2011/10/hp-lovecraft/ |title=Resident Horror Genius |last=Fooy |first=Frederick |date=October 27, 2011 |website=southbrooklynpost.com |publisher=South Brooklyn Post |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802114048/http://southbrooklynpost.com/2011/10/hp-lovecraft/ |archive-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> she thought he needed to get out of Providence in order to flourish and was willing to support him financially.<ref name=\"decamp\">{{Cite book |last=de Camp |first=L Sprague |url=https://archive.org/details/lovecraftbiog00deca |title=Lovecraft: A Biography |publisher=Garden City, N.Y., Doubleday |year=1975 |url-access=registration}}</ref> Greene, who had been married before, later said Lovecraft had performed satisfactorily as a lover,<ref>{{Cite news |last=La Farge |first=Paul |url=https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/the-complicated-friendship-of-h-p-lovecraft-and-robert-barlow-one-of-his-biggest-fans |title=The Complicated Friendship of H. P. Lovecraft and Robert Barlow, One of His Biggest Fans |date=2017 |work=[[The New Yorker]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914074104/https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/the-complicated-friendship-of-h-p-lovecraft-and-robert-barlow-one-of-his-biggest-fans |archive-date=September 14, 2019}}</ref> though she had to take the initiative in all aspects of the relationship. She attributed Lovecraft's passive nature to a stultifying upbringing by his mother. Lovecraft's weight increased to {{convert|200|lb|kg|abbr=on}} on his wife's home cooking.<ref name=decamp />\n\nHe was enthralled by New York, and, in what was informally dubbed the Kalem Club, he acquired a group of encouraging intellectual and literary friends who urged him to submit stories to ''[[Weird Tales]]''; editor [[Edwin Baird]] accepted many otherworldly 'Dream Cycle' Lovecraft stories for the ailing publication, though they were heavily criticized by a section of the readership.<ref name=\"JoshiSchultz2001\">{{Cite book |title=An H.P. Lovecraft Encyclopedia |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-313-31578-7 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |page=294 |chapter=Weiss, Henry George |name-list-format=vanc |editor-last2=Schultz |editor-first2=David E. |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Myawoc_PbF4C&pg=PA294}}</ref><ref name=\"Tyson2010\">{{Cite book |last=Tyson |first=Donald |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S8ppxGzr8cYC&q=The+first+editor+of+the+magazine%2C+Baird%2C+liked+Lovecraft%27s+way+of+writing+and+was+receptive+to+almost+everything+Lovecraft+submitted.#v=snippet&q=The%20first%20editor%20of%20the%20magazine%2C%20Baird%2C%20liked%20Lovecraft's%20way%20of%20writing%20and%20was%20receptive%20to%20almost%20everything%20Lovecraft%20submitted.&f=false |title=The Dream World of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=Llewellyn Publications |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-7387-2829-2 |page=75\u201376}}</ref> Established informally some years before Lovecraft arrived in New York, the core Kalem Club members were boys' adventure novelist [[Henry Everett McNeil]], the lawyer and anarchist writer [[James Ferdinand Morton Jr.]], and the poet Reinhardt Kleiner.\n\nOn New Year's Day of 1925, Sonia moved to Cleveland for a job opportunity, and Lovecraft left Flatbush for a small first-floor apartment on 169 Clinton Street \"at the edge of [[Red Hook, Brooklyn|Red Hook]]\"\u2014a location which came to discomfort him greatly.<ref name=\"Resident Horror Genius\" /> Later that year, the Kalem Club's four regular attendees were joined by Lovecraft along with his prot\u00e9g\u00e9 [[Frank Belknap Long]], bookseller George Willard Kirk, and [[Samuel Loveman]]. Loveman was Jewish, but he and Lovecraft became close friends in spite of the latter's [[Nativism (politics)|nativist]] attitudes.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Tyson |first=Donald |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S8ppxGzr8cYC&q=It+was+through+his+activities+with+the+UAPA+in+1917+that+he+began+to+correspond+with+Samuel+Loveman%2C+an+amateur+poet+who+worked+as+a+bookseller+in+Cleveland+Ohio.#v=snippet&q=It%20was%20through%20his%20activities%20with%20the%20UAPA%20in%201917%20that%20he%20began%20to%20correspond%20with%20Samuel%20Loveman%2C%20an%20amateur%20poet%20who%20worked%20as%20a%20bookseller%20in%20Cleveland%20Ohio.&f=false |title=The Dream World of H. P. Lovecraft: His Life, His Demons, His Universe |publisher=Llewellyn Publications |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-7387-2829-2 |pages=64\u201365 |name-list-format=vanc}}</ref>\n\n===Financial difficulties===\nNot long after the marriage, Greene lost her business and her assets disappeared in a bank failure; she also became ill. Lovecraft made efforts to support his wife through regular jobs, but his lack of previous work experience meant he lacked proven marketable skills. After a few unsuccessful spells as a low-level clerk, his job-seeking became desultory. The publisher of ''Weird Tales'' attempted to put the loss-making magazine on a business footing and offered the job of editor to Lovecraft, who declined, citing his reluctance to relocate to Chicago; \"think of the tragedy of such a move for an aged antiquarian,\" the 34-year-old writer declared. Baird was replaced with [[Farnsworth Wright]], whose writing Lovecraft had criticized. Lovecraft's submissions were often rejected by Wright. (This may have been partially due to censorship guidelines imposed in the aftermath of a ''Weird Tales'' story that hinted at necrophilia, although after Lovecraft's death, Wright accepted many of the stories he had originally rejected.)<ref name=\"JoshiSchultz2001\" /><ref name=\"Tyson2010\" />\n\n===Brooklyn===\nGreene, moving where the work was, relocated to Cincinnati, and then to Cleveland; her employment required constant travel. Added to the daunting reality of failure in a city with a large immigrant population, Lovecraft's single-room apartment at 169 Clinton Street in [[Brooklyn Heights]], not far from the working-class waterfront neighborhood [[Red Hook, Brooklyn|Red Hook]], was burgled, leaving him with only the clothes he was wearing. In August 1925, he wrote \"[[The Horror at Red Hook]]\" and \"[[He (short story)|He]]\", in the latter of which the narrator says \"My coming to New York had been a mistake; for whereas I had looked for poignant wonder and inspiration [...]  I had found instead only a sense of horror and oppression which threatened to master, paralyze, and annihilate me.\" It was at around this time he wrote the outline for \"[[The Call of Cthulhu]]\", with its theme of the insignificance of all humanity. In the bibliographical study ''[[H. P. Lovecraft: Against the World, Against Life]]'', [[Michel Houellebecq]] suggested that the misfortunes fed Lovecraft's central motivation as a writer, which he said was racial resentment.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite book |last=Houellebecq |first=Michel |title=H. P. Lovecraft: Against the World, Against Life |title-link=H. P. Lovecraft: Against the World, Against Life |publisher=Believer Books |year=2005 |isbn=1-932416-18-8 |location=San Francisco |name-list-format=vanc}}</ref> With a weekly allowance Greene sent, Lovecraft moved to a working-class area of [[Brooklyn Heights]], where he subsisted in a tiny apartment. He had lost approximately {{convert|40|lb|kg}} of body weight by 1926, when he left for Providence.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /><ref name=\"Joshi2001\">{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tfrbBSFn_p8C&q=The+one+thing+Lovecraft+could+do+during+Sonia%27s+absence+is+control+his+eating+habits.#v=snippet&q=The%20one%20thing%20Lovecraft%20could%20do%20during%20Sonia's%20absence%20is%20control%20his%20eating%20habits.&f=false |title=A Dreamer and a Visionary: H. P. Lovecraft in His Time |publisher=Liverpool University Press |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-85323-946-8 |pages=214\u2013215}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Providence===\n[[File:The Samuel B. Mumford House.jpg|thumb|left|Lovecraft's final home, May 1933 until March 10, 1937]]\nBack in Providence, Lovecraft lived in a \"spacious brown [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] wooden house\" at 10 Barnes Street until 1933.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Rubinton |first=Noel |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/14/travel/hp-lovecraft-providence.html |title=How to Find the Spirit of H.P. Lovecraft in Providence |date=August 10, 2016 |work=[[The New York Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013213244/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/14/travel/hp-lovecraft-providence.html |archive-date=October 13, 2018}}</ref> The same address is given as the home of Dr. Willett in Lovecraft's ''[[The Case of Charles Dexter Ward]]''. The period beginning after his return to Providence\u2014the last decade of his life\u2014was Lovecraft's most prolific; in that time he produced short stories, as well as his longest works of fiction: ''[[The Dream-Quest of Unknown Kadath]]'', ''The Case of Charles Dexter Ward'', and ''[[At the Mountains of Madness]]''. He frequently revised work for other authors and did a large amount of [[ghost-writing]], including ''[[The Mound (novella)|The Mound]]'', ''Winged Death'', and ''The Diary of Alonzo Typer''. Client [[Harry Houdini]] was laudatory, and attempted to help Lovecraft by introducing him to the head of a newspaper syndicate. Plans for a further project were ended by Houdini's death.<ref>{{Cite book |title=An H.P. Lovecraft Encyclopedia |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-313-31578-7 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=New York |page=117 |name-list-format=vanc |editor-last2=Schultz |editor-first2=David E.}}</ref>\n\nAlthough he was able to combine his distinctive style (allusive and amorphous description by horrified though passive narrators) with the kind of stock content and action that the editor of ''Weird Tales'' wanted\u2014Wright paid handsomely to snap up \"[[The Dunwich Horror]]\" which proved very popular with readers\u2014Lovecraft increasingly produced work that brought him no remuneration. Affecting a calm indifference to the reception of his works, Lovecraft was in reality extremely sensitive to criticism and easily precipitated into withdrawal. He was known to give up trying to sell a story after it had been once rejected. Sometimes, as with ''The Shadow over Innsmouth'' (which included a rousing chase that supplied action) he wrote a story that might have been commercially viable but did not try to sell it. Lovecraft even ignored interested publishers. He failed to reply when one inquired about any novel Lovecraft might have ready: although he had completed such a work, ''The Case of Charles Dexter Ward'', it was never typed up.<ref name=\"Anderson2014\">{{Cite book |last=Anderson |first=James Arthur |title=Out of the Shadows: A Structuralist Approach to Understanding the Fiction of H. P. Lovecraft |date=September 30, 2014 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-1-4794-0384-4 |location=Rockville, Maryland |page=89 |chapter=Charles Dexter Ward |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9FCsBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA89}}</ref>\n\nA few years after Lovecraft had moved to Providence, he and his wife Sonia Greene, having lived separately for so long, agreed to an amicable divorce. Greene moved to California in 1933 and remarried in 1936, unaware that Lovecraft, despite his assurances to the contrary, had never officially signed the final decree.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=H. P. Lovecraft: A Life |date=2004 |publisher=Necronomicon Press |isbn=0-940884-88-7 |location=West Warwick, Rhode Island |page=455}}</ref>\n\n===Last years and death===\nLovecraft was never able to provide for even basic expenses by selling stories and doing paid literary work for others. He lived frugally, subsisting on an inheritance that was nearly depleted by the time he died. He sometimes went without food to be able to pay the cost of mailing letters.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{Cite book |last=Ronan |first=Margaret |title=The Shadow Over Innsmouth and Other Stories of Horror |date=1971 |publisher=Scholastic Book Services |chapter=Forward}}</ref> After leaving New York, he moved to an apartment at 10 Barnes Street near Brown University with his surviving aunt; a few years later, they moved to a slightly less expensive place at 65 Prospect Street. As a result of the [[Great Depression]], he shifted towards socialism. He supported [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], but he thought that the [[New Deal]] was not sufficiently leftist.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=A Dreamer and a Visionary: H.P. Lovecraft in His Time |date=2001 |publisher=Liverpool University Press |isbn=978-0-85323-936-9 |pages=346\u2013358 |chapter=Caring about the Civilization (1929\u201337) |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wk5ixOCy4eMC&q=In+the+summer+of+1936+Lovecraft+made+an+interesting+admission%3A#v=snippet&q=In%20the%20summer%20of%201936%20Lovecraft%20made%20an%20interesting%20admission%3A&f=false}}</ref>\n\n[[File:H.P. Lovecraft's grave.jpg|thumb|right|H. P. Lovecraft's gravestone]]\n\nIn late 1936, he witnessed the publication of ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]'' as a paperback book.{{refn|This is the only one of Lovecraft's stories that was published as a book during his lifetime.<ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\" />|group= n}} However, Lovecraft was displeased, as his book was riddled with errors. It sold slowly and only approximately 200 copies were bound. The remaining manuscripts were destroyed after the publisher went out of business. By this point, Lovecraft's literary career had reached its end. Shortly after having written his last original short story, \"[[The Haunter of the Dark]]\", he stated that the hostile reception of ''At the Mountains of Madness'' had done \"more than anything to end my effective fictional career.\"<ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\">{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=A Dreamer and a Visionary: H.P. Lovecraft in His Time |publisher=[[Liverpool University Press]] |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-85323-946-8 |pages=364\u2013388 |chapter=The End of One's Life (1935\u201337) |author-link=S. T. Joshi |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wk5ixOCy4eMC&q=The+End+of+One%27s+Life+%281935%E2%80%9337%29#v=snippet&q=The%20End%20of%20One's%20Life%20(1935%E2%80%9337)&f=false}}</ref>\n\nOn June 11, [[Robert E. Howard#Death|Robert E. Howard]] committed suicide after being told that his mother would not awaken from her coma. His mother died shortly thereafter. This deeply affected Lovecraft, who consoled Howard's father. Almost immediately, Lovecraft wrote a brief memoir titled \"In Memoriam: Robert Ervin Howard\".<ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\" /><ref>{{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=Collected Essays |date=2006 |publisher=Hippocampus Press |isbn=978-0976159230 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |edition=1st |volume=5 |location=New York |pages=216\u2013218 |chapter=In Memoriam: Robert Ervin Howard |oclc=54350507 |orig-year=first published September 1936}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Lovecraft's physical health was deteriorating. He was suffering from an affliction that he referred to as \"grippe\".{{refn|\"Grippe\" is an archaic term for [[influenza]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.lexico.com/en/definition/grippe |title=Grippe |website=Lexico Dictionaries |access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref>|group= n}}<ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\" /> After seeing a doctor, he was diagnosed with [[Small intestine cancer|terminal cancer of the small intestine]]. Due to his fear of doctors, Lovecraft was not examined until a mere month before his death. He remained hospitalized during that time. He lived in constant pain until his death on March 15, 1937, in Providence. In accordance with his lifelong scientific curiosity, he kept a diary of his illness until he was physically incapable of holding a pen.<ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32716288/the-boston-globe/ |title=Wrote of His Last Month Alive |date=March 15, 1937 |work=The Boston Globe |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228223254/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32716288/the-boston-globe/ |archive-date=February 28, 2020 |page=2 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nLovecraft was listed along with his parents on the Phillips family monument ({{coord|41.8540176|-71.3810921|format=dms|type:landmark}}). In 1977, fans erected a headstone in [[Swan Point Cemetery]] on which they inscribed his name, the dates of his birth and death, and the phrase \"I AM PROVIDENCE\"\u2014a line from one of his personal letters.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://swanpointcemetery.com/notable-people.php |title=Notable Persons Interred at Swan Point Cemetery |website=swanpointcemetery.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160122114735/http://swanpointcemetery.com/notable-people.php |archive-date=January 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Legacy===\nGroups of enthusiasts annually observe the anniversaries of Lovecraft's death at [[Ladd Observatory]] and of his birth at his grave site. In July 2013, the Providence City Council designated \"H. P. Lovecraft Memorial Square\" and installed a commemorative sign at the intersection of Angell and Prospect streets, near the author's former residences.<ref name=\"motif-we-are-providence\">{{Cite news |last=Bilow |first=Michael |url=http://motifri.com/we-are-providence-the-h-p-lovecraft-community/ |title=We are Providence: The H.P. Lovecraft Community |date=July 27, 2013 |work=Motif Magazine |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017080819/http://motifri.com/we-are-providence-the-h-p-lovecraft-community/ |archive-date=October 17, 2013 |location=[[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], Rhode Island}}</ref> In 2016, Lovecraft was inducted into the [[Museum of Pop Culture]]'s Science Fiction and Fantasy Hall of Fame.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://locusmag.com/2017/01/2016-sff-hall-of-fame-inductees/ |title=2016 SF&F Hall of Fame Inductees |last=<!--Not stated--> |date=January 17, 2017 |website=Locus Online |language=en-US |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222001003/https://locusmag.com/2017/01/2016-sff-hall-of-fame-inductees/ |archive-date=December 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====World Fantasy Award bust====\n{{Main|World Fantasy Award#H. P. Lovecraft bust}}\nThe first World Fantasy Awards were held in Providence in 1975. The theme was \"The Lovecraft Circle.\" Until 2015, winners were presented with an elognated bust of Lovecraft that was designed by [[cartoonist]] [[Gahan Wilson]]. The Bust was nicknamed the \"Howard.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/11/hp-lovecraft-world-fantasy-awards/415485/ |title='Political Correctness' Won't Ruin H.P. Lovecraft's Legacy |last=Cruz |first=Lenika |date=November 12, 2015 |website=[[The Atlantic]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117085814/http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/11/hp-lovecraft-world-fantasy-awards/415485/ |archive-date=November 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tor.com/2014/08/20/should-the-world-fantasy-award-be-changed/ |title=Should the World Fantasy Award be Changed? |last=Schnelbach |first=Leah |date=August 20, 2014 |website=Tor.com |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329144215/http://www.tor.com/2014/08/20/should-the-world-fantasy-award-be-changed/ |archive-date=March 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, writer [[Donald Wandrei]] caused some controversy after he was offered a [[World Fantasy Award]] for Life Achievement but refused to accept it because the award was a bust of H. P. Lovecraft that he felt looked more like a caricature of Lovecraft than an actual representation.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Sullivan |first=Jack |title=The Penguin Encyclopedia of Horror and the Supernatural |title-link=The Penguin Encyclopedia of Horror and the Supernatural |publisher=[[Viking Press]] |year=1986 |isbn=978-0-670-80902-8 |location=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/penguinencyclope00sull/page/448 448\u2013449] |author-link=Jack Sullivan (literary scholar)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite encyclopedia |title=Wandrei, Donald |encyclopedia=[[The Encyclopedia of Fantasy]] |last=Morrish |first=Bob |date=March 15, 1999 |editor-last=Grant |editor-first=John |pages=994\u20135 |isbn=978-0-312-19869-5 |editor1-link=John Grant (author) |editor2-link=John Clute |editor2-first=John |editor2-last=Clute}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, author [[Daniel Jos\u00e9 Older]] started a petition to change the World Fantasy Award statuette from a bust of Lovecraft to one of African-American author [[Octavia Butler]].<ref name=\"tg\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/sep/17/world-fantasy-awards-hp-lovecraft-racism-row-statuette |title=World Fantasy awards pressed to drop HP Lovecraft trophy in racism row |date=September 17, 2014 |work=The Guardian |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118165842/http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/sep/17/world-fantasy-awards-hp-lovecraft-racism-row-statuette |archive-date=January 18, 2015}}</ref> Kevin J. Maroney, editor of ''[[The New York Review of Science Fiction]]'', also supported the call for the WFA to be changed from Lovecraft's face, suggesting it be replaced with a symbol representing the fantasy genre. Maroney argued this should be done \"not out of disrespect for Lovecraft as a writer or as a central figure in fantasy, but as a courtesy to generations of writers whom the WFA hopes to honor.\"<ref>{{Cite journal |date=August 2014 |title=Editorial: Chance of Face, Change of Heart |url=http://www.nyrsf.com/2014/09/issue-312-august-2014-editorial-chance-of-face-change-of-heart.html |url-status=live |journal=The New York Review of Science Fiction |issue=312 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908023245/http://www.nyrsf.com/2014/09/issue-312-august-2014-editorial-chance-of-face-change-of-heart.html |archive-date=September 8, 2015}}</ref> In response to the campaign, the board of the World Fantasy Awards announced in September 2014 that it was \"in discussion\" about the future of the award statuette,<ref name=\"tg\" /> and in November 2015 it was announced that the World Fantasy Award trophy would no longer be modeled on H. P. Lovecraft.<ref name=\"TG2\">{{Cite news |last=Flood, Alison |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/09/world-fantasy-award-drops-hp-lovecraft-as-prize-image |title=World Fantasy award drops HP Lovecraft as prize image |date=November 9, 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118192211/http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/09/world-fantasy-award-drops-hp-lovecraft-as-prize-image |archive-date=November 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\n{{more citations needed section|date=May 2012}}\n\nSome of Lovecraft's work was inspired by his own nightmares.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=FRANCH |first=A. |last2=MACROBERT |year=2015 |title=Cosmic Dread: THE ASTRONOMY OF H. P. LOVECRAFT |magazine=Sky & Telescope |volume=129 |issue=2 |pages=34\u201339}}</ref> His interest started from his childhood days when his grandfather would tell him Gothic horror stories. \n\nLovecraft's most significant literary influence was Edgar Allan Poe.  Like Lovecraft, Poe's work was out of step with the prevailing literary trends of his era. Both authors created distinctive, singular worlds of fantasy and employed [[archaism]]s in their writings. This influence can be found in such works as his novella ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]''<ref name=\"The Shadow Over Innsmouth\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/fiction/soi.aspx |title=The Shadow Over Innsmouth |date=August 20, 2009 |publisher=Donovan K. Loucks |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807082000/http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/fiction/soi.aspx |archive-date=August 7, 2013}}</ref> where Lovecraft references Poe's story \"[[The Imp of the Perverse (short story)|The Imp of the Perverse]]\" by name in Chapter 3, and in his poem \"Nemesis\", where the \"...&nbsp;ghoul-guarded gateways of slumber\"<ref name=\"ghoul-guarded\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/poetry/p121.aspx |title=Nemesis |date=October 20, 2009 |publisher=Donovan K. Loucks |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130910194736/http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/poetry/p121.aspx |archive-date=September 10, 2013}}</ref> suggest the \"...&nbsp;ghoul-haunted woodland of Weir\"<ref name=\"ghoul-haunted\">{{Cite book |last=Poe |first=Edgar Allan |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ddJKAQAAMAAJ&q=ghoul-haunted+woodland+of+Weir+#v=snippet&q=ghoul-haunted%20woodland%20of%20Weir&f=false |title=The Works of the Late Edgar Allan Poe |date=1859 |publisher=Redfield |editor-last=Griswold |editor-first=Rufus Wilmot |editor-link=Rufus Wilmot Griswold |volume=II |location=New York City |language=en |chapter=Ulalume |author-link=Edgar Allan Poe}}</ref> found in Poe's \"[[Ulalume]]\". A direct quote from the poem and a reference to Poe's only novel ''[[The Narrative of Arthur Gordon Pym of Nantucket]]'' is alluded to in Lovecraft's ''[[Masterpiece|magnum opus]]'' ''[[At the Mountains of Madness]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/fiction/mm.aspx |title=''At the Mountains of Madness'' |date=August 20, 2009 |website=www.hplovecraft.com |publisher=Donovan K. Loucks |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225184117/http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/fiction/mm.aspx |archive-date=February 25, 2017}}</ref> Both authors shared many biographical similarities as well, such as the loss of their fathers at young ages and an early interest in poetry.\n\nHe was influenced by [[Arthur Machen]]'s<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/culture/2014/10/weird-realism-john-gray-moral-universe-h-p-lovecraft |title=Weird realism: John Gray on the moral universe of H P Lovecraft |website=www.newstatesman.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414140517/http://www.newstatesman.com/culture/2014/10/weird-realism-john-gray-moral-universe-h-p-lovecraft |archive-date=April 14, 2016}}</ref> carefully constructed tales concerning the survival of ancient evil into modern times in an otherwise realistic world and his beliefs in hidden mysteries which lay behind reality. Lovecraft was also influenced by authors such as Oswald Spengler and [[Robert W. Chambers]]. Chambers was the writer of ''[[The King in Yellow]]'', of whom Lovecraft wrote in a letter to [[Clark Ashton Smith]]: \"Chambers is like [[Rupert Hughes]] and a few other fallen Titans \u2013 equipped with the right brains and education but wholly out of the habit of using them.\" Lovecraft's discovery of the stories of [[Edward Plunkett, 18th Baron of Dunsany|Lord Dunsany]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Power |first=Ed |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/10/30/cthulhus-evil-overlord-the-monstrous-world-of-hp-lovecraft/ |title=Cthulhu's evil overlord: the monstrous world of HP Lovecraft |date=October 30, 2016 |work=The Telegraph |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223013216/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/10/30/cthulhus-evil-overlord-the-monstrous-world-of-hp-lovecraft/ |archive-date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> with their pantheon of mighty gods existing in dreamlike outer realms, moved his writing in a new direction, resulting in a series of imitative fantasies in a ''Dreamlands'' setting.\n\nLovecraft also cited [[Algernon Blackwood]] as an influence, quoting ''The Centaur'' in the head paragraph of \"[[The Call of Cthulhu]]\". He declared Blackwood's story ''[[The Willows (story)|The Willows]]'' to be the single best piece of weird fiction ever written.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/essays/shil.aspx |title=Supernatural Horror in Literature |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |date=October 20, 2009 |website=www.hplovecraft.com |publisher=Donovan K. Loucks |orig-year=written 1927 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200119175841/http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/essays/shil.aspx |archive-date=January 19, 2020 |quote=The well-nigh endless array of Mr. Blackwood's fiction includes both novels and shorter tales&nbsp;... Foremost of all must be reckoned 'The Willows'&nbsp;... Here art and restraint in narrative reach their very highest development, and an impression of lasting poignancy is produced without a single strained passage or a single false note.}}</ref>\n\nAnother inspiration came from a completely different source: scientific progress in biology, astronomy,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/84903/7-obsessions-influenced-h-p-lovecrafts-work |title=7 Obsessions That Influenced H. P. Lovecraft's Work |work=Mental Floss |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225053300/http://mentalfloss.com/article/84903/7-obsessions-influenced-h-p-lovecrafts-work |archive-date=February 25, 2017 |language=en}}</ref> geology, and physics.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Rottensteiner |first=Franz |author-link=Franz Rottensteiner |year=1992 |title=Lovecraft as Philosopher |journal=Science Fiction Studies |volume=19 |issue=1 |pages=117\u2013121 |jstor=4240129}}</ref> His study of science contributed to Lovecraft's view of the human race as insignificant, powerless, and doomed in a [[materialistic]] and [[mechanistic]] universe.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Woodard |first=Ben |date=2011 |title=Mad Speculation and Absolute Inhumanism: Lovecraft, Ligotti, and the Weirding of Philosophy |url=http://www.continentcontinent.cc/index.php/continent/article/view/14 |url-status=live |journal=Continent |volume=1 |issue=1 |page=6 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180209220929/http://continentcontinent.cc/index.php/continent/article/view/14 |archive-date=February 9, 2018}}</ref> Lovecraft was a keen amateur astronomer from his youth, often visiting the [[Ladd Observatory]] in Providence, and penning numerous astronomical articles for local newspapers. His astronomical telescope is now housed in the rooms of the [[August Derleth]] Society.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.augustderleth.org/about-the-ads/overview/accomplishments/ |title=Accomplishments |website=www.augustderleth.org |access-date=January 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLovecraft's materialist views led him to espouse his philosophical views through his fiction; these philosophical views came to be called [[cosmicism]]. Cosmicism took on a more pessimistic tone with his creation of what is now known as the Cthulhu Mythos; a fictional universe that contains alien deities and horrors. The term \"Cthulhu Mythos\" was likely coined by Lovecraft's correspondent and prot\u00e9g\u00e9, August Derleth, after Lovecraft's death.<ref name=\"Schweitzer\" /> In his letters, Lovecraft jokingly called his fictional mythology \"Yog-Sothothery.\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=Against Religion: The Atheist Writings of H.P. Lovecraft |date=2010 |publisher=Sporting Gentlemen |isbn=978-0-578-05248-9 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |language=en |chapter=Religion and Indeterminacy |orig-year=written November 22, 1930 |editor-last2=Hitchens |editor-first2=Christopher |editor-link2=Christopher Hitchens |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=hdplAgAAQBAJ&dq=Lovecraft+Yog-Sothothery+Atheist&q=Were+an+child+to+be+reared+in+isolation,+and+surrounded+from+infancy+with+the+religious+precepts+of+Tsathoggua,+YOG-SOTHOTH,+or+the+Doels,+his+inner+emotions+would+all+through+life+inform+him+positively+of+the+truth+of+Tsathogguanism,+Yog-Sothothery,+or+Doelolatry,+as+the+case+might+be,+I%C3%A4!+Shub-Niggurath!+The+Goat+With+a+Thousand+Young!#v=snippet&q=Were%20an%20child%20to%20be%20reared%20in%20isolation,%20and%20surrounded%20from%20infancy%20with%20the%20religious%20precepts%20of%20Tsathoggua,%20YOG-SOTHOTH,%20or%20the%20Doels,%20his%20inner%20emotions%20would%20all%20through%20life%20inform%20him%20positively%20of%20the%20truth%20of%20Tsathogguanism,%20Yog-Sothothery,%20or%20Doelolatry,%20as%20the%20case%20might%20be,%20I%C3%A4!%20Shub-Niggurath!%20The%20Goat%20With%20a%20Thousand%20Young!&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Klinger |first=Leslie S. |title=The New Annotated H. P. Lovecraft |date=October 13, 2014 |publisher=W. W. Norton & Company |isbn=978-1-63149-055-2 |page=xii |language=en}}</ref>\n\nLovecraft's use of [[British English]] owes much to his father's influence. He described his father as having been so [[anglophilic]] that he was commonly presumed to be an Englishman. According to Lovecraft, his father had been constantly warned to avoid using Americanized words and phrases. This influence stretched beyond Lovecraft's use of language. His father's anglophilia had also caused Lovecraft to have a deep affection for [[British culture]] and the [[British Empire]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tfrbBSFn_p8C&q=Perhaps+more+important+than+all+these+matters+is+the+image+and+tokens+of+his+father+which+Lovecraft+retained+in+maturity.#v=snippet&q=Perhaps%20more%20important%20than%20all%20these%20matters%20is%20the%20image%20and%20tokens%20of%20his%20father%20which%20Lovecraft%20retained%20in%20maturity.&f=false |title=A Dreamer and a Visionary: H.P. Lovecraft in His Time |date=2001 |publisher=Liverpool University Press |isbn=978-0-85323-946-8 |pages=15\u201316 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAmong the books found in his library (as evidenced in ''Lovecraft's Library'' by S. T. Joshi){{Full citation needed|date=January 2020}} was ''[[The Seven Who Were Hanged]]'' by [[Leonid Andreyev]] and ''[[A Strange Manuscript Found in a Copper Cylinder]]'' by [[James De Mille]].\n\nLovecraft's style has often been subject to criticism,<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\" /> yet scholars such as S. T. Joshi have shown that Lovecraft consciously utilized a variety of literary devices to form a unique style of his own \u2013 these include conscious [[archaism]], prose-poetic techniques combined with essay-form techniques, [[alliteration]], [[Anaphora (rhetoric)|anaphora]], [[crescendo]], [[transferred epithet]], [[metaphor]], [[Symbolism (arts)|symbolism]], and [[colloquialism]].{{Full citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n==Themes==\n{{Synthesis|section|date=February 2009}}\n\nSeveral themes recur in Lovecraft's stories:\n\n{{quote box|width=30em|align=right|Now all my tales are based on the fundamental premise that common human laws and interests and emotions have no validity or significance in the vast cosmos-at-large. To me there is nothing but puerility in a tale in which the human form\u2014and the local human passions and conditions and standards\u2014are depicted as native to other worlds or other universes. To achieve the essence of real externality, whether of time or space or dimension, one must forget that such things as organic life, good and evil, love and hate, and all such local attributes of a negligible and temporary race called mankind, have any existence at all. Only the human scenes and characters must have human qualities. ''These'' must be handled with unsparing ''realism'', (''not'' catch-penny ''romanticism'') but when we cross the line to the boundless and hideous unknown\u2014the shadow-haunted ''Outside''\u2014we must remember to leave our humanity and terrestrialism at the threshold.|salign=right|source=\u2014&nbsp;H. P. Lovecraft, in note to the editor of ''Weird Tales'', on resubmission of \"The Call of Cthulhu\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=Selected Letters 1925\u20131929 |publisher=Arkham House |year=1968 |location=Sauk City, Wisconsin |page=150 |chapter=Letter to Farnsworth Wright (July 27, 1927)}}</ref>}}\n\n===Forbidden knowledge===\nForbidden, dark, esoterically veiled knowledge is a central theme in many of Lovecraft's works.<ref name=\"Burlesonglass\">{{Cite book |last=Burleson |first=Donald R. |title=An Epicure in the Terrible: A Centennial Anthology of Essays in Honor of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=[[Fairleigh Dickinson University Press]] |year=1991 |isbn=978-0-8386-3415-8 |editor-last=Schultz |editor-first=David E. |pages=135\u2013147 |chapter=On Lovecraft's Themes: Touching the Glass |editor-last2=Joshi |editor-first2=S. T. |editor-link2=S. T. Joshi |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S3oH_VdH3BcC&pg=PA135}}</ref> Many of his characters are driven by curiosity or scientific endeavor, and in many of his stories the knowledge they uncover proves [[Prometheus|Promethean]] in nature, either filling the seeker with regret for what they have learned, destroying them psychologically, or completely destroying the person who holds the knowledge.<ref name=\"Burlesonglass\" /><ref>{{Cite book |last=Dziemianowicz |first=Stefan |title=An Epicure in the Terrible: A Centennial Anthology of Essays in Honor of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=[[Fairleigh Dickinson University Press]] |year=1991 |isbn=978-0-8386-3415-8 |editor-last=Schultz |editor-first=David E. |pages=159\u2013187 |chapter=Outsiders and Aliens: The Uses of Isolation in Lovecraft's Fiction |editor-last2=Joshi |editor-first2=S. T. |editor-link2=S. T. Joshi |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S3oH_VdH3BcC&pg=PA159}}</ref><ref name=\"Hamblycraft\">{{Cite book |last=Hambly |first=Barbara |title=The transition of H. P. Lovecraft: The Road to Madness |publisher=The Random House Publishing Group |year=1996 |isbn=978-0-345-38422-5 |page=viii |chapter=Introduction: The Man Who Loved His Craft}}</ref><ref name=\"burlsonuniverse\">{{Cite book |last=Burleson |first=Donald |title=Lovecraft: Disturbing the Universe |publisher=the University Press of Kentucky |year=1990 |isbn=978-0-8131-1728-7}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Leiber |first=Fritz |title=Discovering H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=Borgo Press |year=2001 |isbn=978-1-58715-471-3 |editor-last=Schweitzer |editor-first=Darrell |page=14 |chapter=A Literary Copernicus |author-link=Fritz Leiber |orig-year=first published 1949 |chapter-url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Discovering_H_P_Lovecraft/-PDksCTdmYMC?hl=en&gbpv=1&bsq=These%20individuals%20are%20in%20all%20other%20ways%20very%20realistically-minded%20indeed,%20but%20having%20glimpsed%20the%20forbidden%20knowledge,%20they%20are%20generally%20more%20susceptible%20to%20cosmic%20terror%20than%20ordinary%20people}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Price |first=Robert M. |title=Introduction:The New Lovecraft Circle |publisher=Random House Publishing |year=1991 |isbn=978-0-345-44406-6}}</ref>\n\nSome critics argue that this theme is a reflection of Lovecraft's contempt of the world around him, causing him to search inwardly for knowledge and inspiration.<ref name=\"Armandborges\">{{Cite book |last=St. Armand |first=Barton Levi |title=An Epicure in the Terrible: A Centennial Anthology of Essays in Honor of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=[[Fairleigh Dickinson University Press]] |year=1991 |isbn=978-0-8386-3415-8 |editor-last=Schultz |editor-first=David E. |pages=319\u2013320 |chapter=Synchronistic Worlds: Lovecraft and Borges |editor-last2=Joshi |editor-first2=S. T. |editor-link2=S. T. Joshi |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S3oH_VdH3BcC&pg=PA319}}</ref>\n\n===Non-human influences on humanity===\nThe beings of Lovecraft's [[mythos]] often have human servants; [[Cthulhu]], for instance, is worshipped under various names by [[cult]]s{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} among both the [[Greenlandic Inuit]] and [[Louisiana Voodoo|voodoo circles of Louisiana]], and in many other parts of the world.\n\nThese worshippers served a useful narrative purpose for Lovecraft. Many beings of the Mythos were too powerful to be defeated by human opponents, and so horrific that direct knowledge of them meant insanity for the victim. When dealing with such beings, Lovecraft needed a way to provide [[Dramatic structure#Exposition|exposition]] and build tension without bringing the story to a premature end. Human followers gave him a way to reveal information about their \"gods\" in a diluted form, and also made it possible for his protagonists to win paltry victories. Lovecraft, like his contemporaries, envisioned \"savages\" as closer to supernatural knowledge unknown to civilized man.\n\n===Inherited guilt===\nAnother recurring theme in Lovecraft's stories is the idea that descendants in a bloodline can never escape the stain of crimes committed by their forebears, at least if the crimes are atrocious enough. Descendants may be very far removed, both in place and in time (and, indeed, in [[culpability]]), from the act itself, and yet, they may be haunted by the revenant past, e.g. \"[[The Rats in the Walls]]\", \"[[The Lurking Fear]]\", \"[[Facts Concerning the Late Arthur Jermyn and His Family]]\", \"[[The Alchemist (short story)|The Alchemist]]\", ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]'', \"[[The Doom that Came to Sarnath]]\" and ''The Case of Charles Dexter Ward''.\n\n===Fate===\nOften in Lovecraft's works, the protagonist is not in control of his own actions or finds it impossible to change course. Many of his characters would be free from danger if they simply managed to run away; however, this possibility either never arises or is somehow curtailed by some outside force, such as in \"[[The Colour Out of Space]]\" and \"[[The Dreams in the Witch House]]\". Often his characters are subject to a compulsive influence from powerful malevolent or indifferent beings. As with the inevitability of one's ancestry, eventually even running away, or death itself, provides no safety (''[[The Thing on the Doorstep]]'', \"[[The Outsider (short story)|The Outsider]]\", ''The Case of Charles Dexter Ward''). In some cases, this doom is manifest in the entirety of humanity, and no escape is possible (''[[The Shadow Out of Time]]'').\n\n===Civilization under threat===\nLovecraft was familiar with the work of the German conservative-revolutionary theorist [[Oswald Spengler]], whose pessimistic thesis of the decadence of the modern West formed a crucial element in Lovecraft's overall [[anti-modern]] worldview. Spenglerian imagery of cyclical decay is present in particular in ''At the Mountains of Madness''. S. T. Joshi, in ''H. P. Lovecraft: The Decline of the West'', places Spengler at the center of his discussion of Lovecraft's political and philosophical ideas.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |url=https://books.google.com/?id=KaklDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=I.%20Spengler%20and%20Lovecraft&f=false |title=H. P. Lovecraft: The Decline of the West |date=2016-05-28 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-1-4794-2754-3 |pages=314\u2013320 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nLovecraft wrote to Clark Ashton Smith in 1927: \"It is my belief, and was so long before Spengler put his seal of scholarly proof on it, that our mechanical and industrial age is one of frank [[decadence]].\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Mi\u00e9ville |first=China |title=At the Mountains of Madness |last2=Lovecraft |first2=H. P. |date=2005 |publisher=Modern Library Classics |isbn=9780812974416 |page=xxi |chapter=Introduction |author-link=China Mi\u00e9ville |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=qfWLDQAAQBAJ&pg=PR21&lpg=PR21&dq=It+is+my+belief,+and+was+so+long+before+Spengler+put+his+seal+of+scholarly+proof+on+it,+that+our+mechanical+and+industrial+age+is+one+of+frank+decadence.}}</ref> Lovecraft was also acquainted with the writings of another German philosopher of decadence: [[Friedrich Nietzsche]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Joshi|1996|p=38|ref=magick}}</ref>\n\nLovecraft frequently dealt with the idea of [[civilization]] struggling against dark, primitive barbarism. In some stories this struggle is at an individual level; many of his [[protagonist]]s are cultured, highly educated men who are gradually corrupted by some obscure and feared influence.\n\nIn such stories, the [[curse]] is often a hereditary one, either because of interbreeding with non-humans (e.g., ''[[Facts Concerning the Late Arthur Jermyn and His Family]]'' (1920), ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]'' (1931)) or through direct magical influence (''The Case of Charles Dexter Ward''). Physical and mental degradation often come together; this theme of 'tainted blood' may represent concerns relating to Lovecraft's own family history, particularly the death of his father due to what Lovecraft must have suspected to be a [[syphilis|syphilitic]] disorder.\n\nIn other tales, an entire society is threatened by barbarism. Sometimes the barbarism comes as an external threat, with a civilized race destroyed in war (e.g. \"[[Polaris (short story)|Polaris]]\"). Sometimes, an isolated pocket of humanity falls into decadence and [[atavism]] of its own accord (e.g. \"[[The Lurking Fear]]\"). But most often, such stories involve a civilized culture being gradually undermined by a malevolent underclass influenced by inhuman forces.\n\nIt is likely that the \"[[Roaring Twenties]]\" left Lovecraft disillusioned as he was still obscure and struggling with the basic necessities of daily life, combined with seeing non-Western European immigrants in New York City.\n\n===Race===\nRace is the most controversial aspect of Lovecraft's legacy, expressed in many disparaging remarks against the various non-Anglo-Saxon [[Race (classification of humans)|races]] and cultures in his work. As he grew older, his original Anglo-Saxon racial worldview softened into a classism or elitism which regarded the superior race to include all those self-ennobled through high culture. From the start, Lovecraft did not hold all [[white people]] in uniform high regard, but rather esteemed the English people and those of English descent.<ref name=\"joshimagic\">{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=A Subtler Magick: The Writings and Philosophy of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=Borgo Press |year=1996 |isbn=978-1-880448-61-8 |pages=22, 41\u201342, 76\u201377, 107\u2013108, 162, 229, 230}}</ref><ref name=\"Berndfantastic\">{{Cite book |last=Steiner |first=Bernd |title=H. P. Lovecraft and the Literature of the fantastic: explorations in a Literary Genre |publisher=GRIN Verlag |year=2005 |isbn=978-3-638-84462-8 |pages=54\u201355}}</ref><ref name=\"tysondream\" /><ref name=\"tysondream\" /> He praised non-[[White Anglo-Saxon Protestant|WASP]] groups such as Hispanics and Jews; however his private writings on groups such as Irish Catholics, German immigrants and African-Americans were consistently negative.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=H. P. Lovecraft, Four Decades of Criticism |publisher=Ohio University Press |year=1980 |isbn=978-0-8214-0577-2}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=January 2020}}<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=I Am Providence: The Life and Times of H. P. Lovecraft |title-link=H. P. Lovecraft: A Life |date=2010 |publisher=Hippocampus Press |isbn=978-0-9824296-7-9 |location=New York City}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=January 2020}} In an early poem, the 1912 \"[[s: On the Creation of Niggers|On the Creation of Niggers]]\", Lovecraft describes [[black people]] not as human but as \"beast[s] ... in semi-human figure, filled with vice.\" In his early published essays, private letters and personal utterances, he argued for a strong [[Color line (civil rights issue)|color line]] to preserve race and culture.<ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\" /><ref name=\"joshimagic\" /><ref name=\"Berndfantastic\" /><ref>{{Cite book |last=Punter |first=David |title=The Literature of Terror: A History of Gothic Fictions from 1765 to the Present Day |publisher=Routledge |year=1996 |isbn=978-0582237148 |volume=I |location=New York |page=40}}</ref> He made these arguments by direct disparagement of various races in his journalism and letters,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /><ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\" /><ref name=\"joshimagic\" /><ref name=\"Berndfantastic\" /><ref name=\"tysondream\" /> and perhaps allegorically in his fiction concerning non-human races.<ref name=\"Hamblycraft\" /><ref name=\"joshimagic\" /><ref>{{Cite book |last=Bloch |first=Robert |title=The Best of H. P. Lovecraft: Bloodcurdling Tales of Horror and the Macabre |publisher=The Random House Publishing Group |year=1982 |isbn=978-0-345-38422-5 |page=xii |chapter=Introduction: Heritage of Horror |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=fZRnpV521IcC&q=Some+critics+cite+this+as+a+disguised+example+of+the+racism+they+find+evident+in+%22He%2C%22+%22The+Horror+at+Red+Hook%2C%22+%22The+Call+of+Cthulhu%2C%22+and+other+stories.#v=snippet&q=Some%20critics%20cite%20this%20as%20a%20disguised%20example%20of%20the%20racism%20they%20find%20evident%20in%20%22He%2C%22%20%22The%20Horror%20at%20Red%20Hook%2C%22%20%22The%20Call%20of%20Cthulhu%2C%22%20and%20other%20stories.&f=false}}</ref><ref name=\"Mievillemountains\" /> Lovecraft showed sympathy to those who adopted Western culture, even to the extent of marrying a Jewish woman whom he viewed as \"well assimilated.\"<ref name=\"JoshiDreamer\" /><ref name=\"joshimagic\" /><ref name=\"Berndfantastic\" /><ref name=\"Mievillemountains\">{{Cite book |last=Mieville |first=China |title=At the Mountains of Madness |publisher=The Random House Publishing Group |year=2005 |isbn=978-0-8129-7441-6 |pages=xvii\u2013xx |chapter=Introduction |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/atmountainsofmad00love_0/page/}}</ref> Lovecraft's racial attitude was common in the society of his day, especially in the New England in which he grew up.<ref name=\"joshimagic\" /><ref name=\"Berndfantastic\" /><ref name=\"tysondream\">{{Cite book |last=Tyson |first=Donald |title=The Dream World of H. P. Lovecraft: His Life, His Demons, His Universe |publisher=Llewellyn Publications |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-7387-2284-9 |pages=5\u20136, 57\u201359}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Schweitzer |first=Darrell |title=Windows of the Imagination |publisher=Wildside Press |year=1998 |isbn=1-880448-60-2 <!-- Note: ISBN shown on book's copyright page is incorrect; the correct number appears on the back cover. --> |pages=94\u201395}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Schwader |first=Ann |title=Eldritch Blue: Love and Sex in the Cthulhu Mythos |publisher=Lindisfarne Press |year=2004 |isbn=978-0-9740297-5-7 |page=59 |chapter=Mail Order Bride}}</ref>\n\n===Risks of a scientific era===\nAt the turn of the 20th century, humanity's increased reliance upon science was both opening new worlds and solidifying understanding of ours. Lovecraft portrays this potential for a growing gap of man's understanding of the universe as a potential for horror, most notably in \"The Colour Out of Space\", where the inability of science to comprehend a contaminated meteorite leads to horror.\n\nIn a letter to [[James F. Morton]] in 1923, Lovecraft specifically pointed to [[Einstein]]'s [[Theory of relativity|theory on relativity]] as throwing the world into chaos and making the cosmos a jest; in a letter to Woodburn Harris in 1929, he speculated that technological comforts risk the collapse of science. Indeed, at a time when men viewed science as limitless and powerful, Lovecraft imagined alternative potential and fearful outcomes. In \"The Call of Cthulhu\", Lovecraft's characters encounter architecture which is \"abnormal, non-Euclidean, and loathsomely redolent of spheres and dimensions apart from ours.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/fiction/cc.aspx |title=The Call of Cthulhu |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |date=August 20, 2009 |website=www.hplovecraft.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722165927/http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/texts/fiction/cc.aspx |archive-date=July 22, 2016}}</ref> [[Non-Euclidean geometry]] is the mathematical language and background of Einstein's [[general theory of relativity]], and Lovecraft references it repeatedly in exploring alien [[archaeology]].\n\n===Religion===\nLovecraft's works are ruled by several distinct pantheons of deities (actually aliens worshiped as such by humans) who are either indifferent or actively hostile to humanity. Lovecraft's actual philosophy has been termed \"cosmic indifference\" and this is expressed in his fiction.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Mosig |first=Yozan Dirk W. |date=August 1, 1985 |orig-year=first published 1979 |title=Lovecraft: The Dissonance Factor in Imaginative Literature |magazine=Crypt of Cthulhu |volume=4 |issue=8 |pages=12\u201323}}</ref> Several of Lovecraft's stories of the Old Ones (alien beings of the Cthulhu Mythos) propose alternate mythic human origins in contrast to those found in the [[creation myth|creation]] stories of existing religions, expanding on a natural world view. For instance, in Lovecraft's ''[[At the Mountains of Madness]]'', it is proposed that humankind was actually created as a slave race by the Old Ones, and that life on Earth as we know it evolved from scientific experiments abandoned by the Elder Things. Protagonist characters in Lovecraft are usually educated men, citing scientific and rational evidence to support their non-faith. ''[[Herbert West\u2013Reanimator]]'' reflects on the [[atheism]] common in academic circles. In ''[[The Silver Key]]'', the character [[Randolph Carter]] loses the ability to dream and seeks solace in religion, specifically [[Congregationalism in the United States|Congregationalism]], but does not find it and ultimately loses faith.\n\nLovecraft himself adopted the stance of atheism early in life. In 1932, he wrote in a letter to [[Robert E. Howard]]:\n\n<blockquote>All I say is that I think it is damned unlikely that anything like a central cosmic will, a spirit world, or an eternal survival of personality exist. They are the most preposterous and unjustified of all the guesses which can be made about the universe, and I am not enough of a hairsplitter to pretend that I don't regard them as arrant and negligible moonshine. In theory, I am an [[Agnosticism|agnostic]], but pending the appearance of radical evidence I must be classed, practically and provisionally, as an atheist.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=Selected Letters 1932\u20131934 |publisher=Arkham House |year=1976 |location=Sauk City, Wisconsin |page=57 |chapter=Letter to Robert E. Howard (August 16, 1932)}}\"</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Superstition===\nIn 1926, famed [[Magic (illusion)|magician]] and [[Escapology|escapist]] [[Harry Houdini]] asked Lovecraft to ghostwrite a treatise exploring the topic of superstition. Houdini's unexpected death later that year halted the project, but ''[[The Cancer of Superstition]]'' was partially completed by Lovecraft along with collaborator [[C. M. Eddy Jr.]] A previously unknown manuscript of the work was discovered in 2016 in a collection owned by a magic shop. The book states \"all superstitious beliefs are relics of a common 'prehistoric ignorance' in humans,\" and goes on to explore various superstitious beliefs in different cultures and times.\"<ref name=\"Flood\">{{Cite news |last=Flood |first=Alison |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/mar/16/hp-lovecraft-harry-houdini-manuscript-cancer-superstition-memorabilia |title=Lost HP Lovecraft work commissioned by Houdini escapes shackles of history |date=March 16, 2016 |work=The Guardian |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008115009/https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/mar/16/hp-lovecraft-harry-houdini-manuscript-cancer-superstition-memorabilia |archive-date=October 8, 2016 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== Lovecraft Country ===\n{{main|Lovecraft Country}}\n\nLovecraft drew extensively from his native New England for settings in his fiction. Numerous historical cities and towns are mentioned, and several fictionalised version of them make frequent appearances in his stories.{{refn|These fictional locations include [[Arkham]], [[Dunwich (Lovecraft)|Dunwich]], [[Innsmouth]], and Kingsport.<ref name=\"murray54\">{{Cite journal |last=Murray |first=Will |author-link=Will Murray |date=October 1, 1986 |title=In Search of Arkham Country |url=https://archive.org/details/Lovecraft_Studies_13v05n02_1986-Fall_CosmicJukebox/page/n13/mode/2up |journal=Lovecraft Studies |volume=5 |issue=2 |pages=54\u201367}}</ref>|group= n}} These municipalities are located in the western half of a fictionalized version of Massachusetts. The exact locations of these municipalities were subject to change, as Lovecraft had shifting literary needs. They were based on areas that he thought were evocative. He then redefined them and changed their names to suit his purposes. After this, he would exaggerate their features. For example, Arkham was based on a town named [[Oakham, Massachusetts|Oakham]]. Lovecraft renamed his fictionalized version of Oakham to Arkham, and expanded it to include a nearby landmark.<ref name=\"murray54\" />\n\n==Appreciation==\n\n===Within the genre===\nBy 1957 [[Floyd C. Gale]] of ''[[Galaxy Science Fiction]]'' said that \"like [[Robert E. Howard|R. E. Howard]], Lovecraft seemingly goes on forever; the two decades since their death are as nothing. In any event, they appear more prolific than ever. What with [[L. Sprague de Camp|de Camp]], [[Bj\u00f6rn Nyberg|Nyberg]] and Derleth avidly rooting out every scrap of their writings and expanding them into novels, there may never be an end to their posthumous careers.\"<ref name=\"gale195712\">{{Cite magazine |last=Gale |first=Floyd C. |date=April 1960 |title=Galaxy's 5 Star Shelf |url=https://archive.org/stream/galaxymagazine-1957-12/Galaxy_1957_12#page/n101/mode/2up |magazine=Galaxy Science Fiction |pages=100\u2013103 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322141855/https://archive.org/stream/galaxymagazine-1957-12/Galaxy_1957_12#page/n101/mode/2up |archive-date=March 22, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> According to [[Joyce Carol Oates]], Lovecraft (and [[Edgar Allan Poe]] in the 19th century) has exerted \"an incalculable influence on succeeding generations of writers of horror fiction.\"<ref name=\"Oates\">{{Cite journal |last=Oates |first=Joyce Carol |date=October 31, 1996 |title=The King of Weird |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/1376 |url-status=live |journal=The New York Review of Books |volume=43 |issue=17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090910081313/http://www.nybooks.com/articles/1376 |archive-date=September 10, 2009}}</ref> Horror, fantasy, and science fiction author [[Stephen King]] called Lovecraft \"the twentieth century's greatest practitioner of the classic horror tale.\"<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Wohleber |first=Curt |date=December 1995 |title=The Man Who Can Scare Stephen King |url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/man-who-can-scare-stephen-king?page=show |url-status=live |journal=[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]] |volume=46 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004220300/http://www.americanheritage.com/content/man-who-can-scare-stephen-king?page=show |archive-date=October 4, 2013 |number=8}}</ref> King has made it clear in his semi-autobiographical non-fiction book ''[[Danse Macabre (book)|Danse Macabre]]'' that Lovecraft was responsible for his own fascination with horror and the macabre and was the largest figure to influence his fiction writing.<ref>{{Cite book |last=King |first=Stephen |url=http://www.librosgratisweb.com/html/king-stephen/danse-macabre/index.htm |title=Danse Macabre |date=February 1987 |publisher=[[Berkley Books|Berkley]] |isbn=978-0-425-10433-0 |page=63 |author-link=Stephen King |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004222501/http://www.librosgratisweb.com/html/king-stephen/danse-macabre/index.htm |archive-date=October 4, 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Literary===\nEarly efforts to revise an established literary view of Lovecraft as an author of 'pulp' were resisted by some eminent critics; in 1945 [[Edmund Wilson]] expressed the opinion that \"the only real horror in most of these fictions is the horror of bad taste and bad art.\" However, Wilson praised Lovecraft's ability to write about his chosen field; he described him as having written about it \"with much intelligence.\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Wilson |first=Edmund |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=auPpqXw6bGQC&q=Tales+of+the+Marvellous+and+the+Ridiculous#v=snippet&q=Tales%20of%20the%20Marvellous%20and%20the%20Ridiculous&f=false |title=Classics and Commercials: A Literary Chronicle of the Forties |date=1950 |publisher=Macmillan |isbn=978-0-374-52667-2 |pages=286\u2013290 |language=en |orig-year=first published November 24, 1945}}</ref> According to L. Sprague de Camp, Wilson later revised his opinion of Lovecraft in a more positive direction. He claimed that Wilson had included a Lovecraftian reference in ''Little Blue Light: A Play in Three Acts''. After he met with him to discuss this, Wilson revealed that he had been reading a copy of Lovecraft's correspondence.<ref name=\"Fantasy Mongers\">{{Cite magazine |last=de Camp |first=L. Sprague |date=March 1979 |title=H. P. Lovecraft and Edmund Wilson |magazine=Fantasy Mongers |issue=1 |page=5}}</ref>{{refn|L. Sprague de Camp also claimed that they began calling each other \"Monstro.\" This is a direct reference to the nicknames that Lovecraft gave to some of his correspondents.<ref name=\"Fantasy Mongers\" />|group= n}} ''Mystery and Adventure'' columnist [[Will Cuppy]] of the ''[[New York Herald Tribune]]'' recommended to readers a volume of Lovecraft's stories, asserting that \"the literature of horror and macabre fantasy belongs with mystery in its broader sense.\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Cuppy |first=Will |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ua8YAAAAIAAJ&q=the+literature+of+horror+and+macabre+fantasy+belongs+with+mystery+in+its+broader+sense.&dq=the+literature+of+horror+and+macabre+fantasy+belongs+with+mystery+in+its+broader+sense. |title=Book Review Digest |date=1944 |publisher=H. W. Wilson Company |volume=39 |page=510 |language=en |author-link=Will Cuppy |orig-year=first published 1943}}</ref>\n\nGale said that \"Lovecraft at his best could build a mood of horror unsurpassed; at his worst, he was laughable.\"{{r|gale195712}} In 1962 [[Colin Wilson]], in his survey of anti-realist trends in fiction ''The Strength to Dream'', cited Lovecraft as one of the pioneers of the \"assault on rationality\" and included him with [[M. R. James]], [[H. G. Wells]], [[Aldous Huxley]], [[J. R. R. Tolkien]] and others as one of the builders of mythicised realities over against the failing project of literary realism.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}} Subsequently, Lovecraft began to acquire the status of a cult writer in the [[counterculture]] of the 1960s, and reprints of his work proliferated.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Luckhurst |first=Roger |title=The Classic Horror Stories |date=May 9, 2013 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-164089-6 |pages=xiii\u2013xiv |language=en |chapter=Introduction |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vQDDYhl057sC&q=Strange+things+started+happening+to+Lovecraft%27s+reputation+in+the+1960s.#v=snippet&q=Strange%20things%20started%20happening%20to%20Lovecraft's%20reputation%20in%20the%201960s.&f=false}}</ref>\nIn 2005, the status of classic American writer was accorded to Lovecraft with the publication of ''Tales'', a collection of his weird fiction stories, by the [[Library of America]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Stefans |first=Brian Kim |date=April 6, 2013 |title=Let's Get Weird: On Graham Harman's H.P. Lovecraft |url=http://lareviewofbooks.org/review/lets-get-weird-on-graham-harmans-h-p-lovecraft |magazine=Los Angeles Review of Books |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017005119/http://lareviewofbooks.org/review/lets-get-weird-on-graham-harmans-h-p-lovecraft |archive-date=October 17, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Philosophical===\nPhilosopher [[Graham Harman]], seeing Lovecraft as having a unique\u2014though implicit\u2014[[Antireductionism|anti-reductionalist]] [[ontology]], writes: \"No other writer is so perplexed by the gap between objects and the power of language to describe them, or between objects and the qualities they possess.\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Harman |first=Graham |url=https://books.google.com/?id=XQ_tBAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |title=Weird Realism: Lovecraft and Philosophy |date=2012-09-28 |publisher=John Hunt Publishing |isbn=978-1-78099-907-4 |page=3 |language=en}}</ref>\nHarman said of leading figures at the initial [[speculative realism]] conference (which included philosophers [[Quentin Meillassoux]], [[Ray Brassier]], and [[Iain Hamilton Grant]]) that, though they shared no philosophical heroes, all were enthusiastic readers of Lovecraft.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Speculative realists, [[Mark Fisher (theorist)|Mark Fisher]] and other contemporary philosophers, took Lovecraft seriously, mainly because Lovecraft's weird reality as presented in his novels, had nothing to do with the Gothic's insistence in the supernatural, but presented another reality incomprehensible to the human mind, but nonetheless real. According to scholar [[S. T. Joshi]]: \"There is never an entity in Lovecraft that is not in some fashion material.\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ubE5ylK0GTgC&pg=PA186&dq=There+is+never+an+entity+in+Lovecraft+that+is+not+in+some+fashion+material.#v=onepage&q=There%20is%20never%20an%20entity%20in%20Lovecraft%20that%20is%20not%20in%20some%20fashion%20material.&f=false |title=The Weird Tale |date=2003-01-01 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-0-8095-3122-6 |page=186 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Influence on culture==\n[[File:H. P. Lovecraft Memorial Plaque at 22 Prospect Street.jpg|thumb|H. P. Lovecraft memorial plaque at 22 Prospect Street in [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]].]]\n{{main|Lovecraftian horror|Cthulhu Mythos in popular culture}}\n{{more citations needed section|date=May 2012}}\n\nLovecraft was relatively unknown during his own time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.denofgeek.com/movies/16993/hp-lovecraft-an-appreciation |title=HP Lovecraft: an appreciation |date=February 8, 2011 |website=denofgeek.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425231937/http://www.denofgeek.com/movies/16993/hp-lovecraft-an-appreciation |archive-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> While his stories appeared in the pages of prominent pulp magazines such as ''Weird Tales'' (eliciting letters of outrage as often as letters of praise from regular readers), not many people knew his name. He did, however, correspond regularly with other contemporary writers such as Clark Ashton Smith and August Derleth,<ref>{{Cite book |last=Schoell |first=William |title=H.P. Lovecraft: Master of Weird Fiction |publisher=Morgan Reynolds |year=2004 |isbn=9781931798150 |pages=8\u201340}}</ref> who became good friends of his, even though they never met in person. This group of writers became known as the \"Lovecraft Circle,\" since their writing freely borrowed elements of Lovecraft's stories, with his encouragement: the mysterious books with disturbing names, the pantheon of ancient alien entities such as Cthulhu and Azathoth, and eldritch places such as the New England town of [[Arkham]] and its [[Miskatonic University]].\n\nAfter Lovecraft's death, the Lovecraft Circle carried on. August Derleth in particular added to and expanded on Lovecraft's vision, not without controversy. While Lovecraft considered his pantheon of alien gods a mere plot device, Derleth created an entire cosmology, complete with a war between the good [[Elder God (Cthulhu Mythos)|Elder Gods]] and the evil [[Outer God]]s, such as [[Cthulhu]] and his ilk. The forces of good were supposed to have won, locking Cthulhu and others up beneath the earth, in the ocean, and so forth. Derleth's Cthulhu Mythos stories went on to associate different gods with the traditional four [[Classical element|elements of fire, air, earth and water]] \u2014 an artificial constraint which required rationalizations on Derleth's part as Lovecraft himself never envisioned such a scheme.\n\nLovecraft's fiction has been grouped into three categories by some critics. While Lovecraft did not refer to these categories himself, he did once write: \"There are my 'Poe' pieces and my '[[Edward Plunkett, 18th Baron of Dunsany|Dunsany]] pieces' \u2014 but alas \u2014 where are any Lovecraft pieces?\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=The New Annotated H. P. Lovecraft |date=October 13, 2014 |publisher=W. W. Norton & Company |isbn=978-1-63149-055-2 |editor-last=Klinger |editor-first=Leslie S. |page=xxiii |language=en}}</ref>\n* Macabre stories ({{circa}} 1905\u20131920);\n* [[Dream Cycle]] stories ({{circa}} 1920\u20131927);\n* [[Cthulhu Mythos|Cthulhu{{\\}}Lovecraft Mythos]] stories ({{circa}} 1925\u20131935).\n\nLovecraft's writing, particularly the so-called Cthulhu Mythos, has influenced fiction authors including modern horror and fantasy writers. [[Stephen King]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.americanheritage.com/man-who-can-scare-stephen-king |title=The Man Who Can Scare Stephen King &#124; AMERICAN HERITAGE |website=www.americanheritage.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725231046/https://www.americanheritage.com/man-who-can-scare-stephen-king |archive-date=July 25, 2019}}</ref> [[Ramsey Campbell]], [[Bentley Little]], [[Joe R. Lansdale]], [[Alan Moore]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://thequietus.com/articles/16129-alan-moore-providence-cthulhu-philosophy-language-lovecraft |title=All About Alienation: Alan Moore On Lovecraft And Providence |last=Talbot |first=Nick |date=August 31, 2014 |website=The Quietus}}</ref> [[Junji Ito]], [[F. Paul Wilson]], [[Brian Lumley]], [[Caitl\u00edn R. Kiernan]], [[William S. Burroughs]], and [[Neil Gaiman]], have cited Lovecraft as one of their primary influences. Beyond direct adaptation, Lovecraft and his stories have had a profound impact on popular culture. Some influence was direct, as he was a friend, inspiration, and correspondent to many of his contemporaries, such as August Derleth, Robert E. Howard, Robert Bloch and [[Fritz Leiber]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-17472580 |title=The long hand of Lovecraft |date=March 22, 2012 |work=BBC News |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712064826/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-17472580 |archive-date=July 12, 2018 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Many later figures were influenced by Lovecraft's works, including author and artist [[Clive Barker]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5k6mfyb3lld560XTKQmCG9Q/a-quick-guide-to-the-best-cult-authors |title=BBC Radio 4 - The Case of Charles Dexter Ward - A quick guide to the best cult authors |website=BBC |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817170958/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5k6mfyb3lld560XTKQmCG9Q/a-quick-guide-to-the-best-cult-authors |archive-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> prolific horror writer Stephen King,<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\" /> Brian Keene<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.briankeene.com/ |title=Brian Keene |website=Brian Keene |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170522065823/http://www.briankeene.com/ |archive-date=May 22, 2017}}</ref> has several novels based on the Old Gods, comics writers Alan Moore, Neil Gaiman<ref name=\"irishtimes.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/hp-lovecraft-love-the-craft-loathe-the-creed-1.2489413 |title=HP Lovecraft: love the craft, loathe the creed |website=irishtimes.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421192246/http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/hp-lovecraft-love-the-craft-loathe-the-creed-1.2489413 |archive-date=April 21, 2016}}</ref> and [[Mike Mignola]], English author [[Colin Wilson]], film directors [[John Carpenter]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.denofgeek.com/movies/18189/hp-lovecraft-and-his-lasting-impact-on-cinema |title=HP Lovecraft and his lasting impact on cinema |date=October 14, 2011 |website=denofgeek.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160801213417/http://www.denofgeek.com/movies/18189/hp-lovecraft-and-his-lasting-impact-on-cinema |archive-date=August 1, 2016}}</ref> [[Stuart Gordon]], [[Guillermo del Toro]]<ref name=\"irishtimes.com\" /> and artist [[H. R. Giger]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Giger |first=H. R. |title=Necronomicon |publisher=Morpheus International |year=1993 |isbn=978-0962344725 |edition=New |orig-year=1977}}</ref> Japan has also been significantly inspired and terrified by Lovecraft's creations and thus even entered the [[manga]] and [[anime]] media. [[Chiaki J. Konaka]] is an acknowledged disciple and has participated in Cthulhu Mythos, expanding several Japanese versions.<ref name=\"askjohn546\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.animenation.net/blog/2002/08/13/ask-john-is-there-any-lovecraftian-anime/ |title=Ask John: Is There Any Lovecraftian Anime? |publisher=[[AnimeNation]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020813010101/http://www.animenation.net/blog/2002/08/13/ask-john-is-there-any-lovecraftian-anime/ |archive-date=August 13, 2002}}</ref> He is an anime scriptwriter who tends to add elements of cosmicism, and is credited for spreading the influence of Lovecraft among the anime base.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Bush |first=Laurence |title=Asian Horror Encyclopedia |publisher=Writers Club Press |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-595-20181-5 |pages=101\u2013102}}</ref> Along with [[Junji Ito]], other influential manga artists have also been inspired by Lovecraft.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Ito |first=Junji |title=Uzumaki, Vol. 1 |date=October 2007 |publisher=[[Viz Media]] |isbn=978-1-4215-1389-8 |edition=2nd |page=207 |orig-year=1998}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.78magazine.com/issues/03-01/arts/junji.shtml |title=Into the Spiral: A Conversation with Japanese Horror Maestro Junji Ito |last=Mira Bai Winsby |date=March 2006 |website=78 Magazine |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022184345/http://www.78magazine.com/issues/03-01/arts/junji.shtml |archive-date=October 22, 2014}}</ref> Novelist and manga author, [[Hideyuki Kikuchi]], incorporated a number of locations, beings and events from the works of Lovecraft into the manga ''[[Taimashin]]''.<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=TAIMASHIN: Vol. 1 Hideyuki Kikuchi, Author, Misaki Saitoh, Illustrator |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-4139-0036-1 |magazine=[[Publishers Weekly]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122053700/http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-4139-0036-1 |archive-date=January 22, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nArgentine writer [[Jorge Luis Borges]] wrote his short story \"[[There Are More Things]]\" in memory of Lovecraft. Contemporary French writer [[Michel Houellebecq]] wrote a literary biography of Lovecraft called ''[[H. P. Lovecraft: Against the World, Against Life]]''. Prolific American writer Joyce Carol Oates wrote an introduction for a collection of Lovecraft stories. The [[Library of America]] published a volume of Lovecraft's work in 2005, a reversal of traditional judgment that \"has been nothing so far from the accepted [[Western canon|canon]] as Lovecraft.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.loa.org/volume.jsp?RequestID=223 |title=H.P Lovecraft: Tales (The Library of America) |last=H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=Loa.org |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100221224608/http://www.loa.org/volume.jsp?RequestID=223 |archive-date=February 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |date=March 7, 2005 |title=The Horror, the Horror! |url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/Content/Public/Articles/000/000/005/285tmhfa.asp |magazine=The Weekly Standard |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091105095444/http://www.weeklystandard.com/Content/Public/Articles/000/000/005/285tmhfa.asp |archive-date=November 5, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boston.com/ae/books/articles/2005/02/15/the_library_of_america_scares_up_a_collection_of_lovecrafts_local_lore/ |title=The Library of America scares up a collection of Lovecraft's local lore |last=Kenney |first=Michael |date=February 15, 2005 |publisher=Boston.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005004203/http://www.boston.com/ae/books/articles/2005/02/15/the_library_of_america_scares_up_a_collection_of_lovecrafts_local_lore/ |archive-date=October 5, 2013}}</ref> French philosophers [[Gilles Deleuze]] and [[F\u00e9lix Guattari]] refer to Lovecraft in ''[[A Thousand Plateaus]]'', calling the short story \"[[Through the Gates of the Silver Key]]\" one of his masterpieces.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Deleuze |first=Gilles |title=A Thousand Plateaus: Capitalism and Schizophrenia |last2=Guattari |first2=F\u00e9lix |date=1987 |publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]] |isbn=978-0816614011 |location=Minneapolis |pages=240, 539 |translator-last=Massumi |translator-first=Brian |oclc=16472336}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nLovecraft's fictional Mythos has influenced a number of musicians, especially in [[rock music]].  Most notably, the [[psychedelic rock]] band [[H. P. Lovecraft (band)|H. P. Lovecraft]] (who shortened their name to Lovecraft and then Love Craft in the 1970s) released the albums ''[[H. P. Lovecraft (album)|H. P. Lovecraft]]'' and ''[[H. P. Lovecraft II]]'' in 1967 and 1968 respectively; their songs included ''[[The White Ship (song)|The White Ship]]'' and ''At the Mountains of Madness'', both titled after Lovecraft stories. The founders of their record company, [[Bill Traut]] and George Badonsky, were fans of the author and gained August Derleth's permission to use Lovecraft's name for the band.<ref name=\"warburton\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thewhiteship.org/index.php/h-p-lovecraft-history/ |title=The White Ship: The Psychedelic Voyage of H.P. Lovecraft |publisher=Nick Warburton's Rock Music Archive |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180110201805/http://www.thewhiteship.org/index.php/h-p-lovecraft-history |archive-date=January 10, 2018 |access-date=January 31, 2018 }}</ref> [[Metallica]] recorded a song inspired by \"The Call of Cthulhu\", an instrumental titled ''The Call of Ktulu'', a song based on ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]'' titled ''The Thing That Should Not Be'' and another based on [[Frank Belknap Long]]'s ''[[Hounds of Tindalos]]'' titled ''[[All Nightmare Long]]''. Later, they released the song ''Dream No More'', which mentions the awakening of Cthulhu.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/M/Metallica/2008/12/08/7668306-sun.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120524233607/http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/M/Metallica/2008/12/08/7668306-sun.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 24, 2012 |title=CANOE \u2013 JAM! Music \u2013 Artists \u2013 Metallica: Interview with James Hetfield |date=December 8, 2008 |publisher=Jam.canoe.ca |access-date=October 3, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://loudwire.com/hp-lovecraft-inspried-metal-songs/ |title=11 METAL SONGS INSPIRED BY H.P. LOVECRAFT |website=Loudwire |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709162311/https://loudwire.com/hp-lovecraft-inspried-metal-songs/ |archive-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> Technical death metal outfit [[Revocation (band)]] frequently write songs based on Lovecraft's stories and frequently use him as inspiration in their original works.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/editorials/277677/metal-mike-into-the-madness-of-death-metal-sci-fi-horror-with-revocation/ |title=Metal & Mike: Into The Madness Of Death Metal, Sci-Fi & Horror With REVOCATION |last=Pementel |first=Michael |date=September 14, 2018 |website=Dread Central |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708222308/https://www.dreadcentral.com/editorials/277677/metal-mike-into-the-madness-of-death-metal-sci-fi-horror-with-revocation/ |archive-date=July 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, [[Synthwave]] band, [[Gunship (band)|Gunship]] released a track called Cthulhu that featured an introductory monologue by [[Corin Hardy]]. Hardy's opening monologue makes reference to Lovecraft's Cthulhu Mythos directly mentioning the \"Great Old Ones\", the cults that worshipped them and the city in which Cthulhu resided, R'lyeh.\n\nAccording to the band's official YouTube channel, Gunship member, Dan Haigh, was quoted as saying:<blockquote>I just felt like writing something creeping, twisted, and possibly dripping with slime. Most importantly, I felt like creating something transportative. I hope the track takes its listeners on a journey to the darkest corners of their imaginations\u2026 listen \u2013 taste the salt on the sea air \u2013 witness the slathering foul beast rise from his slumber\u2026<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jo4-Bc85bF4 |title=GUNSHIP - CTHULHU (feat. Corin Hardy) [Official Audio] |date=February 11, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221041808/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jo4-Bc85bF4&gl=US&hl=en&has_verified=1&bpctr=9999999999 |archive-date=December 21, 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Games===\nLovecraft has also influenced gaming, despite having hated games during his lifetime.<ref name=\"Letters 1932-1934\">{{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=Selected Letters: 1932-1934 |title-link=Selected Letters of H. P. Lovecraft IV (1932\u20131934) |date=1965 |publisher=Arkham House |isbn=9780870540356 |volume=4 |page=13 |language=en}}</ref> [[Chaosium]]'s [[Tabletop role-playing game|tabletop]] [[role-playing game]] ''[[Call of Cthulhu (role-playing game)|Call of Cthulhu]]'', released in 1981 and currently in its seventh major edition, was one of the first games to draw heavily from Lovecraft. Novel to the game was the Lovecraft-inspired [[insanity]] mechanic, which allowed for [[player character]]s to go insane from contact with cosmic horrors. This mechanic would go on to make appearance in subsequent table top and [[video game]]s.<ref name=\"Gollop17\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/the-gollop-chamber-where-are-all-the-lovecraftian-games/ |title=The Gollop Chamber: Where are all the Lovecraftian games? |last=Gollop |first=Julian |date=November 16, 2017 |website=pcgamer |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307151043/https://www.pcgamer.com/the-gollop-chamber-where-are-all-the-lovecraftian-games/ |archive-date=March 7, 2018}}</ref>\n1987 saw the release of one of the first Lovecraftian [[board game]]s, ''[[Arkham Horror]]'', which sold extremely well, and since 2004 is still in print from [[Fantasy Flight Games]].\nThough few subsequent Lovecraftian board games were released annually between 1987 and 2014, the years after 2014 saw a surge in the number of Lovecraftian board games, possibly because of the entry of Lovecraft's work into the [[public domain]] combined with a revival of interest in board games.<ref name=\"Silva17\">{{Cite news |last=Silva |first=Christianna |url=https://www.npr.org/2017/06/07/530186764/h-p-lovecrafts-monster-is-wrapping-family-game-night-up-in-tentacles |title=H.P. Lovecraft's Monster Is Wrapping Family Game Night Up In Tentacles |date=June 7, 2017 |work=NPR.org |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228173021/https://www.npr.org/2017/06/07/530186764/h-p-lovecrafts-monster-is-wrapping-family-game-night-up-in-tentacles |archive-date=February 28, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nFew video games are direct adaptations of Lovecraft's works, but many video games have been inspired or heavily influenced by Lovecraft.<ref name=\"Gollop17\" />\nThe massively-multiplayer online game ''[[World of Warcraft]]'' by [[Blizzard Entertainment]] has continually revealed more of the origin story of the game's playable world to the players, most of which very closely mirrors Lovecraft's work or Derleth's expansion onto the author's original content.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/11/06/know-your-lore-tinfoil-hat-edition-the-genesis-of-azeroth/ |title=Know Your Lore, Tinfoil Hat Edition: The genesis of Azeroth |work=Engadget |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116111659/https://www.engadget.com/2011/11/06/know-your-lore-tinfoil-hat-edition-the-genesis-of-azeroth/ |archive-date=November 16, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>  [[Survival horror|Horror games]] especially can incorporate Cthulthean terrors, despite the conflict between \"act-and-prevail\" nature of video games and the cosmic hopelessness of Lovecraftian horror.\nBesides employing Cthulthean antagonists, games that invoke Lovecraftian horror have used mechanics such as insanity effects, or even [[fourth wall]] breaking effects that suggest to players that something has gone wrong with their [[Video game console|game consoles]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Perron |first=Bernard |url=https://books.google.com/?id=pNaQLQC9XhEC&pg=PA267&dq=cosmic+horror+in+video+games#v=onepage |title=Horror Video Games: Essays on the Fusion of Fear and Play |date=August 25, 2009 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786454792 |pages=279\u2013285 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Religion and occultism===\nSeveral contemporary religions have drawn influence from the works of Lovecraft. ''[[The Satanic Rituals]]'', written either by [[Anton LaVey]] or Michael A. Aquino, includes an essay which claims that the works of Lovecraft carry a partial truth, used in the same symbolic manner as [[Satan]]. [[Kenneth Grant]] of the [[Typhonian Order]] incorporated Lovecraft's Mythos into his ritual and occult system, but in a more direct and literal sense than the Church of Satan. However, the Typhonian Order does not consider the entities to be directly existent, but rather a symbol through which people may interact with something inhuman.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.popmatters.com/cults-of-an-unwitting-oracle-the-unintended-religious-legacy-of-h-p-lovecraft-2496158350.html |title=Cults of an Unwitting Oracle: The (Unintended) Religious Legacy of H. P. Lovecraft |last=Quinn |first=Dennis P. |date=August 19, 2010 |website=PopMatters |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111195159/https://www.popmatters.com/cults-of-an-unwitting-oracle-the-unintended-religious-legacy-of-h-p-lovecraft-2496158350.html |archive-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Engle |first=John |date=October 15, 2014 |title=Cults of Lovecraft: The Impact of H.P. Lovecraft's Fiction on Contemporary Occult Practices |url=https://dc.swosu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1034&context=mythlore |journal=Mythlore |volume=33 |issue=125 |pages=85\u201398 |via=SWOSU Digital Commons}}</ref> \n\nThere have been several books that have claimed to be an authentic edition of Lovecraft's ''[[Necronomicon]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Clore |first=Dan |date=n.d. |orig-year=first published Fall 2001 |title=The Lurker on the Threshold of Interpretation: Hoax ''Necronomicons'' and Paratextual Noise |url=http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/9879/lurker.htm |journal=Lovecraft Studies |pages=61\u201369 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091026163759/http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/9879/lurker.htm |archive-date=October 26, 2009 |via=Yahoo! GeoCities}}</ref> The ''[[Simon Necronomicon]]'' is one such example. It was written by an unknown figure who identified themselves as \"Simon.\" [[Peter Levenda]], an occult author who has written about the ''Necronomicon'', claims that he and \"Simon\" came across a hidden Greek translation of the grimoire while looking through a collection of antiquities at a New York bookstore during the 1960s or 1970s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tMMrqUS8-As |title=Finding the Simon Necronomicon |date=Nov 30, 2014 |publisher=The Lip TV |language=en |via=YouTube |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208154000/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tMMrqUS8-As |archive-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref> This book was claimed to have born the seal of the ''Necronomicon''. Levenda went on to claim that Lovecraft had access to this purported scroll.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Matthews |first=Carol S. |date=April 15, 2018 |title=Letting Sleeping Abnormalities Lie |url=https://dc.swosu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1160&context=mythlore |journal=Mythlore |volume=36 |issue=2 |pages=165\u2013184 |via=SWOSU Digital Commons}}</ref> A textual analysis has determined that the contents of this book were derived from multiple documents that discuss [[Ancient Mesopotamian religion|Mesopotamian myth]] and magic. The finding of a magical text by monks is also a common theme in the history of grimoires.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Davies |first=Owen |url=https://books.google.com/?id=_iaQDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=The%20most%20successful%20of%20the%20print%20editions%20was%20the%20Simon%20Necronomicon%2C%20a%20ninth-century%20Greek%20text%20discovered%20by%20monks%20and%20brought%20to%20America%20in%20the%201970s%20by%20an%20Eastern%20Orthodox%20bishop%20named%20Simon.&f=false |title=Grimoires: A History of Magic Books |date=March 26, 2009 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-154810-9 |page=268 |language=en}}</ref> It has been suggested that Lavenda is the true author of the ''Simon Necronomicon''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/11/12/4849860/the-cult-of-cthulhu-real-prayer-for-a-fake-tentacle |title=The Cult of Cthulhu: Real Prayer for a Fake Tentacle |last=Flatley |first=Joseph L. |date=November 12, 2013 |website=The Verge |language=en-US |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029013156/https://www.theverge.com/2013/11/12/4849860/the-cult-of-cthulhu-real-prayer-for-a-fake-tentacle |archive-date=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Lovecraft as a fictional character===\n{{Primary sources|section|date=January 2020}}\n\nAside from his appearance in [[Robert Bloch]]'s ''[[The Shambler from the Stars]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blog.loa.org/2010/09/what-robert-bloch-owes-to-h-p-lovecraft.html |title=What Robert Bloch owes to H. P. Lovecraft |date=September 23, 2010 |publisher=The Library of America |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101021030024/http://blog.loa.org/2010/09/what-robert-bloch-owes-to-h-p-lovecraft.html |archive-date=October 21, 2010}}</ref> Lovecraft continues to be used as a character in supernatural fiction. He makes a brief appearance in an early version of [[Ray Bradbury]]'s ''The Exiles''.<ref>Published in ''[[The Magazine of Fantasy & Science Fiction]]'', Volume 1 No. 2 (Winter-Spring 1950), and later to become part of Bradbury's ''[[Martian Chronicles]]''</ref> [[John Shirley]]'s story ''When Death Wakes Me To Myself'' offers a tale of a therapy patient slowly remembering a former incarnation when he was H. P. Lovecraft.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hippocampuspress.com/mythos-and-other-authors/fiction/lovecraft-alive-a-collection-of-lovecraftian-stories-by-john-shirley |title=Lovecraft Alive! A Collection of Lovecraftian Stories by John Shirley |date=July 4, 2016 |publisher=Hippocampus Press |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161015160545/http://www.hippocampuspress.com/mythos-and-other-authors/fiction/lovecraft-alive-a-collection-of-lovecraftian-stories-by-john-shirley |archive-date=October 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOther notable works with Lovecraft as a character include [[Richard Lupoff]]'s ''Lovecraft's Book'' (1985), ''[[Cast a Deadly Spell]]'' (1991), ''[[H.P. Lovecraft's: Necronomicon]]'' (1993), ''[[Witch Hunt (1994 film)|Witch Hunt]]'' (1994), ''[[Out of Mind: The Stories of H. P. Lovecraft]]'' (1998), ''[[Stargate SG-1: Roswell]]'' (2007), and [[Alan Moore]]'s comic ''[[Providence (Avatar Press)|Providence]]'' (2015\u201317). Lovecraft also appears in the Season 6, Episode 21 episode ''Let it Bleed'' of the TV show ''[[Supernatural (U.S. TV series)|Supernatural]]''. A satirical version of Lovecraft named H. P. Hatecraft appeared as a recurring character on the [[Cartoon Network]] television series ''[[Scooby-Doo! Mystery Incorporated]]''. Another character based on Lovecraft appears in ''[[Afterlife with Archie]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sullivan |first=Justin |url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/comics/afterlife-with-archie-sabrina-the-teenage-witch-returns/#/8 |title='Afterlife With Archie': Sabrina the Teenage Witch returns |date=July 22, 2014 |work=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514225633/http://herocomplex.latimes.com/comics/afterlife-with-archie-sabrina-the-teenage-witch-returns/#/8 |archive-date=May 14, 2015}}</ref> He appears as a minor character in [[Brian Clevinger]]'s comic book series ''[[Atomic Robo]]'', as an acquaintance and fellow-scientist of [[Nikola Tesla]], having been driven insane by his involvement in the [[Tunguska event]] which exposed him to the hidden horrors of the wider universe. He is eventually killed when his body becomes host to an extradimensional being infecting the timestream.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.atomic-robo.com/atomicrobo/v3ch1-page-19 |title=Atomic Robo - v3ch1 Page 19 |website=www.atomic-robo.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629172346/http://www.atomic-robo.com/atomicrobo/v3ch1-page-19 |archive-date=June 29, 2019}}</ref> Lovecraft is a central plot element, as well as a character in [[Paul LaFarge|Paul La Farge]]'s 2017 novel, ''The Night Ocean''.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Michaud |first=Jon |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/paul-la-farges-the-night-ocean-will-suck-you-into-the-vortex-of-hp-lovecraft/2017/03/02/4d8e1896-ff7e-11e6-8ebe-6e0dbe4f2bca_story.html |title=Paul La Farge's 'The Night Ocean' will suck you into the vortex of H.P. Lovecraft |date=March 2, 2017 |work=The Washington Post |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305111828/https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/paul-la-farges-the-night-ocean-will-suck-you-into-the-vortex-of-hp-lovecraft/2017/03/02/4d8e1896-ff7e-11e6-8ebe-6e0dbe4f2bca_story.html |archive-date=March 5, 2017 |last2=Michaud |first2=Jon |language=en-US |issn=0190-8286}}</ref> In the Japanese manga and anime ''[[Bungo Stray Dogs]]'' there is a character known as Howard Phillips Lovecraft who, like other characters in the series, is named after great literates. His power, \"The Great Old Ones\" pays homage to his classic short story, \"The Call of Cthulhu\" which grants him the ability of transforming himself into an octopus-like monster resembling Cthulhu.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Kafka |first=Asagiri |title=\u6587\u8c6a\u30b9\u30c8\u30ec\u30a4\u30c9\u30c3\u30b0\u30b9 (Bungou Stray Dogs) Volume 5 |publisher=Kadokawa Shoten |year=2014 |isbn=978-4-04-101539-1}}</ref>\n\n== Editions and collections of works ==\n{{more citations needed section|date=May 2012}}\n\nFor most of the 20th century, the definitive editions (specifically ''At the Mountains of Madness and Other Novels'', ''Dagon and Other Macabre Tales'', ''The Dunwich Horror and Others'', and ''The Horror in the Museum and Other Revisions'') of his prose fiction were published by [[Arkham House]], a publisher originally started with the intent of publishing the work of Lovecraft, but which has since published a considerable amount of other literature as well. [[Penguin Classics]] has at present issued three volumes of Lovecraft's works: ''[[The Call of Cthulhu and Other Weird Stories]]'', ''[[The Thing on the Doorstep and Other Weird Stories]]'', and most recently ''[[The Dreams in the Witch House and Other Weird Stories]]''. They collect the standard texts as edited by S. T. Joshi, most of which were available in the Arkham House editions, with the exception of the restored text of ''The Shadow Out of Time'' from ''The Dreams in the Witch House'', which had been previously released by small-press publisher [[Hippocampus Press]]. In 2005 the prestigious [[Library of America]] canonized Lovecraft with a volume of his stories edited by [[Peter Straub]], and Random House's [[Modern Library]] line have issued the \"definitive edition\" of Lovecraft's ''At the Mountains of Madness'' (also including ''[[Supernatural Horror in Literature]]''). In 2014, Liveright Publishing Corp./W. W. Norton published ''The New Annotated H. P. Lovecraft'', edited by [[Leslie S. Klinger]], containing 22 of Lovecraft's tales, with an introduction by [[Alan Moore]]; in September 2019, the second volume of Klinger's annotations, ''The New Annotated H. P. Lovecraft: Beyond Arkham'', containing another 25 of Lovecraft's tales, will appear, together with an introduction by [[Victor LaValle]]. Both volumes are heavily illustrated.\n\nLovecraft's poetry is collected in ''The Ancient Track: The Complete Poetical Works of H. P. Lovecraft'' (Night Shade Books, 2001), while much of his juvenilia, various essays on philosophical, political and literary topics, antiquarian travelogues, and other things, can be found in ''Miscellaneous Writings'' (Arkham House, 1989). Lovecraft's essay ''Supernatural Horror in Literature'', first published in 1927, is a historical survey of horror literature available with endnotes as ''The Annotated Supernatural Horror in Literature''.\n\n===Letters, correspondence, exchange, and contract work===\nAlthough Lovecraft is known mostly for his works of [[weird fiction]], the bulk of his writing consists of voluminous letters about a variety of topics, from weird fiction and art criticism to politics and history. Lovecraft's biographer [[L. Sprague de Camp]] estimates that Lovecraft wrote 100,000 letters in his lifetime, a fifth of which are believed to survive.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/letters/ |title=Lovecraft's Letters |date=September 18, 2019 |website=www.hplovecraft.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628015736/http://www.hplovecraft.com/writings/letters/ |archive-date=June 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe sometimes dated his letters 200 years before the current date, which would have put the writing back in US colonial times, before the [[American Revolution]] (a war that offended his Anglophilia). He explained that he thought that the 18th and 20th centuries were the \"best,\" the former being a period of noble grace, and the latter a century of science.\n\nLovecraft was not an active letter-writer in youth. In 1931 he admitted: \"In youth I scarcely did any letter-writing&nbsp;\u2014 thanking anybody for a present was so much of an ordeal that I would rather have written a two hundred fifty-line pastoral or a twenty-page treatise on the rings of Saturn.\" (SL 3.369\u201370). The initial interest in letters stemmed from his correspondence with his cousin Phillips Gamwell but even more important was his involvement in the amateur journalism movement, which was initially responsible for the enormous number of letters Lovecraft produced.\n\nDespite his light letter-writing in youth, in later life his correspondence was so voluminous that it has been estimated that he may have written around 30,000 letters to various correspondents, a figure which places him second only to [[Voltaire]] as an epistolarian. Lovecraft's later correspondence is primarily to fellow weird fiction writers, rather than to the amateur journalist friends of his earlier years.\n\nLovecraft clearly states that his contact to numerous different people through letter-writing was one of the main factors in broadening his view of the world: \"I found myself opened up to dozens of points of view which would otherwise never have occurred to me. My understanding and sympathies were enlarged, and many of my social, political, and economic views were modified as a consequence of increased knowledge.\"<ref>{{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |url=https://books.google.com/?id=YdO2XRYNUuQC&pg=PA248&lpg=PA248&dq=I+found+myself+opened+up+to+dozens+of+points+of+view+which+would+otherwise+never+have+occurred+to+me.+My+understanding+and+sympathies+were+enlarged,+and+many+of+my+social,+political,+and+economic+views+were+modified+as+a+consequence+of+increased+knowledge.#v=onepage&q=I%20found%20myself%20opened%20up%20to%20dozens%20of%20points%20of%20view%20which%20would%20otherwise%20never%20have%20occurred%20to%20me.%20My%20understanding%20and%20sympathies%20were%20enlarged,%20and%20many%20of%20my%20social,%20political,%20and%20economic%20views%20were%20modified%20as%20a%20consequence%20of%20increased%20knowledge.&f=false |title=A Subtler Magick: The Writings and Philosophy of H.P. Lovecraft |date=December 1, 1996 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-1-880448-61-8 |edition=Third |page=248 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nToday there are five publishing houses that have released letters from Lovecraft, most prominently Arkham House with its five-volume edition ''Selected Letters'' (these volumes severely abridge the letters they contain). Other publishers are [[Hippocampus Press]] (''Letters to Alfred Galpin'' ''et al.''), [[Night Shade Books]] (''Mysteries of Time and Spirit: The Letters of H. P. Lovecraft and Donald Wandrei'' ''et al.''.), [[Necronomicon Press]] (''Letters to Samuel Loveman and Vincent Starrett'' et al.), and University of Tampa Press (''O Fortunate Floridian: H. P. Lovecraft's Letters to R. H. Barlow''). [[S. T. Joshi]] is supervising an ongoing series of volumes collecting Lovecraft's unabridged letters to particular correspondents.\n\n===Copyright and other legal issues===\nDespite several claims to the contrary, there is currently no evidence that any company or individual owns the copyright to any of Lovecraft's work, and it is generally accepted that it has passed into the public domain.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gizmology.net/lovecraft/copyrights.htm |title=The H. P. Lovecraft Library |date=October 3, 2003 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031003114117/http://www.gizmology.net/lovecraft/copyrights.htm |archive-date=October 3, 2003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.aetherial.net/lovecraft/arkham.html |title=The Black Seas of Copyright: Arkham House Publishers and the H.P. Lovecraft Copyrights |website=www.aetherial.net |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224195604/http://www.aetherial.net/lovecraft/arkham.html |archive-date=February 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20110531/02515814477/confusing-case-lovecrafts-copyrights.shtml |title=The Confusing Case Of Lovecraft's Copyrights {{!}} Techdirt |website=Techdirt. |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225040818/https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20110531/02515814477/confusing-case-lovecrafts-copyrights.shtml |archive-date=February 25, 2016}}</ref> Most of his works have been in the public domain outside of the USA since January 1, 2008, 70 calendar years after his death. Works he published during his lifetime between 1925 and 1937 will indisputably be out of copyright as they enter the public domain annually between 2021 and 2033 (pre-1978 works do not use the life+70 rule in the USA).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://copyright.cornell.edu/publicdomain |title=Copyright Term and the Public Domain in the United States &#124; Copyright Information Center |website=copyright.cornell.edu |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911204703/https://copyright.cornell.edu/publicdomain |archive-date=September 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThere has been controversy over the [[copyright]] status of many of Lovecraft's works, especially his later works. Lovecraft had specified that the young [[R. H. Barlow]] would serve as executor of his [[literary estate]],<ref>{{Harvnb|Joshi, Schultz|2001|p=16|ref=hplencyclopedia}}</ref> but these instructions were not incorporated into the will. Nevertheless, his surviving aunt carried out his expressed wishes, and Barlow was given charge of the massive and complex literary estate upon Lovecraft's death.\n\nBarlow deposited the bulk of the papers, including the voluminous correspondence, with the [[John Hay Library]], and attempted to organize and maintain Lovecraft's other writing. [[August Derleth]], an older and more established writer than Barlow, vied for control of the literary estate. One result of these conflicts was the legal confusion over who owned what copyrights.\n\nAll works published before 1925 are [[public domain]] in the US.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.copyright.gov/circs/circ22.pdf |title=How to Investigate the Copyright Status of a Work- U.S. Copyright Office |website=copyright.gov |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100810065221/http://www.copyright.gov/circs/circ22.pdf |archive-date=August 10, 2010}}</ref> With respect to works published later, ownership of the copyrights is disputed.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Before the United States [[Copyright Act of 1976]], copyright lasted for 28 years from publication and a work that did not have its copyright renewed passed into the public domain. The [[Copyright Act of 1976]] retroactively extended this renewal period for all works to a period of 47 years and the [[Copyright Term Extension Act]] of 1998 added another 20 years to that, for a total of 95 years from publication. But everything turned on the renewal or expiration of copyright at the end of the first 28-year term.\n\nThe [[European Union]] [[Copyright Duration Directive]] of 1993 extended the copyrights to 70 years after the author's death. All of Lovecraft's works published during his lifetime became public domain in all 27 European Union countries on January 1, 2008. In those [[Berne Convention for the Protection of Literary and Artistic Works|Berne Convention]] countries that have implemented only the minimum copyright period, copyright expires 50 years after the author's death.\n\nLovecraft prot\u00e9g\u00e9s and part owners of Arkham House, August Derleth and [[Donald Wandrei]], often claimed copyrights over Lovecraft's works. On October 9, 1947, Derleth purchased all rights to ''Weird Tales''. However, since April 1926 at the latest, Lovecraft had reserved to himself all second printing rights to stories published in ''Weird Tales''. ''Weird Tales'' may only have owned the rights to at most six of Lovecraft's tales. Again, even if Derleth did obtain the copyrights to Lovecraft's tales, there is no evidence that the copyrights were renewed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gizmology.net/lovecraft/copyrights.htm |title=Copyright |last=William |first=Johns |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031003114117/http://www.gizmology.net/lovecraft/copyrights.htm |archive-date=October 3, 2003}}</ref> Following Derleth's death in 1971, his attorney proclaimed that all of Lovecraft's literary material was part of the Derleth estate and that it would be \"protected to the fullest extent possible.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.aetherial.net/lovecraft/arkham.html#13 |title=The Black Seas of Copyright: Arkham House Publishers and the H.P. Lovecraft Copyrights |last=Karr |first=Chris J. |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129043906/http://www.aetherial.net/lovecraft/arkham.html#13 |archive-date=November 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nS. T. Joshi concludes in his biography of Lovecraft that Derleth's claims are \"almost certainly fictitious\" and that most of Lovecraft's works published in the amateur press are most likely now in the public domain. The copyright for Lovecraft's works would have been inherited by the only surviving heir named in his 1912 will, his aunt Annie Gamwell. When Gamwell died in 1941, the copyrights passed to her remaining descendants, Ethel Phillips Morrish and Edna Lewis, who then signed a document, sometimes referred to as the Morrish-Lewis gift, permitting Arkham House to republish Lovecraft's works while retaining the copyrights for themselves. Searches of the [[Library of Congress]] have failed to find any evidence that these copyrights were renewed after the 28-year period, making it likely that these works are now in the public domain.\n\nChaosium, publishers of the ''Call of Cthulhu'' role-playing game, have a trademark on the phrase ''The Call of Cthulhu'' for use in game products. [[TSR, Inc.]], original publisher of the ''[[Advanced Dungeons & Dragons]]'' role-playing game, included a section on the Cthulhu Mythos in one of the game's earlier supplements, ''[[Deities & Demigods]]''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/arts/literature/cthulhu5.htm |title=How Cthulhu Works |date=September 4, 2007 |website=howstuffworks.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417100544/http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/arts/literature/cthulhu5.htm |archive-date=April 17, 2016}}</ref> (originally published in 1980 and later renamed to ''Legends & Lore''). TSR later agreed to remove this section at Chaosium's request.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.acaeum.com/ddindexes/setpages/deities.html |title=Deities & Demigods |website=www.acaeum.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812211053/https://www.acaeum.com/ddindexes/setpages/deities.html |archive-date=August 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Lovecraft Holdings, LLC, a company based out of Providence, filed trademark claims for clothing graphics of Lovecraft's name and silhouette.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://trademarks.justia.com/owners/lovecraft-holdings-llc-2613553/ |title=Lovecraft Holdings, LLC Trademarks |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141204170621/http://trademarks.justia.com/owners/lovecraft-holdings-llc-2613553/ |archive-date=December 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nRegardless of the legal disagreements surrounding Lovecraft's works, Lovecraft himself was extremely generous with his own works and encouraged others to borrow ideas from his stories and build on them, particularly with regard to his Cthulhu Mythos.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Mariconda |first=Steven John |url=https://books.google.com/?id=8bBoAAAAMAAJ&q=He+could+thus+encourage+their+use+of+his+Mythos+properties+and+ask+permission+to+use+theirs. |title=On the Emergence of \"Cthulhu\" & Other Observations |last2=Joshi |first2=S. T. |date=1995 |publisher=Necronomicon Press |isbn=978-0-940884-81-6 |page=34 |language=en}}</ref> He encouraged other writers to reference his creations, such as the ''[[Necronomicon]]'', Cthulhu and [[Yog-Sothoth]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bookmans.com/transcending-time-and-space-h-p-lovecraft-lives-on/ |title=Transcending Time and Space: H.P. Lovecraft Lives On |last=Lee P |date=2016 |website=Bookmans Entertainment Exchange |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020151027/https://bookmans.com/transcending-time-and-space-h-p-lovecraft-lives-on/ |archive-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> After his death, many writers have contributed stories and enriched the shared mythology of the Cthulhu Mythos, as well as making numerous references to his work.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{main|H. P. Lovecraft bibliography}}\n\n== Film adaptations ==\nFilms based on the writings of H. P. Lovecraft include the following.<ref name=\"Kaye\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/31-days-halloween-16-films-adapted-horror-giant-hp-lovecraft |title=31 Days of Halloween: 16 Films Adapted from Horror Giant H.P. Lovecraft |last=Kaye |first=Don |date=October 12, 2015 |website=SyFy |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180602135154/http://www.syfy.com/syfywire/31-days-halloween-16-films-adapted-horror-giant-hp-lovecraft |archive-date=June 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*''[[The Haunted Palace]]'' (1963), directed by [[Roger Corman]], starring [[Vincent Price]], and with [[Lon Chaney Jr.]].  Marketed as \"Edgar Allan Poe's ''The Haunted Palace''\", the film is actually based on ''[[The Case of Charles Dexter Ward]]'', and also includes elements taken from ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]'' and \"[[The Dunwich Horror]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lovecraftzine.com/2012/10/24/lovecraft-by-any-other-name-why-the-haunted-palace-is-great/ |title=Lovecraft by Any Other Name: Why ''The Haunted Palace'' Is Great |last=Lamssies |first=Dominique |date=October 24, 2012 |website=Lovecraft eZine |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121229181049/http://lovecraftzine.com/2012/10/24/lovecraft-by-any-other-name-why-the-haunted-palace-is-great/ |archive-date=December 29, 2012}}</ref>\n*''[[Die, Monster, Die!]]'' (1965), directed by [[Daniel Haller]], and starring [[Boris Karloff]] and [[Nick Adams (actor, born 1931)|Nick Adams]]. An adaptation of \"[[The Colour Out of Space]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.popmatters.com/178466-die-monster-die-2495693261.html |title=''Die, Monster, Die!'' |last=Macek |first=J.C. III |date=January 23, 2014 |website=PopMatters |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506220938/https://www.popmatters.com/178466-die-monster-die-2495693261.html |archive-date=May 6, 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[The Dunwich Horror (film)|The Dunwich Horror]]'' (1970), directed by Daniel Haller, and starring [[Sandra Dee]], [[Dean Stockwell]], and [[Ed Begley]]. Based on [[The Dunwich Horror|the short story of the same name]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wickedhorror.com/horror-reviews/cult-corner-the-dunwich-horror-1970/ |title=Cult Corner: The Dunwich Horror (1970) |last=Green |first=Zak |date=May 25, 2015 |website=Wicked Horror |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905091822/http://wickedhorror.com/horror-reviews/cult-corner-the-dunwich-horror-1970/ |archive-date=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n*''[[Re-Animator]]'' (1985), directed by [[Stuart Gordon]], and starring [[Jeffrey Combs]], [[Bruce Abbott]], [[Barbara Crampton]], and [[David Gale (actor)|David Gale]]. An adaptation of \"[[Herbert West\u2013Reanimator]]\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Maslin |first=Janet |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/10/18/movies/screen-stuart-gordon-directs-re-animator.html |title=Screen: Stuart Gordon Directs ''Re-Animator'' |date=October 18, 1985 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191210044231/https://www.nytimes.com/1985/10/18/movies/screen-stuart-gordon-directs-re-animator.html |archive-date=December 10, 2019 |website=New York Times}}</ref>\n*''[[From Beyond (film)|From Beyond]]'' (1986), directed by Stuart Gordon, and starring Jeffrey Combs, Barbara Crampton, and [[Ken Foree]]. Based on [[From Beyond (short story)|the short story of the same name]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/30-years-later-beyond-lovecraft-his-kinkiest |title=30 Years Later, ''From Beyond'' Is Lovecraft at His Kinkiest |last=Kaye |first=Don |date=October 28, 2016 |website=SyFy |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180530195325/http://www.syfy.com/syfywire/30-years-later-beyond-lovecraft-his-kinkiest |archive-date=May 30, 2018}}</ref>\n*''[[The Curse (1987 film)|The Curse]]'' (1987), directed by [[David Keith]], and starring [[Wil Wheaton]].  Based on \"[[The Colour Out of Space]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://crypticrock.com/this-week-in-horror-movie-history-the-curse-1987/ |title=This Week in Horror Movie History \u2013 The Curse (1987) |last=Allen |first=Tracy |date=September 12, 2014 |website=Cryptic Rock |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150321001004/http://crypticrock.com/this-week-in-horror-movie-history-the-curse-1987/ |archive-date=March 21, 2015}}</ref>\n*''[[The Unnamable (film)|The Unnamable]]'' (1988), directed by [[Jean-Paul Ouellette]] and starring [[Mark Kinsey Stephenson]].  Based on [[The Unnamable (short story)|the short story of the same name]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.adventuresinpoortaste.com/2018/11/12/the-unnamable-movie-review-great-special-effects-help-lovecraft-adaptation-exceed-expectations/ |title=The Unnamable (Movie) Review: Great Special Effects Help Lovecraft Adaptation Exceed Expectations |last=Muir |first=Nathaniel |date=November 12, 2018 |website=Adventures In Poor Taste |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710150923/http://www.adventuresinpoortaste.com/2018/11/12/the-unnamable-movie-review-great-special-effects-help-lovecraft-adaptation-exceed-expectations/ |archive-date=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[The Resurrected]]'' (1991), directed by [[Dan O'Bannon]] and starring [[John Terry (actor)|John Terry]], [[Jane Sibbett]], and [[Chris Sarandon]].  Based on ''[[The Case of Charles Dexter Ward]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/reviews/3356891/blu-ray-review-resurrected/ |title=Blu-ray Review: ''The Resurrected'' |last=Coffel |first=Chris |date=August 13, 2015 |website=Bloody Disgusting |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620233046/http://bloody-disgusting.com/reviews/3356891/blu-ray-review-resurrected/ |archive-date=June 20, 2018}}</ref>\n*''[[The Unnamable II: The Statement of Randolph Carter]]'' (1992), directed by Jean-Paul Ouellette and starring Mark Kinsey Stephenson. The film combines story elements from \"[[The Unnamable (short story)|The Unnameable]]\" and \"[[The Statement of Randolph Carter]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://gonewiththetwins.com/new/unnamable-ii-the-statement-of-randolph-carter-1993/ |title=''The Unnamable II: The Statement of Randolph Carter'' |last=Massie |first=Mike |website=Gone with the Twins |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709135012/http://gonewiththetwins.com/new/unnamable-ii-the-statement-of-randolph-carter-1993/ |archive-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[Necronomicon (film)|Necronomicon]]'' (1993), an anthology of three stories based on \"[[The Rats in the Walls]]\", \"[[Cool Air]]\", and ''[[The Whisperer in Darkness]]'', with a wraparound story featuring a fictionalized H. P. Lovecraft.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://doctorzombie.blogspot.com/2006/07/movie-review-necronomicon-1996.html |title=Movie Review: Necronomicon |last=Dr. Zombie |date=July 24, 2006 |website=Dr. Zombie's Midnight Theater of Terror |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620090946/http://doctorzombie.blogspot.com/2006/07/movie-review-necronomicon-1996.html |archive-date=June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[Castle Freak]]'' (1995), directed by Stuart Gordon and starring Jeffrey Combs and Barbara Crampton. Inspired by  \"[[The Outsider (short story)|The Outsider]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3554066/hideous-hungry-loose-brief-history-castle-freak/ |title=Hideous, Hungry and Loose: A Brief History of ''Castle Freak'' |last=Brehmer |first=Nat |date=April 5, 2019 |website=Bloody Disgusting |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408173208/https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3554066/hideous-hungry-loose-brief-history-castle-freak/ |archive-date=April 8, 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[Dagon (film)|Dagon]]'' (2001), directed by Stuart Gordon and starring Ezra Godden, [[Francisco Rabal]], and Raquel Mero\u00f1o. Based on ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nerdist.com/article/lovecraft-films-dagon-re-animator-blu-ray/ |title=Fish People and Mad Scientists: Lovecraft on Film |last=Anderson |first=Kyle |date=July 24, 2018 |website=Nerdist |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806160246/https://nerdist.com/article/lovecraft-films-dagon-re-animator-blu-ray/ |archive-date=August 6, 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[The Call of Cthulhu (film)|The Call of Cthulhu]]'' (2005), a silent black-and-white featurette designed to look like it was released in the late 1920s, when the short story \"[[The Call of Cthulhu]]\" was published.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-call-of-cthulhu-v347041/review |title=The Call of Cthulhu |last=Eder |first=Bruce |website=AllMovie |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523003444/http://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-call-of-cthulhu-v347041/review |archive-date=May 23, 2013}}</ref>\n*''[[Cthulhu (2007 film)|Cthulhu]]'' (2007), directed by Daniel Gildark, and starring Jason Cottle, [[Cara Buono]], and [[Tori Spelling]].  Based on ''[[The Shadow over Innsmouth]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://martianmigrainepress.com/CTHULHU-Is-The-Best-Lovecraftian-Film-You-Didnt-Watch |title=Dan Gildark's ''Cthulhu'' Is the Best Lovecraftian Film You Didn't Watch... |last=Jones |first=Scott R. |date=July 5, 2014 |website=Martian Migraine Press |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160327195644/http://martianmigrainepress.com/CTHULHU-Is-The-Best-Lovecraftian-Film-You-Didnt-Watch |archive-date=March 27, 2016}}</ref>\n*''[[The Whisperer in Darkness (film)|The Whisperer in Darkness]]'' (2011), a black-and-white film designed to look like it was released in the 1930s.  Based on [[The Whisperer in Darkness|the short story of the same name]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://screenanarchy.com/2011/03/the-whisperer-in-darkness-review.html |title=''The Whisperer in Darkness'' Review |last=Ognjanovic |first=Dejan |date=March 26, 2011 |website=Screen Anarchy |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613062954/http://screenanarchy.com/2011/03/the-whisperer-in-darkness-review.html |archive-date=June 13, 2018}}</ref>\n*''[[Color Out of Space (film)|Color Out of Space]]'' (2020), directed by [[Richard Stanley (director)|Richard Stanley]] and starring [[Nicolas Cage]]. Based on \"[[The Colour Out of Space]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/movies/story/2020-01-22/color-out-of-space-review-nicolas-cage |title=Review: An Over-the-Top Nicolas Cage Wigs Out in H.P. Lovecraft's ''Color Out of Space'' |last=Murray |first=Noel |date=January 22, 2020 |website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\n== Documentary biographies and movie portrayals ==\n''[[Lovecraft: Fear of the Unknown]]'' is a 2008 documentary about the life and works of H. P. Lovecraft.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://scottkenemore.com/2009/12/18/documentary-review-lovecraft-fear-of-the-unknown/ |title=Documentary Review: ''Lovecraft: Fear of the Unknown'' |last=Kenmore |first=Scott |date=December 18, 2009 |website=ScottKenmore.com |access-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[Howard Lovecraft and the Frozen Kingdom]]'' (2016), ''[[Howard Lovecraft and the Undersea Kingdom]]'' (2017), and ''[[Howard Lovecraft and the Kingdom of Madness]]'' (2018) are animated movies that are based on graphic novels inspired by the writings of Lovecraft.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/10/h-p-lovecraft-graphic-novel-movie-animated-arcana-shout-1201568108/ |title=Shout! Acquires All U.S. Rights To Arcana Studios' H.P. Lovecraft Animated Film |last=Busch |first=Anita |last2=Busch |first2=Anita |date=2015-10-07 |website=Deadline |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111104105/https://deadline.com/2015/10/h-p-lovecraft-graphic-novel-movie-animated-arcana-shout-1201568108/ |archive-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Speculative fiction/Horror}}\n* [[:Category:H. P. Lovecraft scholars]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=n|colwidth=40em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/publisher-news/article/43793-terror-eternal-the-enduring-popularity-of-h-p-lovecraft.html |title=Terror Eternal: The enduring popularity of H. P. Lovecraft |last=Dziemianowicz |first=Stefan |date=July 12, 2010 |website=[[Publishers Weekly]]}}\n* [http://books.guardian.co.uk/extracts/story/0,6761,1498708,00.html Extract from ''H P Lovecraft: Against the World, Against Life''] by [[Michel Houellebecq]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101230234944/http://www.heymiller.com/2010/08/h-p-lovecraft/ \"H. P. Lovecraft's Afterlife\"] by [[John J. Miller (journalist)|John J. Miller]] of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''\n* {{cite book\n| url = https://books.google.com/?id=cymGaRJmOvgC&pg=RA2-PA38&dq=h.p.+lovecraft,+will+cuppy#v=onepage&q=h.p.%20lovecraft%2C%20will%20cuppy| title = As If: Modern Enchantment and the Literary Prehistory of Virtual Reality\n| publisher = Oxford University Press\n| year = 2011\n| isbn = 978-0-19-988780-4\n| first = Michael\n| last = Saler\n}}\n* {{Cite web |url=https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2006/10/19/the-heroic-nerd/ |title=The Heroic Nerd |last=Sante |first=Luc |authorlink=Luc Sante |date=October 19, 2006 |website=[[The New York Review of Books]] |page=37 |volume=53 |issue=16 |place=New York}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=A Subtler Magick: The Writings and Philosophy of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=[[Wildside Press|Wildside Press LLC]] |year=1996 |isbn=978-1-880448-61-8 |edition=3rd |ref=magick |author-link=S. T. Joshi}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi, S. T. |title=An H. P. Lovecraft Encyclopedia |last2=Schultz, David E. |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |year=2001 |ref=hplencyclopedia}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=I Am Providence |publisher=[[Hippocampus Press]] |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-61498-053-7 |location=New York |ref=harv |author-link=S. T. Joshi}}\n* {{Cite book |last=de Camp |first=L. Sprague |title=H. P. Lovecraft: A Biography |publisher=Barnes & Noble Books |year=1975 |isbn=978-1-56619-994-0 |location=New York |ref=harv |author-link=L. Sprague de Camp}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Poole |first=W. Scott |title=In the Mountains of Madness |publisher=Soft Skull Press |year=2016 |isbn=978-1-59376-647-4 |location=Berkeley, California |ref=harv |author-link=W. Scott Poole}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Roland |first=Paul |title=The Curious Case of H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=Plexus Publishing |year=2014 |isbn=978-0-85965-517-0 |location=London |ref=harv |author-link=PaulRoland}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Montague |first=Charlotte |title=H. P. Lovecraft |publisher=Chartwell Books |year=2015 |isbn=978-0-7858-3269-0 |location=New York |ref=harv |author-link=Charlotte Montague}}{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Anderson |first=James Arthur |title=Out of the Shadows: A Structuralist Approach to Understanding the Fiction of H. P. Lovecraft |date=2011 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-1-4794-0384-4 |location=Rockville, Maryland}} A close reading of Lovecraft's fiction.\n* {{Cite book |last=Burleson |first=Donald R. |title=Lovecraft: Disturbing the Universe |date=1990 |publisher=The University Press of Kentucky |isbn=0-8131-1728-3 |location=Lexington, Kentucky}} This book is the only volume to date analyzing Lovecraft's literature from a deconstructionist standpoint.\n* {{Cite book |last=Carter |first=Lin |title=Lovecraft: A Look Behind the Cthulhu Mythos |title-link=Lovecraft: A Look Behind the Cthulhu Mythos |date=1972 |publisher=[[Ballantine Books]] |isbn=0-586-04166-4}} This is a survey of Lovecraft's work (along with that of other members of the Lovecraft Circle) with considerable information on his life.\n* {{Cite book |last=de Camp |first=L. Sprague |title=Lovecraft: A Biography |title-link=Lovecraft: A Biography |date=July 12, 1976 |publisher=Doubleday |isbn=0-345-25115-6 |author-link=L. Sprague de Camp}} The first full-length biography, published in 1975, now [[out of print]]. It reflected the state of scholarship at the time but is now completely superseded by S.T. Joshi's biography ''I Am Providence''.\n* {{Cite book |last=Eddy |first=Muriel |title=The Gentleman From Angell Street: Memories of H. P. Lovecraft |last2=Eddy |first2=C. M., Jr. |date=June 2001 |publisher=Fenham Publishing, LLC. |isbn=978-0-9701699-1-4 |editor-last=Dyer |editor-first=Jim |location=Narragansett, Rhode Island |author-link2=C. M. Eddy Jr.}} A collection of personal remembrances and anecdotes from two of Lovecraft's closest friends in Providence. The Eddys were fellow writers, and Mr. Eddy was a frequent contributor to ''Weird Tales.''\n* {{Cite book |last=Hill |first=Gary |title=The Strange Sound of Cthulhu: Music Inspired by the Writings of H. P. Lovecraft |last2=Joshi |first2=S. T. |publisher=Music Street Journal |year=2006 |isbn=978-1-84728-776-2}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=I Am Providence: The Life and Times of H. P. Lovecraft |title-link=H. P. Lovecraft: A Life |date=2010 |publisher=Hippocampus Press |isbn=978-0-9824296-7-9 |location=New York City}} The most complete and authoritative biography of Lovecraft.\n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=The Rise and Fall of the Cthulhu Mythos |date=2008 |publisher=Mythos Books}} The first full-length critical study since Lin Carter's to examine the development of Lovecraft's Mythos and its outworking in the oeuvres of various modern writers.\n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=Emperors of Dreams: Some Notes on Weird Poetry |date=2008 |publisher=P'rea Press |isbn=978-0-9804625-4-8 |location=Sydney |chapter=H. P. Lovecraft: Alone in Space}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Long |first=Frank Belknap |title=Howard Phillips Lovecraft: Dreamer on the Nightside |title-link=Howard Phillips Lovecraft: Dreamer on the Nightside |date=1975 |publisher=Arkham House |isbn=0-87054-068-8 |author-link=Frank Belknap Long}} Presents a personal look at Lovecraft's life, combining reminiscence, biography and literary criticism. Long was a friend and correspondent of Lovecraft, as well as a fellow fantasist who wrote a number of Lovecraft-influenced Cthulhu Mythos stories (including ''The Hounds of Tindalos'').\n* {{Cite book |last=Houellebecq |first=Michel |title=H. P. Lovecraft: Against the World, Against Life |title-link=H. P. Lovecraft: Against the World, Against Life |date=2005 |publisher=Believer Books |isbn=1-932416-18-8 |translator-last=Khazeni |translator-first=Dorna |author-link=Michel Houellebecq}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Ludue\u00f1a |first=Fabi\u00e1n |title=H.P. Lovecraft. The Disjunction in Being |last2=de Acosta |first2=Alejandro |date=2015 |publisher=Schism |isbn=978-1-5058-6600-1 |location=New York City |translator-last=de Acosta |translator-first=Alejandro}} A study of Lovecraft's conceptions about philosophy and literature.\n* {{Cite book |title=An H.P. Lovecraft Encyclopedia |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-313-31578-7 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=New York City |page=117 |editor-last2=Schultz |editor-first2=David E.}} \n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=Lovecraft's Library: A Catalogue |publisher=Hippocampus Press |year=2017 |isbn=978-1-61498-217-3 |edition=Revised Fourth |location=New York City}} A meticulous listing of many of the books in Lovecraft's now scattered library. \n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=Lovecraft at Last |last2=Conover |first2=Willis |last3=Joshi |first3=S. T. |publisher=Cooper Square Press |edition=Revised |author-link=Willis Conover}} An account by Willis Conover of his teenage correspondence with Lovecraft. \n* {{Cite book |last=Joshi |first=S. T. |title=A Subtler Magick: The Writings and Philosophy of H. P. Lovecraft |date=1996 |publisher=Wildside Press |isbn=1-880448-61-0 |edition=Third |location=Gillette, New Jersey}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=The Call of Cthulhu and Other Weird Stories |date=1999 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=0-14-118234-2 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=New York City}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |url=https://archive.org/details/thingondoorstep00love |title=The Thing on the Doorstep and Other Weird Stories |date=2001 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=0-14-218003-3 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=New York City}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=The Dreams in the Witch House and Other Weird Stories |title-link=The Dreams in the Witch House and Other Weird Stories |date=2004 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=0-14-243795-6 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=New York City}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=The Horror in the Museum and Other Revisions |title-link=The Horror in the Museum and Other Revisions |last2=Derleth |first2=August |date=1989 |publisher=Arkham House |isbn=0-87054-040-8 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=Sauk City, Wisconsin |author-link2=August Derleth}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=The Annotated Supernatural Horror in Literature |date=2012 |publisher=Hippocampus Press |isbn=978-1-61498-028-5 |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |edition=Second |location=New York City}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=The Annotated H. P. Lovecraft |date=1997 |publisher=Dell |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=New York City}} \n* {{Cite book |last=Lovecraft |first=H. P. |title=More Annotated H. P. Lovecraft |date=1999 |publisher=Dell |editor-last=Joshi |editor-first=S. T. |location=New York City |editor-last2=Cannon |editor-first2=Peter}}\n* {{Cite book |title=An Epicure in the Terrible |date=1991 |publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson University Press |isbn=0-8386-3415-X |editor-last=Schultz |editor-first=David E. |location=Rutherford, New Jersey |editor-last2=Joshi |editor-first2=S. T.}} An anthology of 13 essays on Lovecraft (excluding Joshi's lengthy introduction) on the centennial of Lovecraft's birth. The essays are arranged into 3 sections; Biographical, Thematic Studies and Comparative and Genre Studies. The authors include S. T. Joshi, Kenneth W. Faig, Jr., Jason C. Eckhardt, Will Murray, Donald R. Burleson, Peter Cannon, Stefan Dziemianowicz, Steven J. Mariconda, David E. Schultz, Robert H. Waugh, Robert M. Price, R. Boerem, Norman R. Gatford and Barton Levi St. Armand.\n* {{Cite book |title=The Intersection of Fantasy and Native America: From H. P. Lovecraft to Leslie Marmon Silko |date=2009 |publisher=Mythopoeic Press |isbn=978-1-887726-12-2 |editor-last=Sturgis |editor-first=Amy H. |author-link=[[Amy H. Sturgis]] |editor-last2=Oberhelman |editor-first2=David D.}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Locke |first=John |title=The Thing's Incredible: The Secret Origins of Weird Tales |date=2018 |publisher=Off-Trail Publications |isbn=978-1-935031-25-3}} A history of the first two years of ''[[Weird Tales]]'' (1923\u201324), the book contains extensive information on Lovecraft's introduction to and growing association with the magazine under the Henneberger/Baird regime. Issues covered include the acceptance of his early submissions, his role in the 1924 reorganization, and his recruitment as editor.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |q=H. P. Lovecraft |s=Howard Phillips Lovecraft |commons=H. P. Lovecraft |n=no |v=no |species=no |author=yes |d=Q169566}}\n{{Library resources box |by=yes |onlinebooks=yes |others= |about=yes |label=H. P. Lovecraft|viaf=66470391 }}\n* [http://www.hplhs.org/ The H. P. Lovecraft Historical Society]\n* {{isfdb name}}\n* {{IMDb name|0522454}}\n* {{Discogs artist|H.P. Lovecraft}}\n\n===Library collections===\n* [https://library.brown.edu/collatoz/info.php?id=73 Howard P. Lovecraft Collection] in the Special Collections at the [[John Hay Library]] ([[Brown University]])\n* [https://digital.library.villanova.edu/Item/vudl:591771 H. P. Lovecraft Collection] in the Distinctive Collections of [https://library.villanova.edu/ Falvey Memorial Library] ([https://www1.villanova.edu/university.html Villanova University])\n* {{LCAuth|n80017007|H. P. Lovecraft|113}}\n\n===Online editions===\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=34724|name=Howard Phillips Lovecraft}}\n* {{FadedPage|id=Lovecraft, Howard Phillips|name=H. P. Lovecraft|author=yes}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Howard Phillips Lovecraft}}\n* [https://www.discogs.com/artist/439356-HP-Lovecraft?limit=50&page=1/ H. P. 